<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif., NY, Texas Are Top Spenders  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- California, New York and Texas are tops when
it comes to taking in and spending money.
</P>
<P>
   According to new figures being released Wednesday by the Census
Bureau, California took in nearly $145 billion in revenue in 1998
while New York was second with $96 billion. The next closest was
Texas with nearly $58 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The states, which are also the top three in population, led the
country in expenditures as well: California with $120 billion, New
York with $87 billion, and Texas with $51 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The data is part of the Census Bureau's 1998 Annual Survey of
Government Finances.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for all 50 state governments totaled $1.1 trillion,
while expenditures totaled $930 billion. Nearly $295 billion, or 32
percent, of the expenditure total went to education, and $208
billion went to public welfare programs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the top five states with the highest expenditures, New York
spent the smallest chunk (20 percent) on education while Texas
spent the most (38 percent of its 51 billion in expenditures).
</P>
<P>
   ''Is this adequate investment? Well, we're in a new century,''
said Isabel Garcia of the National Education Association. ''In
terms of school modernization we have tremendous needs across the
nation and we have to look at the needs from state to state.''
</P>
<P>
   Alaska led the country with both highest revenue per capita
($14,722) and highest expenditures per capita ($9,451). Texas was
last in both categories ($2,926 per capita in revenue and $2,584
per capita in expenditures).
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The top ten states in government revenue and expenditures in
1998:
</P>
<P>
   State Revenue
</P>
<P>
   California $144.9 billion
</P>
<P>
   New York $96.1 billion
</P>
<P>
   Texas $57.8 billion
</P>
<P>
   Florida $51.7 billion
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania $48.5 billion
</P>
<P>
   Ohio $48.1 billion
</P>
<P>
   Illinois $40.4 billion
</P>
<P>
   Michigan $40.0 billion
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey $37.0 billion
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina $33.3 billion
</P>
<P>
   United States $1.1 trillion
</P>
<P>
   State Expenditure
</P>
<P>
   California $120.3 billion
</P>
<P>
   New York $87.3 billion
</P>
<P>
   Texas $51.0 billion
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania $40.8 billion
</P>
<P>
   Florida $39.2 billion
</P>
<P>
   Ohio $39.2 billion
</P>
<P>
   Michigan $37.4 billion
</P>
<P>
   Illinois $35.6 billion
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey $31.7 billion
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts $27.1 billion
</P>
<P>
   United States $930.0 billion
</P>
