<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo market's main index fell on profit-taking
Wednesday morning. The dollar was higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 126.37 points,
or 0.69 percent, to 18,145.96 at the end of the morning session. On
Tuesday, the average closed down 207.82 points, or 1.12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 105.72 yen in late morning, up 0.36 yen from
late Tuesday in Tokyo, but below its late New York level of 105.81
yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, prices started higher led by major
information technology blue chips after the Nasdaq composite index
rose 228.75 to 3,711.23 at Tuesday's finish.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nikkei index moved into negative territory as investors
sold in some of the 30 stocks that were added to the index Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Those new issues, which include telecommunications companies,
replaced 30 mostly old-line industrial stocks to better reflect
changes in Japan's economy. Most of the new issues had been bid up
in anticipation of the move.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 4.26 points, or 0.26 percent, to 1,669.54. The
TOPIX closed up 4.26 points, or 0.27 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Also in New York on Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average
rose 218.72 points to close at 11,124.82.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar basically followed its trend in
New York, where the greenback strengthened amid higher U.S. stocks
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the dollar's relative strength against the euro
also led to its firmness against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has come under pressure in recent weeks amid questions
over how European authorities will defend the currency.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was traded at 97.30 yen, down from 98.65 yen late
Tuesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.7350 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.7400 percent. Its
price fell 0.82 point to 100.55.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
