<HEADLINE> Down in the count: 100,000 or bust for Albany  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HILL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- This city will not go down for the count
without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   There are hopes that census workers canvassing door-to-door will
tally enough residents to help keep the city above the 100,000
population mark -- a threshold with financial as well as
psychological significance.
</P>
<P>
   Albany's population is 100,031 based on the 1990 count by the
U.S. Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, the agency estimates that the state capital's
population dropped to 94,305 by 1998. While city officials are
skeptical about the estimated loss of almost 6,000 souls, they have
taken steps to preserve their six-digit population count in the
current census.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're concerned, of course, about that 100,000 mark,'' said
Denise Kelley, Albany's registrar of vital statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The concern stems from more than just bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   There have been estimates that more than $1 million in federal
funding could be at stake over Albany's census count. And Kelley
said a dip below 100,000 could cost Albany the attention of private
marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ''They say,'OK, let's target cities over 100,000' ... It's a
benchmark that you don't want to be knocked out of the running
for,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   For months, city officials have been working to make sure
residents return mailed census forms. Exhortations to fill out the
forms came from church pulpits and at a special dinner for homeless
people. City schools held a census poster contest.
</P>
<P>
   But only 56 percent of Albany residents mailed in their census
forms. That's below the statewide rate of return of 61 percent,
although it is on par with the return rate for other upstate
cities.
</P>
<P>
   With census workers preparing to call on non-responding
households around the nation this week, Albany sees one last
opportunity to promote census compliance. A public service
announcement is being prepared by the city asking residents to
cooperate with census takers who knock on their doors.
</P>
<P>
   The census workers could be in the field through July, although
population tallies won't be known until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Cities across upstate New York lost population from 1990 through
1998, according to census figures. Buffalo lost an estimated 27,458
people, or 8.4 of its population. Syracuse saw a 7.1 percent drop,
and Rochester declined by 5.8 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
