<HEADLINE> Environmental groups ask New York to assess mercury risks  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state should be warning pregnant women
and nursing mothers not to eat seafood, since the federal
government is not properly protecting them from mercury-tainted
fish, environmental groups say.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pregnant women, nursing mothers and people who consume high
levels of fish are not being adequately warned,'' said Laura
Haight, a spokeswoman for the New York Public Interest Research
Group.
</P>
<P>
   NYPIRG joined with the Sierra Club and Environmental Advocates
in calling for the warnings, which coincided with the release of a
new report criticizing the Food and Drug Administration for no
longer testing mercury levels in tuna, swordfish and shark.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released Tuesday by the Vermont-based Mercury Policy
Project, the California Communities Against Toxics, the Sierra Club
and others says what little data exists shows all three of those
heavily consumer species often contain unsafe levels of mercury.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a potential health threat out there the public has
not been warned about,'' said John Stouffer, legislative director
of the Sierra Club's Atlantic chapter. ''The state Health
Department should warn pregnant women, women planning to become
pregnant and nursing mothers to restrict their consumption of
swordfish, shark and tuna.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercury is a metallic chemical element that also is a byproduct
of coal-fired power plants and trash incinerators. The New York
groups say about 33 percent of New York's mercury output was
generated by coal-burning plants that produced 98,000 pounds of the
element last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury can cause neurological damage if it is ingested. Fetuses
and young children are particularly vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont, New Jersey, Minnesota and Michigan have warnings
advising pregnant women and nursing mothers to limit consumption of
the potentially-dangerous seafood.
</P>
<P>
   Claire Pospisil, a spokeswoman for the Health Department, said
her agency would not issue those warnings, though it does warn
anglers against eating fish from some lakes and rivers because of
possible mercury contamination.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Health Department last year extended a warning
against eating more than one meal per month of smallmouth bass from
New York City's Ashokan Reservoir due to elevated levels of mercury
found in fish samples. Similar warnings had earlier been posted by
the Health Department for smallmouth bass taken from the Rondout
and Neversink reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Conservation also said it
would not be appropriate for that agency to issue warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really a federal issue,'' said spokeswoman Jennifer Post.
''The FDA sets (acceptable pollutant) levels and is responsible for
monitoring them. The DEC works with the Health Department to make
sure the fish people eat are safe based on federal standards.''
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials said they can prove the food supply is safe based
on historical data. Since mercury levels have not changed over the
past few years, there is no reason to test fish, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.mercurypolicy.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.fda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 0025 </TRAILER>
