<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State tries using collection agency for court-imposed fines  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state is going to try using a private
collection agency on a trial basis to see if it has better success
than the courts at making people pay fines and surcharges imposed
by judges.
</P>
<P>
   In a strategy aimed ultimately at boosting fees paid to lawyers
who represent indigent people in New York, the state Office of
Court Administration said Tuesday that Outsourcing Solutions Inc.
has been retained to collect money due the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The company's bill collectors at first will seek some of the
480,000 delinquent judgments outstanding in six courts: Rochester
City Court, Queens Supreme Court, Suffolk District Court, Suffolk
County Court, Nassau District Court and New York City Criminal
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Court administrators believe the aggressive collection methods
of professionals in the field may generate tens of millions of
dollars in unpaid fines and surcharges the state imposes on various
offenses. But they had no official estimate Tuesday of how much
they expect Outsourcing Solutions to collect.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has been the tradition that everybody in the criminal
justice system throws up our hands and says, 'We're not a
collection agency,''' Jonathan Lippman, the state's chief
administrative judge, said Tuesday. ''The courts say, 'We're not a
collection agency.' The executive branch, the DAs, they all say,
'We're not a collection agency.'''
</P>
<P>
   In consequence, Lippman said, huge sums due state and county
governments through court-imposed fines and surcharges are not
being collected by anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Lippman predicted it would take about six months for Outsourcing
Solutions to show what state Chief Judge Judith Kaye and other
administrators believe to be the case, that serious collection
efforts will yield significant funds.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Kaye proposed using revenues raised through hiring a
private collection agency to improve fees for so-called assigned
counsels. Those court-appointed lawyers are paid $40 an hour for
in-court work and $25 for out-of-court work on behalf of indigent
clients -- a pay schedule which administrators say has caused the
pool of lawyers willing to volunteer for such work to dry up.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye proposed increasing the assigned counsel fees to $75 an
hour for felony and Family Court cases and to $60 an hour for
non-felony cases. But Gov. George Pataki has been hostile to that
proposal, and the state Legislature refused to dedicate the $80
million or so it is estimated would be needed to nearly double
assigned counsel fees.
</P>
<P>
   Lippman said court administrators expect their new program to
show that uncollected fines and surcharges are a viable way of
paying for increased assigned-counsel fees.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think there is no better revenue stream and no better
symmetry than to use money collected from offenders to pay for
representation for the indigent,'' Lippman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Outsourcing Solutions contract calls for the company to
receive 14.9 percent of what it collects in this state fiscal year
up to a maximum of $250,000, according to Office of Court
Administration spokesman David Bookstaver.
</P>
<P>
   Lippman said he does not expect New Yorkers to criticize his
office for bringing on board a private collection agency with its
presumably aggressive techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would do a disservice to the public and would not be
accountable to the wide, broad public by not going after these
funds,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 0025 </TRAILER>
