<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multimillion dollar settlement to enable boy to move closer tomother  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LYONS, N.Y. (AP) -- Ten years after a 9-year-old boy was hit by a
truck when leaving his school via a street that had no crosswalk,
sidewalk or traffic light, his mother reached a settlement that
could bring up to $37 million for his care.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Ernest will receive an initial payment of $348,250 under the
settlement filed earlier this month in state Supreme Court. Wayne
County will have to pay $660,000, in addition to purchasing an
annuity and paying $6,430 per month. Each year, that amount will
increase by 3 percent. The Red Creek school district must pay $1.4
million and make monthly payments of $12,834 for the rest of
Christopher Knopp's life. Each year, those monthly payments will
also increase by 3 percent. Truck driver Gordon Carvey will have to
pay $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Knopp's mother is ''very pleased that Christopher's care is
going to be provided for the rest of his life and he is going to be
protected,'' her lawyer, Richard DeValk, said in the Geneva Finger
Lakes Times' Tuesday editions. ''The best that would have happened
if we didn't receive the settlement is he would have gotten
released into a group home where he would not have supervision, and
would have been more likely to injure himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Knopp was hit April 2, 1990, when he dodged behind a bus and
tried to cross the road. Carvey said his view was obstructed by a
bus.
</P>
<P>
   Today Knopp has permanent brain injuries, double vision, a
blood-filled tumor on his leg that hasn't healed since the
accident, and suffers tremors that prevent him from holding a
drink.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest said her son remains at the developmental level of a
second-grader and has behavioral problems related to his brain
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest and DeValk maintained that school district officials were
at fault because all students were dismissed with buses that day. A
school policy at the time called for students who walked home to be
dismissed only after buses had left school grounds. The mother also
said Wayne County was negligent for failing to build a sidewalk or
crosswalk for the street in front of the school.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, school officials had urged county and town officials to
extend a sidewalk from the village of Red Creek along the highway
to the school, and to put a crosswalk that would link the sidewalk
to the school.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after Knopp was struck, a sidewalk was constructed
along that section of road.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest's case was twice dismissed, first in the Wayne County
Supreme Court and then in the Fourth Division Appellate Court in
Rochester. But last summer, the state Court of Appeals overturned
those rulings, stating Ernest could go forward with a jury trial
against the school, the county and the truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement will cover Knopp's medical care and enable him to
move out of a rehabilitation center in Greenfield, N.H., and into a
private home near his mother in Cato, in Cayuga County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 0026 </TRAILER>
