<HEADLINE> Clinton encourages college students involvement in politics  </HEADLINE>
o0140nyc--
r n PM-NY--NYSenate-Clinton Bjt   04-26 0417
PM-NY--NY Senate-Clinton, Bjt,417   
Clinton encourages college students involvement in politics   
With PM-NY--NY Senate
AP Photo   
By MARC HUMBERT   
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALFRED, N.Y. (AP) -- As a graduating college student in 1969,
Hillary Rodham Clinton made a well-known commencement speech
decrying the government establishment.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the first lady and U.S. Senate candidate promoted
public life and acknowledged to a college audience that her
generation's cynicism may have hurt political leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know many people have been turned off by politics in the
last several years. In fact, I think it started in the 1960s,''
Clinton said. ''People became very cynical and withdrawn and that
leaves the field to people you may not agree with, to people who
have a very different agenda and ideology. I don't think it is in
any of our interests to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In front of a packed 500-seat auditorium at the New York State
College of Ceramics at Alfred University, Clinton told students
that they should get involved in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   ''This campaign has much more to do with your futures than with
mine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate candidate made her appeal as she began a three-day
foray into traditionally conservative upstate New York, a key
battleground in her Senate race against New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly in her 45-minute speech, the first lady praised the
policies of her husband and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new Democrat philosophy that the president and the vice
president championed and really symbolized clearly points a
direction for our state and our country to head in,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady drew cheers and applause when she used one of her
favorite lines on the students: ''If we give signing bonuses to
athletes, we ought to give signing bonuses to teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, while not criticizing Giuliani by name, did attack
Republicans in general for pushing school vouchers that would allow
parents public funds to send their children to private or parochial
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some places that call themselves churches that set
up schools in garages that I would not want my tax dollars
supporting,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous anti-Clinton signs, including one that read, ''Stand by
your man -- in Arkansas,'' were posted along the road leading into
Alfred.
</P>
<P>
   Placards at the university were more friendly. One suggested,
''Hillary Rocks'' while another said: ''Men want Hillary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 0030 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huntsman To Announce $125M Gift  </HEADLINE>
By HANNAH WOLFSON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Chemical magnate Jon Huntsman, who has
spent $151 million of his own money to fund a cancer center at the
University of Utah, plans to donate another $125 million to the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   An announcement is planned today. The bulk of the money, $100
million, will pay for construction of a six-story hospital to treat
patients along with the Huntsman Cancer Institute. The other $25
million will go to an outreach program with Utah's largest health
care provider, Intermountain Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel I'm a very lucky man because this is such a privilege
to make a donation of this kind,'' Huntsman, 62, told The
Associated Press on Tuesday. ''Years ago and through my life this
was something I never felt would be possible or achievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Huntsman, who built and owns Huntsman Chemical Corp., the
world's largest privately owned chemical company, has always
claimed he made his fortune just to give it away. Earlier this
month, he sold off one of his subsidiaries, Huntsman Packaging
Corp., to Chase Capital Partners in a transaction valued at $1.065
billion, saying the sale would support his philanthropic ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Before the sale, Forbes magazine estimated his personal wealth
at $3.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The billionaire's beneficence began in earnest in 1995 with a
$90 million pledge to start a ''cancer campus'' at the university
his wife and children attended.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually donated another $61 million to help finish off the
institute, which treats some patients but has no overnight care.
The money also helped lure 300 researchers from the top
laboratories in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Huntsman's second gift comes seven months after the institute
opened.
</P>
<P>
   ''This isn't the sort of thing that happens every day up here,''
said university spokesman Fred Esplin. ''This is a very big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The $100 million of the bequest that goes to the university
would rank 15th on the Chronicle of Higher Education's list of
private grants to universities, tied with more than a dozen similar
donations.
</P>
<P>
   But if Huntsman's cumulative $250-million gift to the school was
considered en masse, it would land in fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the money will be used to build the 55-bed Clinical
Research Hospital next door to the research institute, set to open
late 2002 or early 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Huntsman, who has fought off prostate and mouth cancer and lost
his mother, father and stepfather to the disease, says his
high-tech hospital will bear a personal touch, with comfortable
interiors and sweeping mountain views.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I'd like to do is ensure that the cancer patients don't
worry about cancer while they're there,'' Huntsman said.
''Everything we do is centered around hope.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to spread the hope around, Huntsman has set aside
$25 million to establish a cancer partnership with Intermountain
Health Care, which provides hospital care for about 60 percent of
the cancer patients in Utah, Idaho and Wyoming. The money will be
used to expand facilities at IHC hospitals and share new
information from the Huntsman Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ''The object's to get (promising research) out as fast as we
can, not only to other hospitals in Utah and the Intermountain
region but to other hospitals around the country and the world,''
Huntsman said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Huntsman is content with weekly visits to patients in
his institute's chemotherapy center.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great honor to go there and tell them they're going to
be fine and they look beautiful and handsome,'' Huntsman said.
''I've been in those stations before and it's nice to have a
friendly face -- especially someone whose name's on the building.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
