<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tigers 4, Angels 2  </HEADLINE>
By KEN PETERS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Bobby Higginson's RBI single with two
outs in the eighth inning Tuesday night lifted Detroit to a 4-2
victory over the Anaheim Angels, ending the Tigers' eight-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Higginson singled off Kent Bottenfield (2-4) to score Luis
Polonia from second, breaking a 2-2 tie. Polonia, leading off the
inning, reached base on a throwing error by shortstop Benji Gil.
</P>
<P>
   Polonia moved to second on Brad Asmus' groundout, and Juan
Encarnacion walked. Bottenfield got Juan Gonzalez on a flyout, but
Higginson followed with his sharp single to center that chased the
Angels' starter.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers scored again in the ninth when Deivi Cruz doubled and
scored on Polonia's single to short and ensuing wild throw by Gil.
That made the final two Detroit runs unearned.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Poole (1-0) pitched two-thirds of an inning for the win
after Hideo Nomo limited the Angels to two runs in 6 1-3 innings.
Todd Jones pitched the ninth for his fourth save.
</P>
<P>
   Damion Easley, who rejoined the Tigers off the disabled list
earlier in the day, hit his first homer of the season, a solo shot
in the fifth, to tie it at 2.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Kennedy's two-run homer, his second, accounted for all the
Angels' scoring in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Easley was placed on the 15-day disabled list, retroactive to
April 10, with a strained muscle in his rib cage. It was discovered
last weekend that he also had a hairline fracture in his right
wrist, the result of being hit by a pitch on April 5 at Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   He made a rehabilitation appearance at Toledo and hit a two-run
homer on Monday night, then left to join the Tigers in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim went up 2-1 on Kennedy's homer off Nomo after Darin
Erstad singled. Encarnacion's RBI single gave Detroit a 1-0 lead in
the first.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo, who escaped a bases-loaded jam later in the third by
striking out Troy Glaus, gave up six hits in 6 1-3 innings. He
struck out five and walked four.
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield gave up three runs on eight hits in 7 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
NOTES: Anaheim right-hander Tim Belcher, coming back from
offseason arm surgery, gave up one run on five hits in five innings
Tuesday night in a rehab assignment with Triple-A Edmonton. Belcher
walked one, struck out one and threw 60 pitches, 43 of them
strikes. ... First-year manager Mike Scioscia said he would have
the Angels running this season, and they have -- stealing (21) bases
in 22 games. Last year, they stole a total of 71 bases, 25th in the
majors, and did not get their 22nd steal until their 59th game. ...
Doctors told Easley that playing will not aggravate his wrist
injury. ... To make room for Easley on the roster, the Tigers
outrighted outfielder Karim Garcia to Triple-A Toledo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 0101 </TRAILER>
