<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Giuliani trade charges  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton said Rudolph Giuliani
should apologize for calling federal agents in the Elian Gonzalez
raid storm troopers.
</P>
<P>
   But the New York City mayor stood by his remarks. His camp
instead attacked the first lady's fund raising, saying Democrats
were trying to hide soft-money donors to her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, a new Zogby International poll of voters in
GOP-leaning upstate New York showed the mayor leading the first
lady by 14 percent. The upstate poll showed Giuliani with 52
percent and Clinton with 38 percent. The poll has a margin of error
of plus or minus 3.2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who just signed a civility pledge promising a clean
U.S. Senate campaign, said she agreed with the Federal Law
Enforcement Officers Association, which is demanding an apology
from Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that the mayor's inflammatory and divisive rhetoric is
part of a pattern that he has engaged in for quite some time,'' the
first lady said during a campaign stop Tuesday in Westchester
County.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Saturday that the federal government had
''trampled the wishes of (Elian's) mother this morning with guns
and with storm troopers.''
</P>
<P>
   He had this to say Tuesday: ''You do not use loaded automatic
weapons to remove 6-year-old children. Why the attorney general
made the choice to have them dress in battle fatigues and with
automatic weapons that were loaded is a misjudgment of very, very
large proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's campaign targeted Clinton's fund raising, which has
been a frequent line of attack. This time the campaign was critical
of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee's decision not to
immediately disclose soft-money donations to New York Senate 2000,
a committee set up to support Clinton's Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is not subject to $2,000 campaign donation limits for
individuals. It can be used for issue ads and party-building
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've been caught in another of the campaign scams they
imported from Arkansas and perfected in Washington,'' Giuliani
spokeswoman Kim Serafin said of the president and first lady.
</P>
<P>
   DSCC officials said they made an accounting decision not to
detail soft-money donations every month when they file their
reports because the accounting involved was too onerous.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they plan to file those reports when the money is
transferred from a joint fund-raising account set up for the
candidate. New York Senate 2000 raised about $500,000 in soft money
in the first quarter of this year, officials said Tuesday. That is
on top of the roughly $700,000 in soft money raised last year. A
new account set up by Republicans for Giuliani raise nearly
$500,000 in just one month.
</P>
<P>
   DSCC political director Jim Jordan said ''the Clinton campaign
has no control over or knowledge of the administrative
technicalities'' of the account. He asserted the DSCC was following
federal election law.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Interfaith Alliance announced that the first lady
had signed its pledge to run a clean campaign. By signing the
group's Framework of Civility for Political Candidates, candidates
promise to avoid personal attacks, take responsibility for the
conduct of advisers and allies and make documentation available for
factual allegations made about opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is also calling on Giuliani to sign the pledge. He
has not done so.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates Al Gore and George W. Bush signed the
pledge in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 0106 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eighth driver murdered; another arrested for assaulting passenger  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hours after the eighth livery cab driver this
year was murdered on the job, another cabbie was charged with
assaulting a passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Police said George Luciano seriously injured his passenger with
a metal bar after the two argued on a Bronx street corner. Luciano
apparently thought he was about to be robbed. Luciano, 45, has been
charged with assault.
</P>
<P>
   Luciano was on his way to pick up a dispatched fare when Mario
King jumped into his cab at a Bronx intersection. Luciano told him
to get out and the argument ensued, police said.
</P>
<P>
   As King exited the car, so did Luciano -- allegedly with a metal
bar. Luciano then allegedly hit King and drove off. His cab company
notified police about what happened, and Luciano was arrested. King
was listed in serious but stable condition at Jacobi Hospital hours
after the alleged attack.
</P>
<P>
   Luciano had likely heard of Monday night's shooting death of
livery cab driver Jose Olivares. The 35-year-old cabbie was the
eighth driver killed on the job this year. The Dominican Republic
native was shot once in the head shortly after 10 p.m. during a
botched robbery attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four passengers in the cab were injured when the car
crashed into an apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers -- two men and two teen-agers -- were charged with
attempted robbery, murder and criminal possession of a weapon,
police said. They were identified as John Rivera, 19; Ramon Anaya,
18; Norberto Hernandez, 16; and Jasmine Valentine, 16.
</P>
<P>
   News of Olivares' death spread quickly, and may have caused some
panic, as in Luciano's case.
</P>
<P>
   ''He thought he was going to be robbed,'' said a dispatcher
named Segfredo at Watson Car Service in the Bronx, where Luciano
has worked for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates concerned for livery drivers' safety say many cabbies
are driving scared these days. Eight drivers have been killed so
far this year, compared with 11 for all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like a nightmare,'' said Fernando Mateo, president of
the New York State Federation of Taxi Drivers. ''You have not
finished mourning one when you are suddenly arranging for another
wake and funeral procession. When will these killings stop?''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo said Olivares had spoken out about the dangers facing
drivers on the same night he was killed. ''If I get robbed or I get
killed, believe me, I'm going to take them with me,''' Mateo quoted
Olivares as having said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the eight slain cabbies had installed bulletproof
partitions in their cars, police said. Olivares had intended to
have a partition installed but had not been able to because the
shops that do that work were swamped with orders, said Eddie
Almonte, manager of Excellent Car Services, where Olivares had
worked for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by the recent killings, the Taxi and Limousine
Commission voted unanimously last week to require all drivers to
install either bulletproof partitions or digital security cameras
in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the TLC made it mandatory for yellow cabs and livery
cars owned by more than one driver to have the partitions. But cars
owned and operated by individual drivers -- 90 percent of all livery
cars -- could have either partitions or tiny surveillance cameras
installed behind the rearview mirror. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
recently pledged $5 million toward a grant program to help pay for
the security devices.
</P>
<P>
   The recent increase in driver murders and the new requirement
has apparently overwhelmed shops that install partitions, which are
cheaper to install than cameras. Partitions cost between $250 to
$350, and cameras start at $600, the TLC has said.
</P>
<P>
   ''My understanding is that there are waiting lists,'' said TLC
spokesman Allan Fromberg. ''They (the shops) are doing the best
they can, they are operating to capacity. Many hundreds of
partitions have been put in already.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Taxi and Limousine Commission:
http://www.ci.nyc.ny.us/html/tlc.
</P>
</TEXT>
