<HEADLINE> Poor Outlook for Midwestern Farmers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   STILLWATER, Minn. (AP) -- Midwestern farmers are heading into
another growing season with an unpleasant outlook in terms of
commodity prices, government aid and weather.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for major crops grown in the region are likely to be
below most farmers' production costs; dairy prices have sunk with
crop prices, matching 25 year lows; and large areas of the country
are under threat of drought.
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty also hovers about whether the government will come
to the rescue after bailing farmers out of financial problems for
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is in the process of passing a $7 billion farm aid
package for the start of this growing season, and more could be on
the way if drought and weather damage to crops becomes measurable
later, congressional leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   Dairyman George Rydeen, who farms near Stillwater, said he hopes
Asia's improving economy will help farmers through increased
exports.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even our milk prices are tied to grains,'' he said. ''Cheap
feed leads to more milk and lower milk prices. We've had two pretty
good years in dairying, so we knew what would happen. More cows,
and milk production is up.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather provides another way for getting grain supplies back in
balance with demand, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The long-range weather maps I look at show widespread
drought,'' Rydeen said. ''We're on the edge of it, so we have to
figure we will get a crop.''
</P>
<P>
   Drought could bring higher prices for farmers before the year is
out, said Helen Pound, an analyst and trader with Goldenberg
Hehmeyer &AMP; Co. in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   She said, however, that farmers and grain companies have huge
supplies of grain to work with if this year's crop is reduced by
poor growing conditions. Port elevators at Duluth, Minn., and
Superior, Wis., have 18 million bushels of wheat on hand. Farms and
country elevators are loaded with corn and soybeans for export.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of grain in storage that would find some happy
buyers if drought happens,'' Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   BLACKFOOT, Idaho (AP) -- U.S. and Canadian potato growers are
creating an alliance to help them survive an unsettled agriculture
market and get increased prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're at a point in time where we need to know what each other
is doing, and we need to tell each other what we're doing, all the
way to what's happening at the bank,'' said Duane Maatz, president
of the Red River Valley Potato Growers Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Potato Marketing Association of North America, Potato
Growers of Idaho, bargaining cooperatives, and state and provincial
grower associations agreed to create a communications network.
</P>
<P>
   They also agreed to have each growing region determine its
production costs and the potential impact that increasing oil
prices will have on production expenses. They plan to meet and
evaluate the information, which will be used when negotiating 2001
potato-processing contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations involved in the agreement are the Potato
Growers of Alberta, the Potato Growers of Washington, the Malheur
Potato Bargaining Association and the Wisconsin Potato and
Vegetable Growers.
</P>
</TEXT>
