<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elian's New Home Peaceful, Secluded  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER THORNE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEENSTOWN, Md. (AP) -- For nearly five months, the sounds
outside Elian Gonzalez's bedroom in Miami included the buzz from
hordes of reporters and the bullhorn-dominated chants of
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   He is now at the secluded Wye River conference center, where
geese honk on the grounds of the 1,100-acre estate that was the
home of one of the state's first governors, William Paca.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, along with his father, stepmother and baby half-brother,
on Tuesday were moved to a two-story, white farmhouse on the
center's grounds. They are awaiting court action on whether the
6-year-old boy should be granted an asylum hearing, State
Department spokesman James P. Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Wye River was chosen because ''it's good for a youngster who can
use the grounds. And it's large enough so that potentially the two
families could both be there but not be on top of each other,''
said a senior Justice Department official, requesting anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The family had been staying at Andrews Air Force Base since
Saturday, when Elian was forcibly removed from the home of his
Miami relatives. The relatives have been turned away each time
they've sought to see Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The conference center, 70 miles east of Washington, is perhaps
best known as the site of the Middle East peace negotiations in
1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The grounds are the site of Houghton House. The 25-room Georgian
mansion is filled with colonial antiques and has an 18th
century-style garden with a swimming pool. Legend has it that
Paca's wife haunts the mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The complex also has two other executive retreats, each with its
own accommodations and recreational facilities. The 26-room River
House has an impressive view of the Wye River, and the Wye Woods
campus has lodges connected by boardwalks.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye complex is run by the Aspen Institute, a nonprofit
organization dedicated to leadership development and critical
issues facing society. It also has facilities in Aspen, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Its activities include seminars in which leaders from various
backgrounds read and discuss great works of literature to gain a
framework for making decisions, said Janet Froetscher, senior vice
president for seminars and communications.
</P>
<P>
   One neighbor said he didn't think Elian's visit would cause
nearly the commotion the 1998 peace talks caused, when Secret
Service agents shut down the road leading to the estate.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the only time we had security that high, when the
president was here,'' said Kevin Compton, operations manager at
Pintail Point Farm, which runs hunting, boating and recreational
outings. ''There's constantly stuff going on down there that
requires security, but we don't ever feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: AP Writer Michael J. Sniffen contributed to this
report from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.aspeninstitute.org
</P>
