<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Dialysis Fiber Can Break Down  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE ZIEGLER DIZON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A fiber used in dialysis machines across the
country can break down with age, causing such severe reactions in
kidney patients as vision and hearing loss, according to a study
published today.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery came after seven patients at an Alabama hospital
had bad reactions within 24 hours of undergoing dialysis in 1996,
the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said. Their
symptoms ranged from near blindness and deafness to intense
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found that the breakdown of old fiber making up the
membranes of the patients' dialyzers -- which filter blood before it
is returned to the patient -- probably caused the reactions by
introducing chemical byproducts of the fiber into their blood.
</P>
<P>
   All of the patients had been treated the same day using
dialyzers that were more than 11 years old. Five died within 13
months, but researchers said their deaths could not be definitively
linked to the dialyzers.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC and the Food and Drug Administration's findings were
reported in today's Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Matthew Kuehnert, a CDC epidemiologist and co-author of the
study, said it is extremely rare that dialyzers that old are used.
Even so, he said the study is of note for all hospitals that
perform dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   ''It certainly raises a question that it likely does apply to
all dialyzers that use this type of material that can degrade,''
Kuehnert said.
</P>
<P>
   About 250,000 patients in the United States are undergoing
dialysis treatment. The CDC said 43 percent of dialysis centers use
equipment that includes cellulose acetate, the fiber used in the
Alabama cases.
</P>
<P>
   The material is generally safe, said Joseph Hutter, an FDA
chemical engineer and lead author of the study. But it can degrade
after several years, allowing chemicals from the fiber to mix with
the blood being pumped into a patient's body through the artificial
kidney.
</P>
<P>
   Two other patients who went through the Alabama hospital's
dialysis unit the day of the outbreak were treated with dialyzers
that were less than a year old and did not have adverse reactions.
</P>
<P>
   After the Alabama cases, the FDA and the CDC sent letters to all
U.S. dialysis centers suggesting the centers should check with the
manufacturer before using old dialyzers.
</P>
<P>
   All new dialyzers must now display a date of manufacture, and
the FDA is working with manufacturers to develop shelf-life
criteria for the equipment, Hutter said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Journal of the American Medical Association:
http://jama.ama-assn.org
</P>
<P>
   American Association of Kidney Patients: http://www.aakp.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 0124 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Looks at Women's Diet Patterns  </HEADLINE>
By TAMMY WEBBER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Women who eat a wide variety of healthy foods may
significantly lower their risk of dying from such things as cancer,
heart disease and stroke, researchers suggested today.
</P>
<P>
   The findings might sound familiar, but this is the first time
the health effects of overall eating patterns have been studied,
according to the report in today's Journal of the American Medical
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that a diet that includes plenty of
fruits, vegetables, whole grains and low-fat meat and dairy
products reduces a woman's chances of dying -- up to 30 percent for
women who ate the healthiest diets compared with those with the
most unhealthy eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   Most previous studies have looked at the health effects of
specific nutrients, foods or dietary habits -- such as eating
low-fat foods -- but not at overall eating patterns, said Dr. Arthur
Schatzkin, chief of the National Cancer Institute's nutritional
epidemiology branch and one of the study's authors.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's another way of following the standard advice, but may be
a strategy that makes it easier for people to adopt dietary
guidelines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study was based on questionnaires completed between 1987 and
1989 by more than 42,000 women.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers then looked at 23 recommended foods and counted how
many times the women reported eating those foods at least once a
week, giving each woman a score based on the responses. The scores
were compared with death rates among those women 5{ to six years
after the survey was completed.
</P>
<P>
   The study found women's risk of dying decreased as the scores
went up. Those who ate the highest amount of recommended foods were
30 percent less likely to die than those who ate the lowest.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were trying to come up with a fairly simple and practical
approach to looking at overall diet in terms of diversity of food
and recommended food,'' Schatzkin said. ''It is nice that a simple
approach to changing the way you eat improves health and increases
longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   The study does not prove a healthy diet alone accounted for the
results, because people who eat the healthiest food are probably
also more likely to do other healthy things such as exercising and
avoiding smoking, said Schatzkin and Madelyn Fernstrom, an expert
in nutrition and obesity treatment who heads the weight management
center at the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   But they said the results suggest a simpler approach to
achieving good health.
</P>
<P>
   Fernstrom, who was not involved in the study, said people often
are too caught up in selecting foods for specific nutrients or fat
levels instead of simply eating a wide variety of healthy foods.
</P>
<P>
   Concentrating on simply eating a variety of healthy food ''takes
the magic bullet approach of particular foods away.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Food is not medicine,'' she said. ''The whole diet counts.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Journal of the American Medical Association:
http://jama.ama-assn.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
