<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury deliberates after prosecutor calls McDermott 'stud stockpicker'  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A prosecutor suggested that a Wall Street
executive who earned $4 million annually was doing the ''macho
thing'' when he fed secrets about bank stocks to an X-rated movie
actress.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Alex Young Oh said James McDermott Jr.
was trying to impress Kathryn Gannon with his stock picking prowess
when he tipped the actress about six companies involved in deals
that would catapult the value of their stock.
</P>
<P>
   During closing arguments, Oh told jurors it was absurd to think
McDermott, the former chief executive officer at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP;
Woods, gave Gannon $150,000 with which to buy stocks and did not
tell her what to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you think that's how it really happened?'' Oh asked. ''Come
on. She was the actress, dancer and model. He was the stud stock
picker.''
</P>
<P>
   A jury in U.S. District Court in Manhattan began deliberations
in the case Tuesday but retired after two hours without reaching a
verdict. Deliberations were to continue this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Oh rejected arguments by defense lawyers that McDermott never
gave Gannon inside information regarding banks about to announce
mergers because his $4 million annual salary meant he could just
give her cash.
</P>
<P>
   ''The evidence has shown that giving cash to Gannon was not
enough,'' Oh said. ''There was something more to this scheme than
just the money. Maybe McDermott was trying to impress her. This is
a way for him to show her what he did. Maybe it was a macho
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor was not permitted by Judge Kimba Wood to tell
jurors that Gannon danced naked or performed under the name Marylin
Star in movies such as ''Pumped,'' ''Shades of Blonde,'' ''Sins of
the Flesh'' and ''S.M.U.T. 4.''
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, lawyer Denis McInerney had called his client a
''rocket scientist on bank stocks'' who recommended winning stocks
to Gannon long before they were put on lists requiring nothing be
said about them until mergers were announced.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott, 48, of Briarcliff Manor, is charged with conspiracy
and securities fraud in the case along with co-defendant Anthony
Pomponio, 45, of North Caldwell, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Pomponio allegedly traded illegally after he was told the inside
information by Gannon, with whom he also was having an affair.
Gannon, who used to live in Miami, is a fugitive believed to be in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the prosecutor, told jurors that McDermott recommended
stocks to ''his lover, Gannon,'' who in turn recommended the stock
to ''her other lover, Pomponio.'' Gannon, 30, and Pomponio
allegedly made $170,000 in illegal profits.
</P>
<P>
   Oh said the argument that McDermott ''was too rich or made too
much money to commit this crime is silly.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We already know he was willing to risk his marriage and his
job for this affair with Kathryn Gannon,'' Oh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
