<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NU's first-quarter profits soar with restart of Millstone 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BERLIN, Conn. (AP) -- The restart of Millstone 2 nuclear power
plant helped Northeast Utilities first-quarter net earnings soar to
$74.6 million, a 304 percent increase from $18.4 million in the
same period last year, the company reported.
</P>
<P>
   ''The biggest difference is that Millstone 2 ran. It was not
running at all in the first quarter in 1999,'' NU spokesman Jeffrey
Kotkin said Tuesday. ''There was a huge cost that we were incurring
while our nuclear plants were off-line.''
</P>
<P>
   NU stock was up 55 cents per share, compared to 14 cents a share
in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   For the 12 months ending March 31, 2000, NU earned $90.4
million, or 68 cents a share, compared with a loss of $110.4
million, or 84 cents a share, for the 12 months ending March 31,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   All three Millstone reactors at the Waterford complex were shut
down in 1996 due to safety concerns. In the past year, Millstone 2
and 3 gained federal approval to restart. Millstone 1, the oldest
of the three, is being decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
   Nonfuel operation and maintenance costs at Millstone fell to
$256 million in the first three months of 2000, compared with $281
million during the same period of 1999, said Michael G. Morris,
NU's Chairman, president and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said NU also benefited from continued economic expansion
in the region. Despite a mild winter, first-quarter retail sales
were up 3.3 percent
</P>
<P>
   The first-quarter results also reflect NU's March 1 merger with
Yankee Energy System, Inc. and the issuance of approximately 11.1
million NU shares to former Yankee shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   NU's total revenues rose by 32.5 percent to $1.38 billion,
compared with $1.04 billion in the first quarter of 1999. The
growth was due primarily to rapid expansion of Select Energy Inc.,
NU's energy marketing subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin-based Northeast Utilities is New England's largest
electric utility system, serving more than 2.3 million customers in
Connecticut, Massachusetts and New Hampshire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
