<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial adviser to stars accused of living off the backs of hisclients  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An indictment against a financial adviser to
some of Hollywood's young stars accused him of spending their money
on helicopters, hotels, limousines and even the rent for his SoHo
loft.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of ornaments to travel in a world that included clients
such as Leonardo DiCaprio, Ben Stiller and Courtney Cox Arquette
caused Dana C. Giacchetto to reach into his clients' accounts and
grab at least $9 million, prosecutors contend in the indictment
returned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Giacchetto, 37, allegedly misappropriated the money through
Cassandra, a company he ran from Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment in U.S. District Court in Manhattan accuses
Giacchetto of taking the money to benefit himself, his company,
third parties to which he lent money or to pay other clients and
conceal the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year alone, Giacchetto allegedly spent at least
$8,000 on helicopters, $3,400 on limousines, $12,000 to lease a new
Mercedes-Benz and more than $30,000 on stereos, computers, art and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
   He allegedly rang up more than $120,000 on hotel bills,
including one stint at a Hollywood hotel that cost more than
$80,000 for 10 suites, the indictment said. Restaurant bills added
another $55,000.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he gave millions of dollars belonging to his clients
to friends and associates, the government said.
</P>
<P>
   The comforts allegedly supported his ability to flash the pearls
of success at Hollywood parties where he could pad a client list so
valuable that, after his arrest, he announced through his lawyer
that he wanted to become an agent.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said Giacchetto promised clients he used a
conservative investment strategy and did not take custody of their
money when he actually was looting the accounts of at least $9
million.
</P>
<P>
   When federal authorities noticed, he allegedly lied to them and
altered a crucial portion of a Cassandra balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   The altered portion of the balance sheet falsely represented
that the company had no liabilities and net capital of more than $1
million when it actually had more than $9.3 million in liabilities
and was insolvent by more than $2.2 million, the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accused him of failing to disclose that he owed
$4.8 million to the band Phish.
</P>
<P>
   Giacchetto surrendered and was released on bail last month.
Later, he was ordered held without bail after prosecutors said he
was caught at an airport with an expired passport, a bag of cash
and $44,000 in airplane tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charged that he bought airline tickets to Italy,
Japan, Singapore and Germany and had altered an expired passport to
make it appear as though it were still valid.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Giacchetto faces a maximum sentence of 10 years in
prison and a fine of up to $18 million on a securities fraud count.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Levander, Giacchetto's lawyer, did not return a telephone
message for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 0220 </TRAILER>
