<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gorbachev says Putin lacks experience but works hard  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN MATTHEWS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev may
have pulled for another candidate to win the Russian presidency,
but he says the nation must now rally behind Vladimir Putin and
help him continue the democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev, who supported former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov,
says Putin ''will be a serious partner who understands the
importance of the West, the importance of Europe and the importance
particularly of the United States for Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov eventually dropped out of the election won by Putin, a
former KGB agent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Putin is a new man in Russian politics,'' said Gorbachev, who
was a panelist at a forum assembled by media magnate Rupert Murdoch
on Tuesday. ''He doesn't have enough experience of statesmanship.
At the same time he is a serious and well-educated person. He is a
very hardworking person.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who never held elected office until last month's
presidential vote, is viewed with some concern in the West because
of his hard-line positions on the war in Chechnya and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev, who led the Soviet Union from 1985 until its 1991
collapse, made the remarks in a question-and-answer session with
reporters after participating in a panel discussion of global
expectations of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The panelists included Koichi Kato, a former secretary general
of Japan's Liberal-Democratic Party, and World Bank President James
Wolfensohn, who said the developing world expects the United States
to be an equal partner.
</P>
<P>
   A second panel comprised four U.S. political leaders: former
House Speaker Newt Gingrich; Sen. Bob Kerrey, of Nebraska; former
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Gen. Colin Powell, former
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Both panels were moderated by former Secretary of State Henry
Kissinger and ranged widely over issues having to do with the role
of the United States in a post-Cold War world.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said that while the United States must change its
foreign policy style and learn ''to listen better, to be a partner
rather than a dominator,'' the nation's main challenges in the next
25 years are domestic.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not prepared for another wave of technological and
scientific change,'' Gingrich said. ''We ought to go to a model
where every 4-year-old gets a computer with a literacy package.
That may sound radical. In 1800 free education was radical. In 1900
free textbooks were radical in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich called education reform ''the No. 1 challenge to
American leadership in the 21st century'' and said the National
Science Foundation's annual budget should be increased from $4
billion to $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The event, titled Global Forum 2000, took place at a Wall Street
hotel in front of an invited audience of about 250 that included
former New York City Police Commissioner William Bratton,
Republican fund-raiser Georgette Mosbacher and gossip columnist
Cindy Adams.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of demonstrators outside protested the absence of
women on either panel.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a huge oversight,'' said Sonia Ossorio, media director
for the New York chapter of the National Organization for Women.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was the keynote speaker at
a dinner Monday night kicking off the forum, a spokesman for
Murdoch's News Corp. noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 0220 </TRAILER>
