<HEADLINE> Italian Gondola Tragedy Settled  </HEADLINE>
By JOE WHEELAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- More than two years after a Marine jet
severed an Italian ski gondola cable, killing 20 Europeans, the
victims' relatives will get nearly $40 million from the U.S. and
Italian governments.
</P>
<P>
   A Virginia attorney representing the Belgian relatives of five
of the victims of the Feb. 3, 1998, tragedy near Cavalese, Italy,
said the settlement accepted by the families April 14 was a
bittersweet end to their quest for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sad part is that this is what the United States should
have done two years ago,'' C. Torrence Armstrong of McLean, Va.,
said in a telephone interview Tuesday. ''In taking this long, it's
not a very satisfying feeling for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Each victim's family will get nearly $2 million. The U.S.
government will pay 75 percent of the settlement's cost, and the
Italian government will pay the rest, Armstrong said. The
settlement ratio is governed by NATO accords.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems this is all the U.S. is going to do,'' he said,
adding that the U.S. Navy hasn't kept its promise to give the
families a report about the safety of military flights over Italy.
''They reneged on that and never provided it,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach the Pentagon for comment Tuesday were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government is continuing to investigate the
accident, but the settlement ends all civil litigation, Armstrong
said.
</P>
<P>
   An EA-6B Prowler based at Cherry Point Marine Air Base was
deployed at Aviano Air Base in Italy for missions over Bosnia when
it clipped the ski gondola cable during a training flight. All 20
people in the gondola died when it plummeted into an alpine valley.
The damaged jet made it back to base.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators blamed the flight crew for the tragedy, saying the
plane was flying too low and too fast when it hit the cable.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Capt. Richard J. Ashby, of Mission Viejo, Calif., was
acquitted of manslaughter but sentenced to six months in the brig
for destroying a videotape shot during the flight.
</P>
<P>
   The Prowler's navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer of Westbury,
N.Y., was dismissed from the Marines after pleading guilty to a
similar charge for the videotape's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Charges were dropped against the two back-seat crewmen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 0222 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0054 </DOCNO>
