<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shell Fined $2M in Tanker Case  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon is warning oil shippers in the
Persian Gulf that they must be able to prove that cargo found to
include Iraqi oil was not obtained in violation of the U.N. oil
embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Tuesday that oil giant
Royal Dutch-Shell Group was fined $2 million last weekend for
failing to document its claim that Iraqi oil aboard a tanker it
hired in the Persian Gulf was not bought in violation of the
embargo. The oil company will be allowed to keep the oil, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Bacon said, failure to document the legality of
Iraqi oil shipments will result in confiscation of the cargo and
possibly the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said chemical tests of the cargo aboard the Russian tanker
Akademik Pustovoit, detained April 5 with a cargo of 78,000 tons of
Royal-Dutch Shell oil, showed that 20 percent was of Iraqi origin.
Bacon said he believed the rest of the oil was from Iranian fields.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the tanker was stopped, Royal Dutch-Shell officials
insisted its cargo was exclusively Iranian.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Royal Dutch-Shell unwittingly acquired the Iraqi
portion of its cargo, although the circumstances are unclear. As a
result, the oil company was fined but allowed to keep the cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Royal Dutch-Shell cooperated fully with the
international maritime interception force that patrols the Gulf to
enforce U.N. sanctions against Iraq dating from Iraq's 1990
invasion of neighboring Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the Akademik's cargo will be unloaded in Oman, then
returned in its entirety to Royal Dutch-Shell. The oil company will
pay the $2 million fine to a United Nations escrow account used to
pay the cost of enforcing the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq is permitted to sell a prescribed amount of oil under U.N.
guidelines, but in recent months it increasingly has used smuggling
to get around the U.N. limitations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 0222 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0055 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Police Harassed US Tourists  </HEADLINE>
By NATALIA PARRA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACAPULCO, Mexico (AP)-- Two rogue federal police agents assigned
to the international airport in the Pacific coast resort of
Acapulco have allegedly harassed U.S. tourists several times over
the last month, the airport's director said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement Tuesday by airport director Carlos Morlet appears
to lend weight to a complaint by a Los Angeles resident, who told
The Associated Press that federal agents stole $300 from him after
he was held in an airport interrogation room.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have detected two Federal Judicial Police agents assigned
to the airport for more than a month who have carried out actions
against tourists from the United States,'' Morlet said.
</P>
<P>
   Morlet said the three recent cases of harassment were apparently
directed against Mexicans with U.S. residency who came to Acapulco
on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police have abused our countrymen, and it has reached such
extremes that we are taking measures to prevent more abuses,''
Morlet said.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Angel Santos of Los Angeles claimed that two federal
police agents at the airport detained him as he arrived in
Acapulco, held him in an interrogation room for an hour, suggested
he give them a bribe and took $300.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, Santos claimed, was that his traveling companion, Noe
Santos Castro, was also taken away by police, who later denied they
were holding him and offered no information on his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Calls for comment to the Attorney General's Office, which
controls the federal police, went unanswered. Edgar Tapia, customs
director at the airport, confirmed that two plainclothes police
searched travelers for drugs and weapons at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not aware of what kind of treatment they give the
people they subject to searches,'' Tapia said. He said the airport
participates in a nationwide program that seeks to guarantee good
treatment for Mexican resident abroad when they return to visit the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Abuses against returning Mexicans -- common robberies or
extortion by corrupt policemen -- have frequently been reported in
the past. Mexicans living abroad generally earn much more than
their countrymen, a fact that may make them a target for such
abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Morlet said one tourist from Chicago had accused the policemen
of unjustly detaining and threatening him with a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   No criminal complaints on any of the allegations have been filed
with local police, according to both Morlet and Tapia.
</P>
<P>
   Angel Santos said the harassment began after one of his
suitcases didn't turn up when his flight landed in Acapulco. After
reporting the lost bag, he went through customs, where he got a
''green light'' from a random selection device, meaning he would
not be searched.
</P>
<P>
   The agents detained him anyway, Angel Santos said. According to
one airport official, standard procedure states that travelers
cannot be detained in airport interrogation rooms unless they have
been caught with contraband or are suspected of carrying it, or
face criminal charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 0226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missile Defense Cost Reported  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A national missile shield that would offer
limited protection from attack by smaller, newly armed countries
would cost almost $60 billion through 2015, the nonpartisan
Congressional Budget Office says.
</P>
<P>
   A CBO report released Tuesday said that's how much would be
needed to defend the country from attack by a relatively small
number of incoming ballistic missiles. It said those missiles could
contain nuclear, biological or chemical weapons, capable of killing
millions of people.
</P>
<P>
   The report cautioned that many still believe hostile countries
just developing long-range missiles, such as North Korea or Iran,
could find easy ways to outmaneuver the proposed defense system.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota, who
requested the report with Sens. Carl Levin, D-Mich., and Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., said it made clear that the criteria of cost,
operability, effect on national security and impact on arms
reduction efforts can't be ignored in deciding whether to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is far too soon to evaluate the overall feasibility or
advisability of the missile defense project,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., a chief proponent of a missile
defense system, said the CBO estimate was far too high and has ''no
basis in reality.'' ''You can't put a price on protecting American
cities,'' Weldon said, but $60 billion was ''totally out of line,
out of synch with anything I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress last year passed by large majorities, and President
Clinton signed, a bill stating it is the policy of the United
States to deploy, as soon as technologically possible, a system
capable of defending U.S. territory against limited ballistic
missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   The program has had problems with test failures and has met
strong opposition from nuclear powers such as Russia and China.
Russia says it would violate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty
and threatened to pull out of other arms-reduction pacts if the
United States builds the system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to decide this fall, after another Pentagon test of
the system in June, whether to continue with plans to have it
operating by a target date of 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The CBO said the first phase of a national missile defense would
cost $29.5 billion through 2015, $3.9 billion more than the
administration has estimated.
</P>
<P>
   It would include locating 100 interceptors in central Alaska,
constructing a high-resolution X-band radar and upgrading several
existing early-warning radars.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase, to be deployed by 2010 under current plans,
would use satellites that could track not only powered-flight
missiles but also missiles gliding through space. The third phase
would add 150 interceptors, some at a second site currently planned
for Grand Forks, N. D.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has not yet estimated the cost of the last
two phases. The CBO said the second phase would cost another $6.1
billion and the third phase $13.3 billion through 2015. It said
another $10.6 billion would be needed for space-based sensors,
satellites that share have other missions with support of missile
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''The costs are going up, up and away,'' said Daryl Kimball of
the Coalition to Reduce Nuclear Dangers, an advocacy group that
believes a national missile defense is unlikely to work even
against a minimal threat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congress and the American people, once they realize this, will
experience a bit of sticker shock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the system insist the cost is justified because the
threat is increasing for long-range missile attack from North Korea
or a similar potential adversary.
</P>
<P>
   President Reagan in the 1980s proposed the far more ambitious
Strategic Defense Initiative, or ''Star Wars,'' a space-based
anti-missile system designed mainly to defend against Soviet
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget office: http://www.cbo.gov
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's Ballistic Missile Defense Organization:
http://www.acq.osd.mil/bmdo/bmdolink/html/bmdolink.html
</P>
<P>
   The Coalition to Reduce Nuclear Dangers: http://www.crnd.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
