<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Mulls Victims' Rights Bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a debate that delves into the controversial
issue of amending the Constitution, the Senate is weighing a
proposal that would grant victims of violent crimes certain rights.
</P>
<P>
   On an 82-12 vote, the Senate agreed Tuesday to begin debate on a
victims' rights measure. A vote on the amendment itself could occur
by the end of the week, but some Democrats have indicated they may
try to delay it with a lengthy debate on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the amendment said it is needed to balance
constitutional protections that suspects and criminals receive.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States Constitution guarantees 15 separate rights
to criminal defendants and each of these rights was established by
amendment to the Constitution,'' said Sen. Dianne Feinstein,
D-Calif. ''There is not one word written in the U.S. Constitution
on behalf of crime victims.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents accused the amendment's backers of trying to
tinker with the Constitution. ''Some of my colleagues apparently
think it (the Constitution) is a rough draft, available for
amendment at a whim,'' said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment specifies that victims of crimes or their families
would be guaranteed such rights as reasonable notice of court
proceedings and an offender's release or escape, the right to
attend and be heard at legal proceedings and court-ordered
restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, the Senate rejected by four votes a
constitutional amendment to ban flag burning. A two-thirds majority
-- 67 votes in the Senate -- is required in each house to advance a
constitutional amendment. It then must be ratified by at least 35
state legislatures
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., said he would use the victims'
rights debate to press his and President Clinton's demand for new
restrictions, including up to a 72-hour-waiting period, on the sale
of guns at gun shows. The Senate passed such a measure last year,
but the House rejected it. Republican leaders have rejected calls
since then for a meeting to resolve the differences over gun
control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We ought to stick to the subject here,'' said Sen. Jon Kyl,
R-Ariz., who with Feinstein is a chief sponsor of the victims'
rights amendment. ''We all know one good way to defeat a good idea
is to talk it to death.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar measure in the House has yet to be acted upon by the
Judiciary Committee. Some Democrats said they would push a
substitute measure to write similar guarantees into federal law.
Currently, 32 states have some form of victims' rights laws in
place.
</P>
<P>
   Some victims groups agree with opponents. ''Our belief is that
resources and energy need to be focused in other more pressing and
critical matters,'' said Gordon Campbell, executive director of
Victim Services, the nation's largest victims' assistance group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the proposed amendment does have strong support,
including from such groups as Mothers Against Drunk Driving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 0227 </TRAILER>
