<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Nile prevention effort under way in 17 states  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Federal health officials are working with
17 states to prevent an outbreak of the West Nile Virus, which last
year killed seven people in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Ostroff, West Nile coordinator for the federal Centers
for Disease Control, said surveillance of mosquitos and birds that
carry the virus is under way in states along the Atlantic seaboard
and the Gulf of Mexico. Humans may contract the virus when they are
bitten by an infected mosquito.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are concerned that birds from the Northeast may have
spread the virus, a form of encephalitis, when they migrated south
for the winter. An infected dead bird was found in Baltimore, the
only bird with the virus to be found outside the New York City
area, Ostroff said.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC provided the 17 states and two cities considered at risk
with $2.7 million to create surveillance programs.
</P>
<P>
   States and cities targeted by the CDC are: Alabama, Connecticut,
District of Columbia, Delaware, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana,
Massachusetts, Mississippi, Pennsylvania, Maryland, New York, New
York City, New Jersey, North Carolina, Rhode Island, South
Carolina, Texas and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita Lowey, a Westchester Democrat on the House
Appropriations Subcommittee, which funds the CDC, is asking for
another $5 million to combat the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who become infected either show no reaction or
become mildly ill with flu-like symptoms. Fatalities are rare. The
most vulnerable are the elderly, the very young and those with
immune deficiencies. In those people, the virus can cause the brain
lining to swell.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials who were caught off guard by the outbreak last
year in New York City said they are better prepared this time
around.
</P>
<P>
   ''In many of the areas that were involved in the outbreak last
year ... there are intense prevention efforts under way,'' Ostroff
said at a lengthy briefing on the virus Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the full reach of the virus will likely not be known
until mosquitos stir from hibernation in the coming weeks.
Researchers have already detected the virus in some hibernating
mosquitos in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   A CDC survey of some 600 people in the Whitestone neighborhood
in Queens, one of the most severely affected areas during last
year's outbreak, found that 2.5 percent of the residents were
infected with the virus, Ostroff said. Health officials tested
residents' blood.
</P>
<P>
   Although the chances of becoming seriously ill from the virus
are low, officials still suggest that people in at-risk states wear
insect repellant and eliminate pools of stagnant water, which are
breeding grounds for mosquitos.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Johnson, of the Environmental Protection Agency, also
suggested that communities use larvicides to kill mosquito larvae.
Larvicides are already being used in New York City. They pose less
risk to humans than pesticides, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Mass spraying of malathion, which was used last year in New York
City, should be used only as a last resort, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
