<DOCNO> APW20000426.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National League Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By JOSH DUBOW, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Phillies are the only team able to knock out
Randy Johnson this season. They just aren't good enough to beat the
Big Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson struck out 11 batters in 6 2-3 innings Tuesday night as
the Arizona Diamondbacks snapped a three-game losing streak with a
10-2 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a true stopper,'' Arizona's Steve Finley said. ''He's one
of the elite.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (5-0) allowed two runs and three hits on a 49-degree
night in Philadelphia. He recorded the 129th double-digit strikeout
game of his career and his fourth in five starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson pitched 8 2-3 innings in a 6-4 victory over Philadelphia
on opening day and went the distance in his next three starts. He
left after throwing 117 pitches Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The guys got me runs and it was my job to preserve it,'' he
said. ''The more pitches I don't throw early in the season, I'll be
that much better later in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   In other games, it was San Francisco 6, Florida 4; the Mets 6,
Cincinnati 5; Atlanta 1, Los Angeles 0; Montreal 10, Colorado 4;
Pittsburgh 4, San Diego 3; Houston 11, the Cubs 7; and St. Louis 7,
Milwaukee 2.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Stinnett had his second, two-homer game of the season and
drove in four runs to lead Arizona. Travis Lee and Finley also
homered for the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies, who were coming off a 1-6 road trip, have lost
four straight.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona took a 2-0 lead when Stinnett hit a two-run homer in the
second off Chris Brock (0-3). Stinnett hit his sixth homer in the
seventh inning, a two-run shot that made it 10-2. It was the third
two-homer game of Stinnett's career.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was looking for something up, got good wood on it and the
wind helped it,'' Stinnett said of his first homer.
</P>
<P>
Giants 6, Marlins 4
</P>
<P>
   With much of the focus on a Cuban-American boycott, Armando Rios
hit an RBI double in the 11th inning off Dan Miceli (2-1) to give
visiting San Francisco its fourth straight win.
</P>
<P>
   The game had eight players sitting out as part of a work
stoppage by Miami's Cuban-American community. They protested Elian
Gonzalez's removal from the home of his relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gardner (2-1) pitched the final two innings for the win.
</P>
<P>
Mets 6, Reds 5
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell, robbed of a home run earlier by Ken Griffey Jr.,
homered off Scott Sullivan (0-1) to spark a seventh-inning rally
that gave New York its ninth straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   Mets shortstop Rey Ordonez and third base coach Cookie Rojas
were absent, in protest of the Elian Gonzalez case. Reds outfielder
Alex Ochoa, whose parents were born in Cuba, decided to play.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, who blocked a trade last winter that would have sent
him from Seattle to the Mets, struck out three times in his Shea
Stadium debut.
</P>
<P>
   Turk Wendell (2-0) got the win and Armando Benitez earned his
eighth save.
</P>
<P>
Braves 1, Dodgers 0
</P>
<P>
   At Atlanta, Tom Glavine pitched a three-hitter to outduel Kevin
Brown and the Braves won their eighth straight.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine (4-0) no-hit the Dodgers for 4 1-3 innings, and Quilvio
Veras drove in the lone run with a two-out single in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (1-1), returning from the 15-day disabled list, pitched
well, but sustained his first regular-season loss to the Braves
since July 13, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Expos 10, Rockies 4
</P>
<P>
   Lee Stevens hit a three-run homer and Michael Barrett had a
two-run double to lead host Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Widger also homered for Montreal as Carl Pavano (3-0)
allowed four runs in six innings to become the first Expos pitcher
to get three wins.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bohanon (0-2) took the loss.
</P>
<P>
Pirates 4, Padres 3, 11 innings
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Brown doubled and scored the tying run in the ninth
against Trevor Hoffman, then tripled off Carlos Almanzar (0-1) and
scored the winning run in the 11th as Pittsburgh rallied at home.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sauerbeck (1-0) got the final out in the 11th for the
victory as the Pirates stopped a four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
Cardinals 7, Brewers 2
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire homered for the third straight game and Darryl Kile
(4-1) won his fourth game.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who missed nine games this season with a sore back,
homered in the first, one out after a homer by Edgar Renteria off
Brewers starter Jason Bere (2-2).
</P>
<P>
Astros 11, Cubs 7
</P>
<P>
   At Houston, Moises Alou went 4-for-4 and Richard Hidalgo had
three RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds (4-0) allowed four runs and seven hits in six
innings as the Astros snapped a three-game skid.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Downs (1-1) took the loss.
</P>
