<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Track Cycling Trials Open  </HEADLINE>
By TIM KORTE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRISCO, Texas (AP) -- Sky Christopherson knew every second would
count at the U.S. Olympic cycling trials, on the track and away
from it.
</P>
<P>
   Christopherson won the men's kilometer time trial in 1 minute,
5.044 seconds as the five-day trials began Tuesday. He asked for an
early start in the race so he could be rested for today's Olympic
sprint, a team event.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to get as much recovery as I could. The Olympic
sprint is very important to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The kilometer time trial is cycling's version of the 400 meters
in track and field. It's a sprint that requires pacing, but any
competitor who doesn't go hard gets left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought I could go 1:04.5, but my time was good enough today
to win,'' said Christopherson, of Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   He now moves to Olympic sprint, a new men's event for the Sydney
Games. Riding all out, one cyclist and then a second leaves the
track, one at a time, after the first two laps. The third rider
sprints another lap to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Christopherson will join two riders who shared the gold medal at
last summer's Pan American Games, Marcelo Arrue of Woodland Hills,
Calif., and Johnny Barrios of Redlands, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Erin Hartwell of Indianapolis, the only American cyclist to win
medals in two Olympics, has changed from the speed races to
endurance. He's scheduled to compete in the men's individual
pursuit today.
</P>
<P>
   In individual pursuit, two racers start from opposite sides of
the track and race for the fastest times. The women go to three
kilometers and the men to four, but the race ends early if one
cyclist passes the other.
</P>
<P>
   Although Christopherson won the kilometer time trial, he was two
seconds behind the qualifying standard for a spot on the U.S. long
team, the pool of riders eligible for Olympic team consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Kurreck of Los Altos, Calif., won the women's individual
pursuit in 3:47.538, more than 10 seconds behind the long team
qualifying standard. There was a good reason both times were slow.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic trials are being held early in the racing season
because U.S. coaches want to consider performances in World Cup
events, as well as training and trials results, before selecting
the team in July.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's early in the year,'' said Erin Veenstra-Mirabella of
Colorado Springs, third in individual pursuit at 3:50.721. ''After
we get a few World Cup races, the Olympic picture should be a
little clearer.''
</P>
<P>
   The long team qualifying times, established by U.S. Cycling, are
based on projected medal results at Sydney. To reach those marks, a
racer needs one of the world's best times for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Kurreck is safe because she's already on the long team as a road
racer. She wanted to qualify on the track, too, and practiced only
two days in Texas after taking a break from her road racing team in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did my first pursuit race in two years this morning in
qualifying. It took a little getting used to again,'' said Kurreck,
the runner-up in individual pursuit on the Frisco track at 1998
nationals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 0246 </TRAILER>
