<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Candidates Hold First Debate  </HEADLINE>
By JULIE WATSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- In the first debate of one of the tightest
presidential races in Mexican history, opposition candidates bashed
the ruling party but offered few specifics on what they would
change if they end its 71-year reign.
</P>
<P>
   Tough-talking northerner Vicente Fox, who has pulled almost even
in polls with Francisco Labastida of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, appeared relaxed and conciliatory Tuesday as
he tried to use the debate to unite the divided opposition behind
his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tonight six candidates appeared, and five of us share a common
idea: the urgent need to get another party into power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All six presidential candidates appeared in the debate, which
allowed each 14 minutes to put forth their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The debate largely focused on the rivalry between the
front-runners, Labastida and Fox, but two of the other candidates
joined Fox in attacking what they called the record of corruption
of the ruling party, known as the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, who seemed touchy at times, attacked Fox's political
record directly, and depicted himself -- despite his lifelong career
in the PRI -- as ''the candidate of change ... Change with a course,
change with security for the country, true change.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Many politicians, from many parties, have used power to enrich
themselves,'' Labastida said, saying he would implement broad
anti-corruption programs.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the need to defeat the PRI almost as a mantra, the main
opposition candidates didn't get beyond vague promises of more
jobs, higher wages, better education, and more public safety -- the
touchstone issues for decades here.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard nice wishes, but I didn't find concrete proposals,''
political analyst Marco Levario said on a television panel
following the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Martinez, who listened to the debate on a radio at his
streetside taco stand, agreed: ''There wasn't anything firm. It was
all promises.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference following the 1{-hour debate, Labastida
said he hoped to focus on more specific economic and political
proposals in a second debate, tentatively scheduled for May 23. The
election is July 2.
</P>
<P>
   Fox made reference to the possibility of fraud in his remarks
after the debate: ''We still have 70 days left to election day. We
still face the action of the state apparatus, and the machinery of
the ruling party.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the July 2 elections could be Mexico's cleanest ever
and probably represent the best chance ever for the opposition to
defeat the PRI, which has held the presidency since it was founded
in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, a former Coca-Cola executive who favors cowboy boots and
represents the right-center National Action Party, has so far
failed to draw the center-left Democratic Revolution Party -- the
other main opposition group -- into an alliance.
</P>
<P>
   One of the debate's sharpest attacks came after Labastida told
the story of a woman who told him she was afraid to leave her house
because of crime in a city governed by Fox's party. Fox ridiculed
the story as borrowed from U.S. campaigns, reminding voters that
Clintonite James Carville advised Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very American to tell little stories that never
existed,'' Fox said. ''It's the only thing Mr. Labastida is
learning: how to follow the teachings of Mr. Carville.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, a former agriculture secretary, touted his plans to
revitalize Mexico's poor countryside. But Fox, a rancher, took him
on his own turf: ''We'll have a president who knows the
countryside, who's from the countryside, and not a bureaucrat who
doesn't even know how to milk a cow.''
</P>
<P>
   The two have traded insults during campaign stops, with
Labastida accusing Fox of speaking from both sides of his mouth,
and Fox -- at 6-foot-3 -- calling the 5-foot-9 Labastida ''shorty''
and ''more of the same.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than seven decades, the PRI has held onto the
presidency by means fair and foul, but the party has been forced by
both domestic and international pressure to make itself, and
Mexico's electoral system, more democratic.
</P>
<P>
   The changes have allowed the opposition to take state and local
governments, and opened up the possibility -- unthinkable a
generation ago -- that the PRI could even lose the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you don't think change is possible, just look at what has
happened in the world,'' Fox said, recalling the elections of
Nelson Mandela and Lech Walesa and the fall of the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today the eyes of the world are on Mexico. But only you can
decide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 0248 </TRAILER>
