<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 07:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8th driver murdered; another arrested for assaulting passenger  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two livery cab drivers were carjacked overnight,
the day after the eighth livery cab driver this year was killed on
the job.
</P>
<P>
   A 46-year-old driver's car was stolen by two unidentified men at
about 11 p.m. Tuesday. Police said the driver had picked up the men
in lower Manhattan and drove them to Brooklyn. Once there, the
passengers said they couldn't open the doors. When the driver tried
to help, they pushed him away and stole his light blue Lincoln Town
Car, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 2 a.m. today, a Bronx livery driver was robbed at
knifepoint of $112 by three passengers who had called his company
for a pickup, police said. The unidentified 55-year-old driver was
thrown out of the car but was not seriously hurt. The robbers sped
off with the car.
</P>
<P>
   Police were looking for both cars and the robbers.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incidents involving cabbies came after driver George
Luciano seriously injured one of his passengers with a metal bar
following an argument on a Bronx street corner Tuesday, police
said. Luciano apparently thought he was about to be robbed.
Luciano, 45, has been charged with assault.
</P>
<P>
   Luciano was on his way to pick up a dispatched fare when Mario
King jumped into his cab at a Bronx intersection. Luciano told him
to get out, and the argument ensued, police said.
</P>
<P>
   As King exited the car, so did Luciano -- allegedly with a metal
bar. Luciano then allegedly hit King and drove off. His cab company
notified police about what happened, and Luciano was arrested. King
was listed in serious but stable condition at Jacobi Hospital hours
after the alleged attack.
</P>
<P>
   Luciano had likely heard of Monday night's shooting death of
livery cab driver Jose Olivares. The 35-year-old cabbie was the
eighth driver killed on the job this year. The Dominican Republic
native was shot once in the head shortly after 10 p.m. during a
botched robbery attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the four passengers in the cab were injured when the car
crashed into an apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers -- two men, a boy and a girl -- were charged with
attempted robbery, murder and criminal possession of a weapon. They
were identified as John Rivera, 19; Ramon Anaya, 18; Norberto
Hernandez, 16; and Jasmine Valentine, 16.
</P>
<P>
   News of Olivares' death spread quickly and may have caused some
panic, as in Luciano's case.
</P>
<P>
   ''He thought he was going to be robbed,'' said a dispatcher
named Segfredo at Watson Car Service in the Bronx, where Luciano
has worked for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates concerned for livery drivers' safety say many cabbies
are driving scared these days. Eight drivers have been killed so
far this year, compared with 11 for all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like a nightmare,'' said Fernando Mateo, president of
the New York State Federation of Taxi Drivers. ''You have not
finished mourning one when you are suddenly arranging for another
wake and funeral procession. When will these killings stop?''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo said Olivares had spoken out about the dangers facing
drivers on the same night he was killed.
</P>
<P>
   '''If I get robbed or I get killed, believe me, I'm going to
take them with me,''' Mateo quoted Olivares as having said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the eight slain cabbies had installed a bulletproof
partition in his car, police said. Olivares had intended to have a
partition installed but had not been able to because the shops that
do that work were swamped with orders, said Eddie Almonte, manager
of Excellent Car Services, where Olivares had worked for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by the recent killings, the Taxi and Limousine
Commission voted unanimously last week to require all drivers to
install either bulletproof partitions or digital security cameras
in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the TLC made it mandatory for yellow cabs and livery
cars owned by more than one driver to have the partitions. But cars
owned and operated by individual drivers -- 90 percent of all livery
cars -- could have either partitions or tiny surveillance cameras
installed behind the rearview mirror. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
recently pledged $5 million toward a grant program to help pay for
the security devices.
</P>
<P>
   The recent increase in driver murders and the new requirement
has apparently overwhelmed shops that install partitions, which are
cheaper to install than cameras. Partitions cost between $250 to
$350, and cameras start at $600.
</P>
<P>
   ''My understanding is that there are waiting lists,'' said TLC
spokesman Allan Fromberg. ''They (the shops) are doing the best
they can, they are operating to capacity. Many hundreds of
partitions have been put in already.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Taxi and Limousine Commission: http://www.ci.nyc.ny.us/html/tlc
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
