<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 13; Nasdaq Down 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed in quiet trading
today as investors took a breather after a strong rally on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 13.26 to 11,138.08.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was down 3.45 to 3,707.78 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 1.15 to 1,478.29.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Dow and the Nasdaq each rose more than 200
points, investors retreated to the sidelines, debating their next
moves. Corporate earnings reports provided the only real spark in
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer edged up 3/8 to 29 7/8. Late Tuesday, the
computer maker reported that excluding gains in its investment
portfolio, first-quarter net income and revenues were virtually
unchanged from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Online auctioneer eBay rose 2 1/8 to 155 11/16. The company's
first-quarter operating results exceeded Wall Street expectations
as the amount of merchandise sold on its site surpassed $1 billion
for the first time. Also, eBay announced plans to split its stock
2-for-1.
</P>
<P>
   The latest sign of the economy's continued growth came today
from the Commerce Department, which said orders to U.S. factories
for big-ticket manufactured goods rose in March for the first time
this year.
</P>
<P>
   After two straight months of declines, orders for durable goods
-- items expected to last at least three years -- rose 2.6 percent
last month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $215.2 billion,
the government reported.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to slow the economy to a more sustainable rate of
growth and keep inflation at bay, the Federal Reserve has raised
interest rates five times since June 30. Given the outlook for
strong continuing growth, many economists believe the Fed will bump
up interest rates again on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 127.21 million
shares, behind Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 0.83 to 489.86.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.8 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was up 2.0 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.5 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
