<DOCNO> APW20000426.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Giuliani trade charges  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton said Rudolph Giuliani
should apologize for calling federal agents in the Elian Gonzalez
raid storm troopers.
</P>
<P>
   But the New York City mayor stood by his remarks. His camp
instead attacked the first lady's fund raising, saying Democrats
were trying to hide soft-money donors to her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, a new Zogby International poll of voters in
GOP-leaning upstate New York showed the mayor leading the first
lady by 14 percent. The upstate poll showed Giuliani with 52
percent and Clinton with 38 percent. The poll has a margin of error
of plus or minus 3.2 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who just signed a civility pledge promising a clean
U.S. Senate campaign, said she agreed with the Federal Law
Enforcement Officers Association, which is demanding an apology
from Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that the mayor's inflammatory and divisive rhetoric is
part of a pattern that he has engaged in for quite some time,'' the
first lady said during a campaign stop Tuesday in Westchester
County.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Saturday that the federal government had
''trampled the wishes of (Elian's) mother this morning with guns
and with storm troopers.''
</P>
<P>
   He had this to say Tuesday: ''You do not use loaded automatic
weapons to remove 6-year-old children. Why the attorney general
made the choice to have them dress in battle fatigues and with
automatic weapons that were loaded is a misjudgment of very, very
large proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani added: ''I'm not going to back down from it. ... I've
been in law enforcement a very long time. I've never seen a
situation in which a 6-year-old was removed in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The ''storm trooper'' remark, he said, ''was meant clearly as a
criticism, and a direct one, of Attorney General Reno and Bill
Clinton'' and was ''not intended as a criticism of the particular
law enforcement officers carrying out the mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's campaign targeted Clinton's fund raising, which has
been a frequent line of attack. This time the campaign was critical
of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee's decision not to
immediately disclose soft-money donations to New York Senate 2000,
a committee set up to support Clinton's Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is not subject to $2,000 campaign donation limits for
individuals. It can be used for issue ads and party-building
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've been caught in another of the campaign scams they
imported from Arkansas and perfected in Washington,'' Giuliani
spokeswoman Kim Serafin said of the president and first lady.
</P>
<P>
   DSCC officials said they made an accounting decision not to
detail soft-money donations every month when they file their
reports because the accounting involved was too onerous.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they plan to file those reports when the money is
transferred from a joint fund-raising account set up for the
candidate. New York Senate 2000 raised about $500,000 in soft money
in the first quarter of this year, officials said Tuesday. That is
on top of the roughly $700,000 in soft money raised last year. A
new account set up by Republicans for Giuliani raise nearly
$500,000 in just one month.
</P>
<P>
   DSCC political director Jim Jordan said ''the Clinton campaign
has no control over or knowledge of the administrative
technicalities'' of the account. He asserted the DSCC was following
federal election law.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Interfaith Alliance announced that the first lady
had signed its pledge to run a clean campaign. By signing the
group's Framework of Civility for Political Candidates, candidates
promise to avoid personal attacks, take responsibility for the
conduct of advisers and allies and make documentation available for
factual allegations made about opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance is also calling on Giuliani to sign the pledge. He
has not done so.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates Al Gore and George W. Bush signed the
pledge in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 1117 </TRAILER>
