<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Almodovar's Roots Lie in La Mancha  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL WOOLLS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALZADA DE CALATRAVA, Spain (AP) -- Pedro Almodovar doesn't live
here any more.
</P>
<P>
   The film director's birthplace is a drab little grid of potholes
and dust, the kind of poor farming town that teen-agers can't wait
to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's been decades since Almodovar made his home in this
patch of the La Mancha region with a tongue-twister name.
</P>
<P>
   But people here remember him. When the 48-year-old director paid
a rare homecoming visit this month to receive an award, after
winning the Oscar for best foreign film (''All About My Mother''),
the small town square swelled with TV cameras, people and pride.
People on balconies craned their nexks to watch. Rockets burst
overhead in a leaden sky.
</P>
<P>
   A local boy turned big-time director, Almodovar looked the part:
droopy black suit, black shirt, dark glasses, with a white scarf
against the evening chill. A stiff wind tussled his mop of hair.
</P>
<P>
   He confessed, though, that he wore sunglasses not to act cool
but to hide. This was only the second time he had returned since
his mother died here last year at age 83, and the pain was still
raw.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar says he has fond memories of Calzada de Calatrava, a
town of which there are no postcards, where Solitude Street lies
around the corner from Bitterness Street, where one grocer sells
stale bread as dogfood.
</P>
<P>
   His films may be ultra urban, but beneath it all, he says,
there's a strong influence from La Mancha, his town and its people
-- especially his mother, Francisca.
</P>
<P>
   The strong-willed women who dominate most of his 13 movies, both
comic and tragic, come from her, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ''You all knew her,'' Almodovar told the crowd, drawing cheers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The moral autonomy they have, the strength, the energy to
tackle all the problems they face -- all this comes directly from my
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar was born in Calzada de Calatrava, current population
around 5,000, and lived here until he was 8, when his father,
Antonio, a traveling wine salesman, moved the family of six to the
southwest Extremadura region, and eventually to Madrid. Almodovar
Sr. died 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   During the family's time here, the father was often away,
lugging wine on muleback to farms and ranches, sometimes bartering
for produce such as potatoes. His absence, neighbors and family
friends say, meant his wife was left with a prominent role raising
Pedro, his brother and two sisters.
</P>
<P>
   People who knew Pedro as a boy describe him as a chatty, playful
child who bordered on the mischievous. ''He was a real talker. He
was always getting into something,'' says Remedios Alcarcon, 62,
who lived down the street from the Almodovars.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a creative side, too. Felicia Caballero, who lived
across the street and says she changed his diapers more times than
she could count, said her little neighbor developed a thing about
pencils and paper.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'd always find him down on the ground, on his knees,
leaning over and writing or scribbling or drawing,'' said
Caballero, 68.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar's aunt Cecilia, one of the few surviving relatives of
his parents' generation, agrees he had a soft, reflective streak as
a young man and a weakness for poetry.
</P>
<P>
   People here are fabulously friendly and helpful. A visitor
looking for the squat, red-brick house where Almodovar's mother
lived in her final years is more than likely to be grabbed by the
arm and taken there. Those who knew the Almodovars love to talk
about them, and seem genuinely proud of Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   But even as many beam over his success and revel in the town's
15-minute puff of fame, there's an undercurrent of grumbling among
others, a hushed you-never-come-and-see-us resentment.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar has returned infrequently over the years, mainly
paying quick visits to his mother, and never mixing with locals.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he comes, Pedro tries to keep as low a profile as
possible,'' Mayor Francisco Espinosa says.
</P>
<P>
   One lifetime resident who declined to be named said that until
recently, Almodovar would say only that he was from La Mancha,
never mentioning thoroughly unglamorous Calzada de Calatrava.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that because he left so long ago, Almodovar isn't a
native at all but a city slicker. Yet another gripe is that some of
Almodovar's movie themes, such as sexual bondage, and his
characters, such as transvestites, hold little appeal in a farming
community more concerned with olive prices and weather forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Espinosa, who is among the director's defenders, said that
Almodovar's films have been hits in the town's lone movie theater
and that there is nothing wrong with his preferring privacy when he
comes to town.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar insists he is a son of La Mancha, the land of Don
Quixote, and does not rule out filming an entire movie there.
</P>
<P>
   So far, many of his films have paid sly homage to the region or
his hometown. For instance, in the 1984 ''What Did I Do to Deserve
This?'', a bus bound for Calzada de Calatrava tries its best but
never quite manages to leave the bus station.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar disclosed at the homecoming ceremony that he has
received many offers over the years from U.S. movie studios to
shoot a film about Don Quixote. But he couldn't bring himself to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't come to my native region and film a movie in which
Don Quixote, Sancho Panza and Dulcinea speak English,'' Almodovar
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
