<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kitchen Musical a Hit in S. Korea  </HEADLINE>
By SANG-HUN CHOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- On stage, four chefs chop, slice and
dice. Bits of cabbage and onions fly. Pots boil, and soon the
savory aroma of vegetables and spices fills the theater.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than culinary tips in the oddball South Korean
musical called ''Nanta,'' or ''Wild Beating.'' The performers beat
knives and kettles, pots and pans -- just about any utensil found in
a kitchen -- to a frenzied, infectious rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a huge hit in South Korea. Under the title
''Cookin','' it has played well in Tokyo, Disney World in Orlando,
Fla., and Scotland's Edinburgh Fringe Festival. Now, producers are
setting their sights on a New York run.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe our show has a universal appeal because the kitchen
is a natural place for percussion music. There, you can find more
items to beat than anywhere else,'' says director Choi Chul-ki, 28.
</P>
<P>
   Nanta echoes ''Stomp,'' the off-Broadway hit in which performers
fashion music with flotsam found on city streets.
</P>
<P>
   But while ''Stomp'' is built around a distinctive urban beat,
''Nanta'' borrows its heart-thumping rhythms from Korea's lively --
but fading -- traditional farmers' percussive music.
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, anthropologists reported a rhythm distinctive of
Korea when rural housewives ironed starched clothes by laying them
on a stone block and pounding away with a pair of round sticks.
Similar beats were heard when workers chopped with knives while
preparing a village feast.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of the 80-minute musical is simple. A restaurant
manager gives his three wacky chefs one hour to prepare a wedding
banquet with the help, or handicap, of the manager's bumbling
cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Clad in loose traditional cotton outfits, the chefs make a
solemn bow before a gargoyle-like Korean kitchen god. Then they sit
and tease delicate beats out of rice bowls with chopsticks and
spoons.
</P>
<P>
   When the show gets rolling, however, the cooks appear in
sleeveless T-shirts and barrel through rhythms with cleavers and
knives on chopping blocks, water-cooler bottles and trash cans at a
speed that would put the fast-slicing chefs at teppanyaki
restaurants to shame.
</P>
<P>
   Butcher knives flash in strobes. Vegetables fly everywhere,
sometimes into spectators' laps. A rock band booms.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was especially difficult to find rhythms with kitchen
gadgets because they did not have the kind of elasticity that
traditional instruments have,'' says Cho Hae-sun, 29, who plays a
chef.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nanta'' is a stark departure from traditional Korean musicals
that emphasize grace and decorum. Ancient Korean nobles stressed
the delicate ritual of cuisine, and they celebrated with musicians
who twanged sleepy tunes on zithers, spinning out oration that
could last hours.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ''Nanta'' gets inspiration from a different crowd --
irreverent tenants who celebrated autumn harvests with vulgar
clowning, punchy jokes at landlords, and crudely built drums and
gongs. True to that tradition, ''Nanta'' adds a hearty helping of
circus and slapstick comedy. Chefs juggle dishes, breathe fire and
joust with broom sticks.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, two chefs argue over who should dispose of the
trash. The rubbish bag lands in the laps of people sitting in the
most expensive seats of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nanta'' debuted in late 1997 and has attracted 350,000 viewers
to become one of the longest-running shows in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Starting out with four performers, the show has recruited 10
more young actors so that more than three performances can be
staged simultaneously at different locations.
</P>
<P>
   In May, ''Nanta'' will start touring in Asia, Europe and the
United States. The musical's creator, PMC Whan Performance, is
negotiating to take the musical to New York early next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1203 </TRAILER>
