<HEADLINE> Dow Down 107; Nasdaq Down 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mostly lower today as investors
took a breather after a strong rally on Tuesday. Technology stocks
were holding up better than the broad market.
</P>
<P>
   In midday on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite was down 3.20 to
3,708.03
</P>
<P>
   Other stock indicators were lower. The Dow Jones industrial
average was down 107.65 to 11,017.17 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 4.27 to 1,472.87.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Dow and the Nasdaq each rose more than 200
points, many investors retreated to the sidelines, debating their
next moves. Corporate earnings reports provided the only real spark
in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer edged up 7/16 to 29 15/16. Late Tuesday, the
computer maker reported that excluding gains in its investment
portfolio, first-quarter net income and revenues were virtually
unchanged from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Online auctioneer eBay gave up early gains and was down 2 11/16
to 150 7/8. The company's first-quarter operating results exceeded
Wall Street expectations as the amount of merchandise sold on its
site surpassed $1 billion for the first time. Also, eBay announced
plans to split its stock 2-for-1.
</P>
<P>
   A wide range of technology stocks were higher today. Internet
retail powerhouse Amazon.com gained 2 11/16 to 55 1/8 and Broadcom,
a maker of silicon semiconductors, rose 1 3/16 to 162 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   The latest sign of the economy's continued growth came today
from the Commerce Department, which said orders to U.S. factories
for big-ticket manufactured goods rose in March for the first time
this year.
</P>
<P>
   After two straight months of declines, orders for durable goods
-- items expected to last at least three years -- rose 2.6 percent
last month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $215.2 billion,
the government reported.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to slow the economy to a more sustainable rate of
growth and keep inflation at bay, the Federal Reserve has raised
interest rates five times since June 30. Given the outlook for
strong continuing growth, many economists believe the Fed will bump
up interest rates again on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Fed is looking for signs of moderation, they won't find
it'' in the durable goods report, said David Orr, chief economist
at First Union Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors were looking ahead to Thursday, when the
government will release first-quarter gross domestic product
figures. Many analysts expect the economy grew at a 6 percent rate
-- too fast for the Fed's comfort, but not as brisk as the 7.3
percent rate posted in the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Worries about rising interest rates weighed on
financial-services stocks. American Express fell 2 1/8 to 155 7/8
and J.P. Morgan fell 2 5/16 to 135 5/8, weighing most heavily on
the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 453.39 million
shares, behind Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 0.92 to 489.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
