<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GE Investors Reject Pension Changes  </HEADLINE>
By HANK KURZ Jr., Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Retired General Electric employees who
claim they're forced to live on meager pensions while the company
sits on a $24 billion pension fund were unable to alter the
corporation's pension plan today.
</P>
<P>
   A union proposal to require shareholder approval of retirement
packages for those who serve on the board was defeated, garnering
only 33 percent support of the shares that were voted. Many
retirees say the pension plan offered to regular employees is
meager, especially when compared to benefits offered to top
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Carrie J. Biggs-Adams, an NBC editor who spoke on behalf of the
union proposal at today's annual sharholder meting, said she was
pleased that the proposal gained more support than a year ago, when
it received 29 percent support.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're getting there,'' Biggs-Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders also gave overwhelming approval to a 3-for-1 stock
split at today's meeting. GE stock closed Tuesday at an all-time
high of $165.75 a share.
</P>
<P>
   GE shares were off 56\ cents a share at $165.43} in midday
trading today on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 retirees handed out fliers outside today's
shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in two days angry workers have gone to
shareholders to try to bend management of their company's pension
plan.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, IBM workers got more support than they expected, but
fell short in a bid to make the company offer its traditional
pension plan to all workers. The computer maker converted thousands
of workers' pensions to a cash-balance plan, which critics say
hurts loyal employees who spend their entire careers at one
company. IBM employees who are at least 40 years old with at least
10 years' service are given a choice.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking early retirement seven years ago when his job was
made obsolete, Lockett said, he has received about $50 in pension
increases. He said most GE pensions average between $700 and $800
per month.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not beggars,'' Lockett, a machine repairman who served
37 years at GE, said at a rally Tuesday. ''We don't want handouts.
... What we want is a little respect.''
</P>
<P>
   A GE spokesman said the company has given retirees six pension
increases in 20 years, which he said was more than most of its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our pensions are very competitive with other companies,''
spokesman Gary Sheffer said. ''That's one of the reasons people
like to come to work for GE.''
</P>
<P>
   But Karen Friedman, a spokeswoman for the Washington, D.C.-based
Pension Rights Center, said GE uses its pension surplus to
artificially boost earnings, while some retiree pensions are lower
than $400 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say to GE, 'You have a moral obligation to your
shareholders and your workers and retirees not just to do the
minimum or what you can get away with, but to do what's right. GE
should be a light onto corporate America, a leader,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman came to Richmond from Cleveland, Ohio, where she helped
IBM workers with their pension case.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: General Electric: http://www.ge.com
</P>
<P>
   Pension Rights Center: http://www.aoa.dhhs.gov/aoa/dir/210.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
