<HEADLINE> Cartoons Go Three-Dimensional  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN, AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A parade of cartoon stars is going
three-dimensional as Hollywood mines the animated world for
live-action movies starring X-men, the Grinch, Rocky and
Bullwinkle, and the Flintstones.
</P>
<P>
   From Superman to Batman, Popeye to Dick Tracy, movie studios
have had a long history of transforming comic-book or cartoon
characters into flesh and blood. The tradition continues Friday
with a second live-action movie about the prehistoric folks of
Bedrock.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Flintstones in Viva Rock Vegas'' recounts the early
romance of Fred and Wilma and Barney and Betty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a huge fan of the cartoon when I was kid,'' said Stephen
Baldwin, who plays Barney Rubble in ''The Flintstones'' flick.
''It's kind of coincidental because Barney was my favorite
character, because he was seemingly the dopey guy who usually had
the solution or answer in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie co-stars Mark Addy as Fred, Kristen Johnston as Wilma,
Jane Krakowski as Betty and Joan Collins as Fred's mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   This summer brings ''The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle,''
featuring computer-generated versions of the cartoon moose and
flying squirrel. Co-starring as their real-life nemeses are Robert
De Niro as Fearless Leader, Jason Alexander as Boris Badenov and
Rene Russo as Natasha.
</P>
<P>
   ''These characters are part of our pop culture,'' said ''Rocky
and Bullwinkle'' director Des McAnuff. ''It's great to revisit
them, and for people with fond memories of the characters, you
hopefully want to spend 90 minutes with them in a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Also coming this summer is ''X-men,'' featuring living,
breathing versions of the comic-book world's favorite mutants.
</P>
<P>
   Coming for the holidays late this year are Jim Carrey in ''Dr.
Seuss' How the Grinch Stole Christmas,'' directed by Ron Howard,
and ''102 Dalmatians,'' the second live-action flick based on
Disney's animated classic.
</P>
<P>
   In the works over the next few years are live-action takes on
other Marvel comics, including Spider-man and the Incredible Hulk.
Also planned is a live-action movie of Josie and the Pussycats,
based on the comic-book and cartoon series about an all-girl rock
band.
</P>
<P>
   Adaptations of two-dimensional characters pose a challenge for
filmmakers, who must try to satisfy fiercely loyal fans of the
originals while fleshing out the material for wider audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we do our jobs right, audiences will love these characters
not just as cartoon characters but as people,'' said Brian Levant,
who directed the new Flintstones movie and its 1994 predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has been abuzz with chat and pre-emptive carping
about ''X-men,'' which has nearly 40 years of comic-book devotion
to cope with. Many X-men fans seem pleased with much of the
casting, particularly Patrick Stewart and Ian McKellen as lead
mutants Professor X and Magneto, but devotees are critical of how
some characters look in the movie's trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is it me, or does Magneto's helmet look too small? Like he's a
pinhead,'' one fan said on an ''X-men'' message board. ''I think
this movie is going to be a BIG disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian McKellen, who plays Magneto, has his own ''X-men'' site
where he provides information about the film, dispels rumors and
offers reassurances that the movie will adhere to the X-men spirit
despite a modern, more realistic look to the costumes than the
campy comic-book outfits.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's appropriate on the page isn't necessarily appropriate
in a moving picture,'' McKellen said. ''I caution people to wait
and see the movie. If they don't like it, they should go make their
own movie, or just stay with the original comic.''
</P>
<P>
   While he loved immersing himself in the ''X-men'' world,
director Bryan Singer said he is anxious for a project with fewer
fan preconceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're very passionate people,'' Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''X-men'' fans should take heart in knowing the movie is being
made by devotees of the comic books themselves, said Avi Arad,
chief executive of Marvel Studios, which is working with Hollywood
producers on other films based on Marvel characters.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a whole new generation of filmmakers, geeks like us
who grew up on these universes,'' Arad said. ''They have the talent
and clout to bring these characters to life in ways they've dreamed
about for a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   ''Flintstones'' movie site: http://www.vivarockvegas.com
</P>
<P>
   ''Rocky and Bullwinkle'' movie site:
http://rockyandbullwinkle.com
</P>
<P>
   ''X-men'' movie site: http://www.x-men-the-movie.com
</P>
<P>
   Ian McKellen site: http://www.mckellen.com/cinema/xmen/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
