<HEADLINE> Taxpayers' Electronic Filing Rises  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON, AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taxpayers dramatically increased their use of
computers, credit cards and direct bank deposits during this year's
income tax filing season, in which 35 million returns were filed
electronically with the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   But getting through on the telephone to the IRS remained a
problem. Almost four in 10 calls went unanswered even though the
lines were open 24 hours, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics released Wednesday by the IRS show that people are
growing increasingly comfortable with doing their own taxes on home
computers. The number of self-prepared electronic returns received
as of last Friday doubled to more than 4.9 million compared with
the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The 35 million electronic returns -- most of them filed by
professional preparers -- was 1.4 million more than the IRS had
expected and represented a 20 percent increase over last year. The
number of electronically filed returns now makes up 27 percent of
the total.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are more used to computers,'' IRS Commissioner Charles
Rossotti said. ''Secondly, the software is getting very good. It's
not just the filing, it's a better way to prepare the tax return.''
</P>
<P>
   Working toward a goal of 80 percent electronic filing by 2007,
the IRS has been aggressively promoting the advantages, such as
fewer mistakes and much faster processing of refunds. Rossotti said
the agency will continue expanding the number of taxpayers who can
use identification numbers in place of the signature form that is
still required for most who file electronically.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a little thing but it is still a barrier,'' Rossotti
said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, about 7 million taxpayers used the electronic
signature option, including 1.4 million who did their own returns.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has asked Congress to approve a $10 tax credit
for people who file electronically, which would cover the cost of
most electronic filing services. The IRS is also working with
private industry on ways to allow people to prepare and file their
taxes on the Internet at no cost, Rossotti said.
</P>
<P>
   About 186,000 taxpayers have charged $536 million in taxes on
their American Express, Mastercard and Discover cards so far this
year. Both are huge increases over 1999, when about $184 million
was charged on credit cards in the first year of the program.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 200 percent increase in the number of people who
paid taxes through direct debits from bank accounts and 25 percent
more people had their refunds deposited directly, the IRS reported.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this growth, an older piece of technology remained a
problem for the IRS. About 65 percent of all telephone calls have
gotten through so far this year, up from last year's dismal 50
percent level but far from adequate, Rossotti said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were better than we expected to be. But we still have a
long ways to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although technology and better use of existing staff will
improve things, Rossotti wants Congress to approve a 9.5 percent
budget increase that will enable the IRS to hire about 2,000 more
employees for customer service and to reverse a steep slide in
enforcement. In both cases, he said, technology will never fully
replace people.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people who are trying to pay, we want them to get through
and get the help they need,'' Rossotti said. ''If they don't want
to pay, we don't want them to be able to shift the tax burden onto
their neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: IRS: http://www.irs.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1437 </TRAILER>
