<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts: Medical Privacy Laws Needed  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Proposed federal regulations to assure the
privacy of medical records are inadequate in some respects,
excessive in others, health care officials said Wednesday in urging
Congress to come up with comprehensive privacy legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Rules proposed last November by Health and Human Services
Secretary Donna Shalala fall short in terms of coverage and
enforcement, said Janlori Goldman, director of the Health Privacy
Project at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congress should act swiftly to fill these gaps,'' she said at
a hearing of the Senate health committee.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala came out with the rules after Congress failed to meet a
self-imposed August 1999, deadline to enact a law ensuring that a
person's medical records remain confidential and are not subject to
abuse by marketers or employers.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, to be finalized later this year and go into effect in
2002, limit disclosure of medical information to the ''minimum
necessary,'' give patients the right to see their medical records,
require health care providers to write privacy contracts with their
business partners, and preempt weaker state privacy rules.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary, said Janet Heinrich of the General Accounting
Office, the investigative wing of Congress, ''has attempted to fill
an otherwise significant gap in privacy protection.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said a GAO study of public comment on the proposed rules
revealed that while there is considerable support for the aims of
the rules, there are also concerns that they could be too costly
and in some cases impede good health care.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joanna Horobin, speaking for the Biotechnology Industry
Organization, said too many restrictions on access to important
data ''will severely hurt medical research.''
</P>
<P>
   John Houston of the American Hospital Association said his group
was ''gravely concerned'' that Shalala had exceeded her authority
in drawing up the rules. He said the standards on ''minimum
necessary'' disclosure were ''at odds with good medical practice
and potentially very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kahn III, president of the Health Insurance Association
of America, warned that the standards ''would have a chilling
effect on detecting and reporting (medical) errors.''
</P>
<P>
   Several witnesses complained of the cost and complexity of
determining whether state or federal rules prevail. ''One of the
primary reasons for supporting federal confidentiality legislation
is that care is delivered across state boundaries,'' Houston said.
</P>
<P>
   Others noted that Shalala was limited in what she could impose
without congressional action. The rules cover only health care
providers, health plans and clearinghouses and apply only to
electronic data, not the paper records that make up most health
information.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congressional action would protect all health information,
however it is transmitted and wherever it exists,'' said Sen.
Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts, Democrat on the committee chaired
by Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords, Kennedy and others were close last year to reaching a
compromise medical privacy bill. But they were unable to resolve
differences on two issues -- the right to sue over improper use of
records and the privacy of teen-agers who have abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Health Privacy Project: http://www.healthprivacy.org
</P>
<P>
   American Hospital Association
testimony:http://www.aha.org/ar/testimony4-26-00.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1511 </TRAILER>
