<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pilot Flies Open Cockpit To N. Pole  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER ANDES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gus McLeod knows cold better than most anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur aviator from suburban Maryland made history April 17
as the first pilot ever to fly to the North Pole in an open cockpit
plane.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was cold beyond caring,'' McLeod, 45, said Wednesday at a
news conference at the National Geographic Society, a sponsor of
the two-week, 3,500-mile journey.
</P>
<P>
   He even tried an electric suit -- and turned it up full blast --
to battle temperatures that for days hovered at 15 degrees below
zero. The suit left a silver-dollar-sized 3rd degree burn in his
stomach that he did not even feel.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't get any warmer, and that burning part wasn't good,''
McLeod said.
</P>
<P>
   So why did he do it? ''A personal challenge,'' he said. McLeod
said he's a longtime admirer of Roscoe Turner and other early
aviation pioneers. ''I always like to feel I was part of that
club,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even his craft, a 1939 Boeing Stearman biplane, heralded from
the era of his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The cockpit was a bit tight for the six-feet-one-inch, 285-pound
aviator. McLeod said his chest was just six inches from the rim of
the cockpit, and that all he could move -- sometimes during six
hours of flight -- were his arms and ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Between the tight fit and extreme cold, ''the suffering was
unimaginable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod was in the plane by himself but not completely alone. A
crew from National Geographic followed in a ''chase plane'' and got
the trip on film. It airs June 4 as part of the Explorer series.
</P>
<P>
   ''He squeezed this massive frame into what looked like a little,
toy airplane with his head popping out of the cockpit,'' said show
Producer Lori Butterfield. She said she teased him about not having
any blood in his veins, to which he confirmed he circulates
antifreeze.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod weathered a tough stretch between Pickle Lake, Ontario,
and Churchill, Manitoba, when engine gaskets blew, spilling oil
down the side of his craft. Temperatures plunged, visibility was
lost and McLeod and his craft had to rest in Churchill for a few
days to wait for spare engine parts.
</P>
<P>
   A film clip showed McLeod landing April 16 in Eureka, Nunavut,
with a hearty, ''Hey, Eureka, glad to meet ya!'' And again moments
after the April 17 touch down at his final destination. ''I made
it,'' he said in a satellite call to his wife, Mary.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod left two items dear to him at the Pole. One is an urn
bearing the ashes of his friend, Doug Duff, who spoke of making the
trip to the Pole for years, right up until his death in a 1998
plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   He also left his aircraft, which he hopes to have recovered.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod said the engine broke for about the fourth and final time
during the trip and could not be repaired. It's at 86 degrees north
and 93 degrees west, and drifting.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's headed for Norway at 12 miles a day,'' McLeod said.
''That plane loves to travel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1520 </TRAILER>
