<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dobbs, CNN Say They Won't Meet Again  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Don't look for any return engagement at CNN for
former ''Moneyline'' anchor Lou Dobbs.
</P>
<P>
   The financial journalist and CNN on Wednesday both emphatically
denied speculation that Dobbs, who left the network last year for
an Internet venture, would be going back to CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal and New York Daily News reported that
CNN founder Ted Turner had approached Dobbs about returning as an
anchor. Since Dobbs left, CNN's nightly business wrapup has lost
ground in the ratings to CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Although a no-compete clause has prevented Dobbs from anchoring
another TV show, he is a partner with NBC in a monthly financial
newsletter and syndicated radio show. NBC has also acquired a
minority stake in the Web site devoted to outer space that Dobbs
has started, and there is speculation he may eventually work for
CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs confirmed his conversations with Turner. He talked about
it Wednesday on the Don Imus radio show, which is simulcast on
MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this were just between Ted and me,'' he probably wouldn't
have left CNN, Dobbs said. Dobbs had been feuding with Rick Kaplan,
CNN USA president, before his exit.
</P>
<P>
   Imus pointed out that NBC had ''put up a lot of money'' for
Dobbs' Internet venture.
</P>
<P>
   ''It wouldn't look good for you to stick it to NBC by going back
with Ted, would it?'' Imus asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wouldn't, as put so eloquently, stick it to NBC, Don,''
Dobbs replied. ''I'm very happy with my partners at NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   He told Imus he would not return to CNN.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN spokeswoman said Dobbs and Turner are friends who talk
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no plans for Lou Dobbs to return to CNN,'' said Sue
Binford of CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Under his CNN contract, Dobbs cannot anchor another television
show until 2002. He said he cannot predict if he will want to get
back into TV then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
