<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore: Drug Profits 'Out of Line'  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Al Gore blamed pharmaceutical
companies Wednesday for profits that are ''way out of line'' and
plugged his own drug-payment plan with assists from President
Clinton at the White House and senior citizen Shirley Kindle at a
drugstore photo-op.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigning vice president, the Democrats' presumptive
presidential nominee, put Republican rival George W. Bush and the
drug companies at the center of his argument for expanding Medicare
coverage to include prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Profits are good for encouraging investors, Gore said, but drug
companies are ''going far beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They're going to the point that the margins are way out of
line with what most other industries and most other lines of
business believe is normal and adequate. They're using the market
power to dictate prices that are way above what competition would
set them at.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Kindle, 65, of Ansonia, spoke to a small assembly in
the bingo room of South End Senior Center.
</P>
<P>
   Kindle, who had already bought her April supply of medications,
accompanied Gore earlier to Pelton's family drugstore for what he
called ''an illustration'' for invited news cameras: pharmacist Hal
Schoen lining up the woman's 12 different prescriptions and ringing
up the total of $506.34.
</P>
<P>
   ''Which is more than I get from Social Security,'' Kindle said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who said later she never shops at the photogenic
Pelton's, told Gore her husband makes a little too much money for
her to qualify for a state prescription-drug program.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was advised if they got divorced she'd be eligible for
some low-income assistance, but she said after 35 years she's
really not ready to give him up,'' Gore chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokesman Chris Lehane said later the Kindles' monthly
income of $1,800 also would make them ineligible for aid under a
House Republican plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed adding a Medicare prescription drug benefit
and letting uninsured Americans 55 to 65 buy into Medicare
coverage. His drug plan would offer free coverage for low-income
recipients, catastrophic coverage for all and an optional
cost-sharing benefit for others with premiums of $44 a month when
phased in.
</P>
<P>
   By design, Gore's appearances Wednesday coincided with the
release of an advocacy group's findings that prices for drugs most
commonly used by senior citizens jumped higher than the rate of
inflation last year, with some doubling in price.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton and congressional Democrats cited
the Families USA study as proof that people need help.
</P>
<P>
   ''Seniors living on fixed incomes simply can't cope with these
kinds of price increases forever,'' Clinton said. ''That's why we
should take action to help them, and do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican House Speaker Dennis Hastert said Clinton's comments
indicated ''he is clearly misinformed about our fair and
responsible plan that both strengthens Medicare and provides
prescription drug coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration and GOP leaders in the House are locked in a
dispute over the size and scope of the action Congress should take.
</P>
<P>
   At the senior center, Gore warned anew against Bush's tax-cut
and spending proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ''He calls it compassionate conservatism, but it's really casino
economics. He wants us to roll the dice on an unaffordable tax
scheme that gives the most to those who need it the least,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer countered that Bush would dedicate
nearly half of his five-year budget to ''strengthen and save Social
Security and Medicare, provide a prescription drug benefit and work
in a bipartisan manner to enact much-needed reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Fleischer, ''If Al Gore is wondering why he has a problem
with credibility, his partisan response to Medicare reform provides
yet another reason why.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush recommends keeping Medicare as a federal commitment but
says there should be more choice and more private alternatives for
the elderly. He supports an unspecified drug benefit and subsidies
to help the poorest of the elderly afford supplementary or
alternative coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to Washington, Gore took questions from
reporters, including the customary question about whether some
local Democrat -- this time Connecticut Sen. Joseph Lieberman --
might be considered as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even if it were at a stage where I could, if I wanted to, give
you the names on a long list, I wouldn't do it because I don't
think it's fair to people who would end up on that list,'' Gore
said, adding praise for Lieberman and fellow Connecticut Sen.
Christopher Dodd as ''outstanding individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also was asked whether, given Bush's repeated criticism
that he will say anything to get elected, he worries he might have
a ''credibility problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he has a repetition problem,'' Gore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1540 </TRAILER>
