<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockheed Vows To Beat Estimates  </HEADLINE>
By ARLENE LEVINSON, AP National Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Lockheed Martin Corp. expects to exceed
diminished earnings estimates for this year with help from
streamlining and exports of its F-16 fighter, chief executive Vance
Coffman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's No. 1 defense contractor forecast annual earnings
of $1.05 a share. Last fall, as a series of rocket launch failures
weakened its business, Lockheed had slashed earnings estimates for
2000 to $1 a share from $2.15.
</P>
<P>
   With Lockheed's $9 billion-plus in orders to make more than 200
F-16s for the United Arab Emirates, Israel, Greece and Egypt,
Coffman said, the F-16 ''has had a terrific run for new business.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffman, chairman and chief executive of the Bethesda, Md.-based
maker of rockets, satellites and fighter jets, discussed the
prospects of Lockheed in a presentation at an aerospace symposium
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The event hosted by Aviation Week &AMP; Space Technology magazine
and Credit Suisse/First Boston was attended by some 300 financial
analysts, investment bankers and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Coffman also repeated previous remarks that the Defense
Department may divide a $200 billion order for the Joint Strike
Fighter between Lockheed and rival bidder Boeing Co.
</P>
<P>
   The order for about 3,000 of the jet fighter now in development
is the biggest weapons program under way anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The company later reiterated Lockheed was sticking to its
''winner-take-all'' bid strategy toward getting the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The planes are to replace the Air Force's F-16 and A-10 planes
and the Marine Corps' AV-8Bs and F/A-18s. The government has said
it will decide next year who gets the contract, with the first
aircraft to be delivered in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Also in on the program are Britain, a financial partner planning
to buy some of the jets, and Turkey as a development partner.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Wednesday afternoon on the New York Stock Exchange,
Lockheed was down almost 6 percent, or by $1.50, at $24.06\ a
share.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
