<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murder of U.K. Burgler Stirs Debate  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BARR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The maxim that a man's home is his castle is being
tested by the case of a farmer sentenced to life in prison for
murdering a burglar in his home.
</P>
<P>
   The bloody confrontation at Tony Martin's shabby Victorian
farmhouse has highlighted public concerns about crime and the
ability of police to protect people in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, tabloid newspapers and some politicians have rallied
to defend Martin, who shot two unarmed intruders with a shotgun.
His case has been on front pages repeatedly since he was convicted
last week of murdering 16-year-old Fred Barras, whom he shot in the
back, and wounding Brendon Fearon with intent to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Fearon, 30, and Darren Bark, 33, who waited outside the home,
were both convicted of conspiring to burglarize Martin's home and
sentenced to three years and 30 months, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Barras had been in court 28 times for various offenses, Fearon
35 times and Bark 52 times.
</P>
<P>
   ''What has happened to our courts system when career burglars
and muggers get a few dozen hours community service, or a couple of
months in prison if they're unlucky, while people defending their
homes against the very same criminals risk long prison sentences?''
Conservative Party leader William Hague said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hague called for a change in the law to create ''a strong
presumption that ... the state will be on the side of people who
protect their homes and their families against criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not spell out how he would change the law on
self-defense, which says that lethal violence is permissible to
fend off a violent attack, provided the defender had taken
reasonable steps to avoid violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''What does Mr. Hague suggest?'' asked Sir Michael Davies, a
former High Court judge who opposes any change in the law. ''Are
people going to be encouraged to have guns or an electric fence
with killing power around their back garden, to have a pair of
man-eating tigers tied up to be released if there is a burglar
about?''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors described Martin, who came to court each day with a
teddy bear, as an eccentric man with a deep fear of burglars.
</P>
<P>
   ''He fired at Barras and Fearon not in self-defense but in
accordance with his professed view that the only way to stop
thieves was to shoot them,'' prosecuting attorney Rosamund
Horwood-Smart said.
</P>
<P>
   According to testimony in the trial, Martin lived alone near the
village of Emneth, 100 miles north of London, in a house
illuminated by a single 15-watt bulb on each floor, and slept fully
clothed with his pump-action shotgun close by.
</P>
<P>
   His three Rottweilers -- Otto, Bruno and Daniel -- patrolled
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Shotguns are common in the countryside, but Martin's certificate
to own one was revoked in 1994 after he shot at the car of a man
caught gathering apples in his orchard.
</P>
<P>
   After the Aug. 20 killing, some 300 people jammed the village
hall for a meeting about crime, many complaining about the length
of time it took for police to respond to calls.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, eel-catcher John Spalton said he had seen
Fearon bleeding at the side of the road but did not stop because of
his fear of crime in the area. ''You don't stop unless it is
somebody you know,'' Spalton said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin plans to appeal the murder conviction. He can also apply
for early release in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Comment in many newspapers was sympathetic to Martin, with
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Martin may have shot the boy in the back -- he may well have
deserved to be punished -- but did he deserve a life sentence?''
said The Sun.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Mail also thought Martin went too far, but said: ''In
hamlets and remote farmhouses all over the country, there are
countless people who today wonder how they would have respond in
such circumstances. What has been so glaringly exposed in this
awful case is the way whole swathes of rural Britain have been all
but abandoned by the forces of law and order.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
