<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 34; Dow Down 151  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower today as the latest
sign of economic growth brought interest rate worries to the
foreground for the first time this week. Technology stocks held up
better than the broad market.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq composite was down 34.44 to 3,676.79.
</P>
<P>
   Other stock indicators were lower. The Dow Jones industrial
average was down 151.40 at 10,973.42 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 10.77 at 1,466.37.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Dow and the Nasdaq each rose more than 200
points, many investors retreated to the sidelines, debating their
next moves. The market was rattled after the Commerce Department
reported orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket manufactured goods
rose in March for the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
   After two straight months of declines, orders for durable goods
-- items expected to last at least three years -- rose 2.6 percent
last month to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $215.2 billion,
the government said.
</P>
<P>
   The report revived fears that the Federal Reserve will continue
raising interest rates in an effort to force a slowdown of the
economy. The Fed has raised interest rates five times since last
June, and many economists expect the Fed to bump up rates again on
May 16.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Fed is looking for signs of moderation, they won't find
it'' in the durable goods report, said David Orr, chief economist
at First Union Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors were looking ahead to Thursday, when the
government will release first-quarter gross domestic product
figures. Many analysts expect the economy grew at a 6 percent rate
-- too fast for the Fed's comfort, but not as brisk as the 7.3
percent rate posted in the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The government will also release the latest employment cost
index -- a gauge of wage pressures which Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan
considers a crucial barometer of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a latent fear that if those numbers are stronger than
expected, it will force the Fed to be aggressive about raising
rates,'' said John Shaughnessy, chief investment strategist at
Advest Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Worries about rising interest rates hurt financial services
stocks, which typically suffer when higher rates crimp lending
volume. Citigroup fell 2 to 62 1/2 and J.P. Morgan fell 2 1/4 to
135 11/16, weighing heavily on the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate earnings reports provided the only real spark in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer edged up 3/8 to 29 7/8. Late Tuesday, the
computer maker reported that excluding gains in its investment
portfolio, first-quarter net income and revenues were virtually
unchanged from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Online auctioneer eBay gave up early gains and was down 1 7/8 to
151 11/16. The company's first-quarter operating results exceeded
Wall Street expectations as the amount of merchandise sold on its
site surpassed $1 billion for the first time. Also, eBay announced
plans to split its stock 2-for-1.
</P>
<P>
   A wide range of technology stocks were higher today. Internet
retail powerhouse Amazon.com gained 1 1/2 to 53 15/16 and Broadcom,
a maker of silicon semiconductors, rose 3 7/8 to 164 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a very slender margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 789.69 million
shares, behind Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 1.43 to 487.60.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
