<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plunging Euro Takes Financial Toll  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE STANLEY, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Although the euro stabilized Wednesday after
sinking to a new low against the dollar, its weakness poses a
challenge not only to the European Central Bank but also to
economies and individuals outside the zone of 11 countries that use
the single currency.
</P>
<P>
   Among its casualties are British manufacturers, who are losing
sales as they try to compete against goods priced in chronically
weak euros.
</P>
<P>
   Americans investing in shares of European companies also are
taking a beating. Swelling regional stock valuations look a lot
less impressive once those shares are converted from euros into
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has plunged almost 23 percent since January 1999, when
it was launched amid hopes that it would one day rival the dollar
as a global reserve currency.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the euro fell to a record low of 91.62 cents during
trading in New York. It staged a modest rally on Wednesday, rising
to 92.33 cents in late trading in New York.
</P>
<P>
   This chronic weakness leaves the European Central Bank in an
unenviable position when it decides Thursday whether to raise a key
interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   If the ECB boosts the lending rate from its current level of 3.5
percent, it risks choking off the economic recovery under way in
many parts of Europe and exacerbating the region's already high
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   But if the bank leaves the rate unchanged, its inaction could
further weaken confidence in the currency and trigger a global
selloff of euros.
</P>
<P>
   The only alternative, some economists said, is for the bank to
overcome its reticence about intervening directly in currency
markets to try to prop up the sagging euro.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is almost imperative,'' said Neil Parker, chief economist
at the Royal Bank of Scotland. ''You need the ECB to step in and
stop the decline before it gets out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts blame much of the euro's decline on the charms of the
glittering U.S. economy, which has attracted money from Europe that
investors might otherwise have put into European stocks. This
outflow of funds has caused the dollar to strengthen and has
undermined the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's decline also has proven to be a boon to tourists
visiting from the United States who are able to buy more with their
dollars when they exchange them.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. boom highlights structural problems, such as inflexible
labor markets, that are constraining growth in Europe, said Lee
Ferridge, chief currency strategist at Rabobank in London.
</P>
<P>
   Ferridge predicted that the euro will resume its slide and drop
to 90 cents in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, leader of the euro-zone's
largest economy, said he expects the currency to strengthen in the
near future, thanks to regional economic growth and low inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I advise a little more calm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The weak currency has been particularly worrisome to British
companies that export to continental Europe or compete with imports
priced in euros.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederation of British Industry released a quarterly
survey Wednesday showing that exports among Britain's manufacturers
have fallen, with more companies recording a downturn in overseas
orders.
</P>
<P>
   ''These results are generally depressing and send some ominous
signals. They suggest that the hoped-for recovery has stalled and
that manufacturing is on the brink of slipping back into decline,''
the survey quoted Nick Reilly, chairman and managing director of
Vauxhall Motors, as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The British government has opted for now to keep the pound
rather than join the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about the euro extends across the Atlantic, where
private and institutional investors have tried to cash in on
Europe's gradual recovery by buying shares of Siemens AG, Vodfafone
AirTouch PLC and other standout companies.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Xetra Dax index of blue-chip shares listed on the
Frankfurt stock exchange has increased by 7.8 percent since the
start of the year. The Paris CAC 40 stock index has risen 4.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, the euro has plunged 7.8 percent against the dollar
during this same period. For Americans, that decline has offset
much of the nominal appreciation in European stock valuations.
</P>
<P>
   After euro-denominated shares are converted into dollars, the
Xetra Dax index showed no increase for the year, while the Paris
CAC 40 actually lost 2.9 percent of its value in dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1609 </TRAILER>
