<HEADLINE> Japan Gov. Defies Environmentalists  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The governor of Japan's southernmost island gave
the go-ahead Wednesday on plans to build an airport despite
protests from environmentalists concerned about nearby coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns to protect the reefs and complaints from some
landowners have so far delayed plans for the new airport on the
southern part of Ishigaki Island in Okinawa, about 1,000 miles
southwest of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Keiichi Inamine promised to make sure that construction of
the airport does not harm nature, said Tomohiro Maekawa, an
Okinawan official. Steps will be taken to prevent soil drainage
into the sea during the construction, which will cost about $415.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Okinawan government has pushed to build the new airport for
more than two decades because Ishigaki's current airport does not
have the capacity to handle the large number of visitors. About 1.3
million passengers arrive every year.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental assessment and other measures are expected to take
about three years, with six to seven more years needed for the
construction, Maekawa said.
</P>
<P>
   On April 17, construction began on a new runway at Tokyo's main
international airport that had been held up for more than three
decades by farmers who refused to give up their land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
