<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vermont Gov. Signs Gay Union Bill  </HEADLINE>
By ROSS SNEYD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- Gov. Howard Dean signed a
first-in-the-nation law Wednesday granting gay couples nearly all
of the benefits of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is a courageous and powerful statement about who we
are in the state of Vermont,'' the Democrat said. ''I also believe
that this legislation speaks to the heart of this state, and
certainly to my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation creating marriage-like ''civil unions'' reached
the governor's desk shortly before lunch time, just a day after the
House gave its final approval. And by the time of a 2 p.m. news
conference, he had already signed it out of view of TV cameras,
photographers and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Dean said he signed the bill privately because he did not want
the ceremony to be a triumphal party by supporters of the law.
Instead, he said, it was time for the state to begin healing.
</P>
<P>
   ''In politics, bill-signings are triumphal,'' he said. ''They
represent overcoming of one side over another. These celebrations,
as the subject of the matter of the bill, will be private.''
</P>
<P>
   The law will allow gay couples to form civil unions beginning
July 1. That will entitle them to all of the 300 or so rights and
responsibilities available to married couples under Vermont law in
such areas as taxes, inheritance and medical decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   Other states will probably not recognize Vermont civil unions,
and such status will not entitle gay couples to any the benefits
available to married couples under federal law in areas such as
taxes and immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, no state has gone further than Vermont is giving
gay couples something approximating marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The bill came about after the Vermont Supreme Court unanimously
ruled in December that gay couples were being unconstitutionally
denied the benefits of marriage. The court left it up to the
Legislature time to decide whether to let gays marry or to create
some kind of domestic partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation passed after strong debate in which opponents
argued that homosexuality is ''against natural law.'' Opponents
have warned that they will make their anger known at the polls in
November when members of the Legislature are up for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, gay couples will be able to go to their town
clerks for licenses and have their unions certified by a judge or
member of the clergy. Breakups will be handled in Family Court,
just as divorces are, although they will be called dissolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers deeply involved in the issue said they were
disappointed there was no bill-signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the story needs to be that gay and lesbian couples in
Vermont had a historical day,'' said Democratic Rep. William
Lippert, the Legislature's only openly gay member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1627 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge restores Essenberg as chairman of Independence Party  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A judge Wednesday reinstated Jack Essenberg
as chairman of the state Independence Party, ruling that insurgents
improperly removed him from the post in February.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Bernard Malone Jr.'s ruling was the
latest twist in intraparty squabbling among Independence members.
</P>
<P>
   Malone decided both the Independence Party's rules and Robert's
Rules of Order indicate that only Essenberg, as chairman, had the
authority to set the agenda during special meetings of the party's
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the judge said Essenberg was within his authority to
refuse to place his own removal on the agenda of a stormy Feb. 4
meeting which resulted in his ouster by opponents after Essenberg
had stormed out. Frank MacKay of North Babylon was voted in as the
Independence Party's new chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Also fueling the power struggle is a rivalry between factions of
the Independence Party, which is New York state's version of the
national Reform Party. One faction was led by Essenberg and the
other by leftist activist Lenora Fulani.
</P>
<P>
   Fulani's unconventional backing of conservative Pat Buchanan for
the party's presidential nomination also brought her in opposition
to Essenberg, who favored Donald Trump as the party's presidential
standardbearer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their attempt to remove two-thirds of the executive committee
for disloyalty and corruption was a joke because it's not true,''
Essenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed his ouster on Fulani's attempt to seize control of the
party leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Malone ordered the other executive committee office holders
under Essenberg's chairmanship to also get their posts back
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Stewart, a Fulani ally, said Wednesday's ruling will be
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision is an outrage,'' Stewart said. ''It undermines
the democratic process. It shows just how much the electoral
arrangement in New York, including the courts, is opposed to the
right of recall.''
</P>
<P>
   MacKay is scheduled to moderate a forum Saturday in Buffalo to
hear from candidates interested in the Independence Party's
nomination for U.S. Senate. MacKay said he expects to be regarded
as the rightful party chairman by the state committee at that
event.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who do you think it is going to recognize, Essenberg?'' MacKay
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also predicted that Malone's ruling will be ''laughed out''
of the Appellate Division of state Supreme Court on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a Republican, has
confirmed he will be at the Buffalo forum and is seeking the
party's nomination while Democratic first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton has been noncommittal.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Salamanca Wednesday, Clinton acknowledged she was
wary of running on a line on the New York ballot which Buchanan
would head as a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a problem with Mr. Buchanan,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, sources also say Clinton is concerned about being
backed by a party Fulani plays a major role in.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Wednesday he also remains critical about Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I continue to have all the same objections to him and problems
with him and problems with his background,'' Giuliani said at a
City Hall news conference.
</P>
<P>
   If Buchanan heads the Independence Party ticket in New York,
Giuliani said, ''I'll have to make a decision about'' accepting the
party's nomination for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, MacKay said attendance at the Buffalo event
Saturday was a must for any candidate seeking the Independence
nomination. But Essenberg said he was not regarding the forum that
way.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's a do or die,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party backing can be valuable to candidates running for
statewide office in New York since the state allows major party
candidates to also run on third-party ballot lines. The
Independence Party line helped Democrat Charles Schumer defeat
Republican incumbent Sen. Alfonse D'Amato in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, the Independence Party's state committee will have
to meet to consider the party's Senate nomination. It is unclear
whether the leadership of the party will also be sorted out by then
or whether litigation will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Essenberg, from Highland Lake, had failed in federal court to
get his chairman's post back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
