<HEADLINE> Eastman School of Music gets $1 million from stock-savvy pianoteacher  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A frugal piano teacher with a talent for
investing in the stock market is giving away her third $1 million
gift -- this time to the Eastman School of Music where she studied
on a scholarship in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Murray Trebert, 88, equates her success in accumulating
money with her musical talents. ''I use my eyes, I use my memory
and I'm not slow -- when I want to do anything, I don't fuss
around,'' she said with a hearty chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Yet holding onto the riches she has built up since the 1960s has
never interested her, so investing it back into the arts comes
easily.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just don't like money. Why, I don't know!'' she said. ''I
guess being in music from a tender young age, that was my love.
Everything was the music. The value of music is important, not
money. My mother used to say, 'Oh, that's only filthy lucre.'''
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of her gift to the Eastman School will provide
annual scholarship assistance to graduate and undergraduate
students. The remainder goes to the school's Sibley Music Library,
one of the world's largest academic music libraries.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Trebert has given $1 million to the Hochstein
School of Music, where she taught piano, and another $1 million to
the Al Sigl Center, a partnership of agencies that help people with
disabilities. She also has set aside two $100,000 scholarships at
the acclaimed Eastman School, begun by Kodak founder George Eastman
in 1921.
</P>
<P>
   From age 8 to 10, Trebert benefited from annual music
scholarships. ''They were little scholarships, but it's the
thought, just the encouragement, that counts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking her modest upbringing -- her father died when she was 10
-- Trebert recalled many times not being able to afford an ice cream
cone or spare a dime to ride a street car.
</P>
<P>
   Among the valuable lessons of childhood -- and from learning the
piano -- were persistence and patience. ''You have to be awful
patient with the stock market,'' she said, adding that
''thriftiness and investing ability'' also play a big part.
</P>
<P>
   She began playing the stock market after her husband, William, a
lawyer, died in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want to be like my mother, cry all over the house and
moan and groan,'' she said. ''So I said, I'm going to sit down and
concentrate and get my mind on some of these companies. I want to
know all about them, their earnings and stuff. So I did and I stuck
with it. I taught myself. I'm not the type to join a stock club --
I'd be long gone, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by her music-loving mother, Trebert earned a master's
degree in musicology at Eastman in 1941, then taught at Western
Maryland College and worked as an organist. After marrying, she
returned to her hometown in the 1950s and taught music history at
the University of Rochester and piano at Hochstein. She also played
organ at several churches.
</P>
<P>
   While declining to quantify her worth, Trebert said she has not
yet given all her millions away. ''I'm going to continue to do it
just for fun,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 1633 </TRAILER>
