<HEADLINE> 4 Charged in 1998 Sweden Disco Fire  </HEADLINE>
By KIM GAMEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOTEBORG, Sweden (AP) -- Four men were charged Wednesday with
aggravated arson in a fire that swept a crowded dance hall in
western Sweden, killing 63 people and seriously injuring 50 others.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say a flammable liquid was poured over a pile of
chairs in the stairwell leading to the rented second-floor dance
hall, and at least one of the defendants set them on fire.
</P>
<P>
   The Oct. 29, 1998, fire was allegedly started after an argument
broke out with party organizers over the entrance fee, prosecutors
claimed.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were indifferent to the danger they had caused by their
actions,'' the summary of a 3,000-page judicial report said.
</P>
<P>
   The four men all denied the charge, though defense attorneys
acknowledged at least three were present at the stairwell of the
Macedonian cultural association where the fire started.
</P>
<P>
   Shoresh Kaveh, 19, Housein Arsani, 19, Mohammad Mohammadamini,
21, and Meysam Mohammadyeh, 19, all born in Iran but now
naturalized Swedes, were arrested earlier this year. Formal charges
were filed only after the investigation was completed.
</P>
<P>
   Kaveh's attorney, Goeran Bergendahl, said his client set the
chairs on fire, but ''He denies the charge of arson because he
couldn't understand that anybody would be hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Mohammadamini and Arsani said their clients were
nearby but were not involved in starting the fire.
</P>
<P>
   A conviction on charges of aggravated arson usually carries a
sentence ranging from six years to life in prison, but prosecutor
Ulf Noren said Swedish law would allow a lesser sentence because
the suspects all were under age 20 at the time of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know there are a lot of emotions involved, but I hope it
will be a fair trial,'' Noren said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial was set to begin next Wednesday at an exhibition
center in Goteborg, 300 miles southwest of the Swedish capital,
Stockholm. Authorities had to find a site large enough to
accommodate some 500 relatives of the victims and survivors.
</P>
<P>
   When the fire broke out, some 400 people were crammed into a
space suitable for about 150. The staircase where the blaze started
was also the emergency exit, leaving only one narrow staircase for
the panicked crowd to flee. Many people jumped from second-story
windows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
