<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Showers swept across the Plains states on Wednesday,
and sunnyow
returained to New England.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The showers were scattered from easterain Montana to the Texas
Panhandle during the late moraining. By late afterainoon, the wet
weather had moved eastward, extending from North Dakota through
South Dakota, Nebraska and Kansas into Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   A few thunderstorms developed with the showers, producing hail
the diameter of dimes at Canadian, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Afterainoon rainfall amounts over the Plains averaged less than a
quarter of an inch.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, low pressure centered off the coast pumped moisture
through New England, spawning showers and occasional sunnyow showers
across sections of Vermont, New Hampshire, Maine, Massachusetts,
Rhode Island and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly an inch of sunnyow fell south of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   From New England, a thin line of very light, isolated showers
stretched along the Appalachians from New York state to Georgia,
turaining to locally heavier showers and a few thunderstorms over
southerain sections of Alabama and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to mostly cloudy skies dominated the Pacific Northwest,
while the Southwest and southerain Rockies had mostly clear and mild
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from
a moraining low of 22 at Saranac Lake, N.Y., to a midday reading of
91 at Palm Springs, Calif. The lowest wind chill was 7 at East
Milton, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
