<HEADLINE> Park Service May Ban Snowmobiles  </HEADLINE>
By ELISABETH A. WRIGHT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST YELLOWSTONE, Mont. (AP) -- Randy Roberson remembers what
this bustling tourist town was like 30 years ago, before
snowmobiles started becoming the most popular wintertime way to see
Yellowstone National park.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was kind of a winter ghost town,'' the Rendezvous Rentals
owner says. ''There was no economy here. The majority of the people
moved away for the winter to follow employment opportunities. Even
business owners would close up. That was just a normal way of
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the National Park Service is ready to impose new
restrictions on recreational snowmobiling at more than two dozen of
the sites it manages. In some cases, snowmobiles may be banned
entirely by next winter.
</P>
<P>
   The agency plans to announce the details Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Snowmobiles are allowed in more than 40 Park Service sites from
Acadia National Park in Maine to California's Sequoia National Park
and numerous parks in the Northwest and Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service says a ban would significantly reduce pollution
and noise and may ease the stress on wildlife. But residents around
Yellowstone and Grand Teton national parks call it an unnecessary
threat to their way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Wanner, manager of Yellowstone Arctic-Yamaha, said the
bigger problem is the thousands of automobiles and motorhomes that
stream into the park every summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's no more a wilderness area than Carnegie Hall,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service predicts a 30 percent decline in winter
visitors because of the snowmobiling restrictions. That would cost
the 17-county region of Wyoming, Montana and Idaho $16.5 million
and about 400 jobs, according to the Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Snowmobiling has grown into a wintertime boon for the area.
About 75,000 people take snowmobiles into Yellowstone each winter,
most entering the park on the groomed route from West Yellowstone
to Old Faithful. Hotels have sprung up, tours are advertised on the
Internet, and snowmobile sales, rental or repair shops are on
almost every street.
</P>
<P>
   Snowmobiles first entered the park in 1963. Last winter, the
park had 62,531 snowmobiles and 130,564 visitors. Winter attendance
was just a small fraction of the 3.1 million visitors Yellowstone
had in all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The BlueRibbon Coalition, a group of off-road enthusiasts, is
petitioning Congress to oppose a ban. Senators from all three
Yellowstone states have promised ''vigorous opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Snowmobile supporters contend that the Park Service is allowing
too little time for the development of cleaner, quieter machines,
and that they could live with some restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service proposal would maintain groomed trails only for
snowcoaches -- vans that run on tracks instead of wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Roberson said many of his clients won't come back if
snowmobiling is banned. The winter economy makes up half of his
business, he said. He also owns two motels, rents cars and provides
bus tours.
</P>
<P>
   Marysue Costello, executive director of the West Yellowstone
Chamber of Commerce, said tourists are calling to ask if a ban
already is in place.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just tell them that's not the case. But those are the
people having to call. How about all the ones that don't?'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency has said anything short of a
snowmobile ban would violate federal air quality standards and a
1972 presidential order against off-road vehicle use that damages a
national park.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA is expected to propose national emissions standards for
snowmobiles and other off-road vehicles later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1636 </TRAILER>
