<BODY>
<HEADLINE> James Rubin Holds Last Briefing  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- James P. Rubin closed out a three-year run as
the State Department's main spokesman Wednesday in a shower of
rattles and spinning tops and gentle ribbing at his last briefing
for correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin is stepping down to help his wife, television reporter
Christiane Amanpour, take care of their infant son, Darius, in
their London home.
</P>
<P>
   From a back-row seat, Amanpour tried to elicit from her husband
a promise to take his turn at changing the baby's diapers. With
practiced diplomatic ambiguity, Rubin responded: ''I will do
whatever is necessary and appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   He wound up the lighthearted session by saying, ''It's been a
great honor to stand here and represent the United States.'' Rubin
also told reporters, ''It was a privilege to exchange with you
difficult questions, hopefully decent answers.''
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Anne Gazeau-Secret, spokeswoman for the French foreign
ministry, called Rubin's departure ''a sad day for journalists.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart surprised Rubin with a bag of
carrots, saying it was a gift from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The carrots were a reminder of a rare blunder by Rubin. During a
trip to the Middle East in December 1997, Rubin had told reporters
the White House was considering expanding the amount of food and
medicine Iraq could buy in spite of economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Described as a humanitarian program to help Iraqi children and
the elderly, the administration was sensitive to any suggestion it
was easing up on President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin, briefing reporters, said the program ''may be a
little carrot.'' He also took the required hard line toward Iraq
but any impression the administration was ready to negotiate with
Baghdad was not what the White House wanted left by a U.S.
official.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was said to be furious and Rubin was reprimanded by
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and national security adviser
Sandy Berger for the misstep.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart presented the bag of carrots Wednesday ''as a small
token of (Clinton's) gratitude'' and said Rubin's service to the
president had been ''invaluable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin was the spokesman for Albright, the U.S. ambassador to the
United Nations, in her four years there and then moved with her to
the State Department where he continued as one of her closest
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The correspondents at Wednesday's briefing then showered Rubin
with baby toys, squeezed rattles and staged a mock walkout,
returning after a few minutes to continue with the daily
question-and-answer session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
