<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-IBF official describes $100,000 payoff for Foreman-Schulzrematch  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Even though a rematch between
then-heavyweight champion George Foreman and Axel Schulz never
happened, it got the green light from the IBF because IBF president
Robert W. Lee squeezed Schulz promoter Cedric Kushner for $100,000,
a longtime IBF official testified Wednesday in Lee's racketeering
trial.
</P>
<P>
   While the accusation became public with Lee's November
indictment, the official, C. Douglas Beavers, for the first time
described his reluctance to participate in this affair, despite his
own bribe-riddled boxing career.
</P>
<P>
   That payoff, and a similar sum the prosecutors say another
promoter paid for the initial Foreman-Schulz match, are the largest
in the indictment against Lee and other IBF officials that charges
they took $338,000 to rig IBF rankings.
</P>
<P>
   They are also the only two payoffs to the IBF in the indictment
that appear directly related to heavyweight championship bouts.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner had protested Foreman's split-decision April 1995
victory over Schulz, and IBF rules allow rematches of controversial
bouts. Beavers sympathized, telling a federal jury the German
fighter outpointed Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just thought he should have got the rematch without having
to pay anything. I thought it was a travesty,'' Beavers said.
</P>
<P>
   At the IBF's convention the next month in Atlanta, Lee had
Beavers tell Kushner a rematch would cost $100,000, said Beavers,
Lee's handpicked ratings chairman from 1983-98.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers said Kushner initially thought he was joking, even
though Kushner had been making periodic payoffs averaging $5,000
twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers said Lee would regularly order him to get money from
Kushner by saying, ''Isn't it time you went to see the Fat Man,'' a
reference to Kushner's weight.
</P>
<P>
   The money, Kushner knew, was evenly divided among Lee, Lee's son
and aide Robert W. Lee Jr., IBF championship committee chairman
Bill Brennan, and Beavers, Beavers said.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner agreed to pay the $100,000, and the next month Beavers
drove from his home in Portsmouth, Va., and collected a manilla
envelope containing the money from Kushner at his home in East
Hampton, N.Y., Beavers said. The $100 bills were divided into four
packets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers then drove to the Vince Lombardi rest stop at the
northern end of the New Jersey Turnpike and gave $50,000 to Lee Jr.
for him and his father, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He did not linger with Lee Jr., nervous that their meeting would
look like a drug deal because the younger man drove up in a sporty
red convertible, wore a yellow jacket and gold jewelry, Beavers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers then drove to Brennan's home in Warsaw, Va., and
delivered his cut, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers said he did not know Schulz co-promoter Wilfrid
Sauerland, who prosecutors say gave Kushner the $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The IBF ordered the rematch, but Foreman relinquished the IBF
belt instead of complying.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner has not been charged. His lawyer again declined to
comment on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Jr., 38, of Scotch Plains, is on trial with his 66-year-old
father, who lives in Fanwood.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 86, was indicted with Lee, but was severed from the
trial due to ill health.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers, 56, succeeded Brennan in 1981 as executive director of
the Virginia Athletic Commission, the agency that until 1995
regulated boxing in the commonwealth. That function is now
contracted to a private company owned by Beavers, the Virginia
Boxing and Wrestling Association Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Beavers, who cooperated with investigators and is testifying
with immunity, wore a ''body wire'' to secretly record hundreds of
conversations with Lee. In coming weeks, Beavers is to guide the
jury through 80 talks, as well as videotaped meetings they had in
which money was exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors have not yet heard testimony from Foreman promoter Bob
Arum, who prosecutors said will tell how he funneled $100,000 to
the IBF to sanction the initial Foreman-Schulz title fight. An
exception was needed because Schulz was unranked.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, now in its third week, is expected to last three
months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
