<HEADLINE> 'Yard Gal' a Spare, Riveting Play  </HEADLINE>
V0911-----
r e *1404AP-Theater-Yard-Ga     04-26 0395
*1404 AP-Theater-Yard-Gal,0394   
'Yard Gal' a Spare, Riveting Play   
An AP Entertainment Review, 
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''Yard Gal'' opens with a complaint: Too many
people talk about Hackney without having been there.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that New Yorkers watching this British theater
import haven't been to that grimy blue-collar district of London
either. It's a bit off the tourist trail. But by the end of the
play they'll feel they had. ''Yard Gal'' is spare and riveting, and
while it's spoken in sometimes unintelligible London slang and
accent, you get the picture, loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   The play that opened Wednesday at the off-Broadway MCC Theater
is about six teen-age girls in a posse, or gang, although we only
meet two of them in this two-actor play on a bare stage with
minimal props.
</P>
<P>
   Marie (Amelia Lowdell) and Boo (Sharon Duncan-Brewster) are best
friends. They laugh, dance, fix each other's hair, take dope,
shoplift. After someone dies at a dance they spend a night in jail.
They aren't ruled by parents, school or jobs. They aren't avidly
seeking sex, violence or revenge on society, but won't shy away
from doing any of these things.
</P>
<P>
   They look down on prostitution, but will trade sex with a yardie
(pusher) for gear (dope), or use the lure of sex to steal a man's
wallet. Boo lives in a juvenile home, and Marie with her father,
who beats her up when she comes home wearing a miniskirt.
</P>
<P>
   Marie wounds a rival with a broken bottle, and Boo goes to jail
for it. Marie gets pregnant. It's a sordid story without any kind
of happy end, and yet in their quirky, very up-to-the-minute way,
they're just normal kids who make you care about them without
pitying them.
</P>
<P>
   The play, by 27-year-old Rebecca Prichard, was performed in 1998
by the English Stage Company at the Royal Court Theater, which was
founded to discover provocative, stimulating plays. ''Yard Gal''
toured England in 1998 and was performed in 1999 in Essen, Germany.
The New York production came about through an exchange program
between American and British Equity.
</P>
<P>
   It was originally commissioned by the Clean Break Theater
Company, a troupe for ex-convicts. But the credits list no jail
time for actresses Lowdell and Duncan-Brewster, playwright Prichard
or director Gemma Bodinetz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1704 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
