<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Sinks; Pork Bellies Advance  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crude oil futures plummeted Wednesday after new data showed an
unexpectedly large rise in U.S. stockpiles, which reached their
highest level in five months.
</P>
<P>
   In other commodity markets, gold fell and pork bellies rose
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month after OPEC approved production increases for
an oil-thirsty world market, the specter of increased crude
supplies is keeping oil prices in check.
</P>
<P>
   Even though officials had said it would take six weeks for the
new oil to show up, data from the Department of Energy early
Wednesday indicated that U.S. crude stocks rose by 5.1 million
barrels last week. The reason apparently is stronger demand from
U.S. refineries, although unofficial OPEC increases may also be
reflected.
</P>
<P>
   The government figure confirmed a separate inventory report late
Tuesday from the American Petroleum Institute which showed a 4.25
million-barrel increase.
</P>
<P>
   Both numbers easily exceeded analysts' expectations, touching
off a big selloff in the oil trading pit of the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ''The big build in crude stocks kind of weighed over the
market,'' said Phil Flynn, senior energy analyst for Alaron Trading
Corp. in Chicago. ''The market couldn't get anywhere and it just
marked time all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the pressures on oil prices, industry consultant
Petrologistics reportedly estimated that crude output from
Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries members increased
by 773,000 barrels a day in April, exceeding the new target.
</P>
<P>
   Light, sweet crude for June delivery fell 68 cents, or 3
percent, to $24.65 a barrel. Also, May heating oil rose .81 cent to
75.86 cents a gallon, May unleaded gasoline fell 2.03 cents to
80.29 cents a gallon and May natural gas fell 2.1 cents to $3.089
per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, June Brent crude from the North Sea fell 35 cents to
$22.98 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   On another floor of the New York Merc, gold futures slipped
briefly to a seven-month low of $276.40 an ounce before recovering
slightly to settle at $277.10, down $2.70 or 1 percent for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts blamed the strong dollar and the prospect of upcoming
central bank sales by Switzerland and Britain, a portion of which
will take place in May.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen pork bellies rocketed up nearly the limit on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange on the latest evidence of whopping demand for
bacon, which is made from hogs' bellies, and talk of decreasing
fresh supplies, market-watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   With fast-food chains promoting bacon sandwiches and burgers,
pork consumption is higher than it has been in two decades.
Restaurant demand alone for bacon and other pork products has
increased 17 percent in the last year, according to the National
Pork Producers Council.
</P>
<P>
   May pork bellies rose 2.62 cents to 99.72 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
