<P>
   Texas Lockheed Machinists End Strike
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- After a 17-day strike, Lockheed Martin
machinists in Fort Worth overwhelmingly approved a new contract
today and agreed to return to the assembly line. ''We didn't get
what we wanted, but it's better than a poke in the eye,'' said
Terry Faulkner, 45, a 20-year employee. Members of Local 776 of the
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers voted
1,514-246 for the new contract, and many expected to return to work
tomorrow. The Fort Worth facility is Lockheed's largest
manufacturer of F-16 fighter jets. Under the new contract, the
workers will get 3 percent annual raises this year and next and a 4
percent raise in 2002, among other things. Shares of Lockheed were
at 24[, down 1 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Renewed AOL-Time Warner Deal Sought
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer groups today demanded a major
restructuring of the proposed America Online-Time Warner merger,
saying the new company could squelch Internet competitors and would
be connected with another cable giant -- AT&AMP;T. The petition filed
with the Federal Communications Commission by leading consumer
advocates seeks a severing of any ties that would link the two
merging businesses with cable or satellite competitors. The groups
fear that without such measures, consumers will ultimately have
less choice for Internet services and the content they receive. The
consumer groups included Consumer Federation of America, The Media
Access Project.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron's 1st Quarter Earnings Soar
</P>
<P>
   SAN RAMON, Calif. (AP) -- Chevron Corp.'s first quarter profit
tripled from last year as the company cashed in on a spike in oil
prices that had motorists fuming about the soaring cost of
gasoline. The company reported net income of $1.04 billion, or
$1.59 per share, for the three months ended March 31, compared with
a profit of $329 million, or 59 cents a share, a year earlier.
Excluding one-time charges and gains, Chevron registered an
operating profit of $1.11 billion, or $1.68 per share -- the highest
for any three-month period in the company's long history. The
earnings easily beat analysts' expectations. Shares of Chevron were
at 86 5/16, up 1{.
</P>
<P>
   GE Rejects Pension Changes
</P>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- General Electric shareholders rejected a
proposal to alter the company's retirement benefits today, but
union workers and retirees said their campaign for a better pension
plan is gaining momentum. A union proposal to require shareholder
approval of top executives' retirement benefits gained 33 percent
shareholder support at the company's annual meeting. Some retirees
and workers say the company's pension plan for regular employees is
meager when compared to the benefits offered to the board of
directors. Shareholders overwhelmingly approved a three-to-one
stock split.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom Reports Pre-Merger Earnings
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Viacom Inc., owner of the MTV cable channel and
the Blockbuster video chain, reported a large jump in net earnings
in the latest fiscal quarter, which will likely be its last
reporting period before merging with CBS Corp. Viacom earned $76
million, or 11 cents per share, in the three months ended March 31,
compared to $44.9 million, or 5 cents a share, in the same period a
year ago. Revenues rose 2.5 percent to $3.03 billion. Yesterday,
Federal Communications Commission staff recommended that the
commission approve Viacom's merger deal with CBS, provided the
companies sell assets to comply with federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   Teens Help Microsoft With New Ideas
</P>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- The world's largest software maker is
turning to a pair of teens to tell it how to run the company.
Michael Furdyk, 17, and Jennifer Corriero, 19, are the newest
consultants at Microsoft Corp. Teen-age wunderkinder are nothing
new in the high-technology industry. But Furdyk and Corriero aren't
just pare of another college internship program. Their generation
grew up with the Internet, and Microsoft believes they will
integrate this new medium throughout their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo OKs Renault Unit Purchase
</P>
<P>
   GOTEBORG, Sweden (AP) -- Volvo shareholders on Wednesday approved
the purchase of Renault's truck division even as the company
announced a sharp decline in first-quarter earnings. The
shareholder approval of the $1.6 billion deal came during Volvo's
two-hour annual meeting and was largely expected. The deal still
needs approval from U.S. and European antitrust authorities.
</P>
<P>
   European Stocks Close Mostly Higher
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks ended mostly higher today, led by
gains in technology shares. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in
European companies rose 3.90 points, or 1 percent, to 388.94, with
the technology sector rising by 4 percent. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx
Index ended up 6.15 points at 434.66. London's FTSE-100 Share Index
fell 26.5 points, or 0.4 percent, to close at 6256.5, after holding
onto slight gains for much of the trading session. Milan's MibTel
index ended up 0.4 percent, having only begun trading at 1415 GMT
after technical problems crippled the bourse's information
distribution channels before the market opened. Trading closed 30
minutes later than usual, at 1600 GMT, due to the delay.
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index rose 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Plunging Euro Takes Financial Toll
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Although the euro stabilized today after sinking
to a new low against the dollar, its weakness poses a challenge not
only to the European Central Bank but also to economies and
individuals outside the zone of 11 countries that use the single
currency. Among its casualties are British manufacturers, who are
losing sales as they try to compete against goods priced in
chronically weak euros. Americans investing in shares of European
companies also are taking a beating. Swelling regional stock
valuations look a lot less impressive once those shares are
converted from euros into dollars. The euro has plunged almost 23
percent since January 1999, when it was launched. Yesterday, the
euro fell to a record low of 91.62 cents during trading in New
York. It staged a modest rally today, rising to 92.33 cents in late
trading in New York.
</P>
