<HEADLINE> Clinton calls for breaks on estate taxes for farmers  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELDON, N.Y. (AP) -- Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton
called Wednesday for giving farmers further breaks on their estate
taxes so businesses could be kept in the family.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, visiting a more than 100-year-old dairy farm in
Wyoming County, said the estate tax exemption on family farms and
family-owned businesses should be raised to $1.75 million, up from
the current $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''You ought to be able to leave your land and the bulk of your
fortunes to your children and not to the government,'' the Democrat
told the audience of more than 100 people at the Almeter Brothers
Dairy Farm, located about 35 miles east of Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   With some of the Almeter Brothers' 289 cows mooing in the
background, Clinton told supporters that she wants ''to be a
senator who represents the entire state.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I know how tough it is in agriculture right now and I know the
challenges you are up against,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reducing estate taxes, Clinton said she would
also work to lower utility costs, taxes and labor costs that make
farming difficult in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting a fleece jacket to ward off the morning chill, the
first lady took questions for about a half hour from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought she did a great job, especially answering questions
off the cuff,'' said Harry Boshart, a retired construction worker
and a Democrat. Boshart said he would definitely be voting for
Clinton in November.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is running for the Senate against Republican New York
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by the Giuliani campaign said ''Mrs. Clinton
flip-flopped on yet another issue today in Wyoming County,
pandering to New York state farmers by suddenly deciding she
supports a reduction in the estate tax'' and that ''just last year,
Mrs. Clinton strongly opposed a Republican-sponsored tax bill that
included a 10-year phase-out of the estate tax.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady told the farmers Wednesday that one of her themes
as she moves across the state is to remind New Yorkers that
agriculture is the state's No. 1 industry and must be protected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
