<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall Slightly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The price of 30-year Treasury bonds fell
slightly Wednesday in cautious trading ahead of Thursday's release
of government reports on economic activity and wages in the first
quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell [ point,
or $1.25 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, rose to 5.94 percent from 5.93 percent Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was light as investors awaited news of the direction of
the U.S. economy. The government on Thursday is scheduled to report
on the gross domestic product and the employment cost index, both
for the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   If the economy continues its fast pace, it would reinforce
expectations that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates at
its May 16 meeting. Higher interest rates hurt the allure of bonds,
which pay a fixed rate of return.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader bond market, short-term notes fell between 1/32
point and 1/16 point, while intermediate notes were unchanged to
down 1/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information
service.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.74 percent as the
discount fell 0.04 percentage point from Tuesday to 5.59 percent.
Six-month yields were 5.99 as the discount rate fell 0.01 point to
5.75 percent. One-year yields were 6.10 percent as the discount
fell 0.01 percentage point to 5.80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, remained unchanged at 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 3/32 point to 94 23/32. The average
yield to maturity was unchanged at 5.98 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
