<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Up After New Low Vs. Dollar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro stablized somewhat Wednesday as traders
pulled back from a sharp selloff the day before that sent Europe's
single currency to an all-time low.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was quoted at 92.33 cents in late New York trading, up
from 92.08 cents Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 106.27 Japanese yen in New York,
up from 105.81 yen.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market is taking a bit of a breather,'' said Tim Fox,
currency analyst at Standard Chartered Bank in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the euro fell below 93 cents for the first time
ever, then dipped below 92 cents during heavy selling before
recovering slightly late in the session.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's session was less volatile, but the concerns for the
European economy and political environment that led to Tuesday's
selloff remain, according to Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ''Perceptions remain unchanged. There's a pervasive cynicism
about the euro,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has come under pressure in recent weeks amid questions
over how European authorities will defend the currency.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, like many foreign exchange analysts, expects the European
Central Bank to raise interest rates at its meeting Thursday in an
effort to provide support to the sagging currency.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox said he's not convinced the action will address the
long-term problems afflicting the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 1.7022 Swiss francs, down from
1.7083, and 1.4752 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4705. The British
pound fell to $1.5768 from $1.5803.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.1172 German
marks, down from 2.1263; 7.1006 French francs, down from 7.1315;
and 2,095.98 Italian lire, down from 2,105.10.
</P>
</TEXT>
