<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday, April 26, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Columbine Tapes Released to Public
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- To the horror of the Columbine victims' families, law
enforcement authorities released video today of the dead and the dying.
Jefferson County District Attorney Frank Hutfless released the tapes to the
school victims' families on Tuesday under a court order after a judge ruled that
the relatives have an "undeniable and compelling public interest" in seeing the
footage. The county attorney also made copies available to the public today for
$25. The tapes depict the carnage of April 20, 1999, when two students killed 12
classmates and a teacher, wounded 23 others and committed suicide.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian, Relatives Meeting Delay Urged
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After spending 2 1/2 hours with Elian Gonzalez, a child
psychologist for the government today recommended delaying any visit between the
6-year-old Cuban refugee and his Miami relatives until the relatives reconcile
with his father. But Miami child psychologist Dr. Lidya Usategui contended Dr.
Paulina F. Kernberg spent too little time with Elian for a proper evaluation.
Dr. Jose Carro, president of the Cuban Pediatric Society in Exile, said, "In our
view, he (Elian) continues to suffer.... Elian should have access to his family
from Miami."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vt. Gov. Signs Nation's 1st Gay Union Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- Gov. Howard Dean today signed a first-in-the-nation
law that grants gay couples nearly all of the benefits of marriage. The state
law will allow gay couples to form civil unions beginning July 1. That will
entitle them to all of the 300 or so rights and responsibilities available to
married couples under Vermont law in such areas as taxes, inheritance and
medical decision-making. No state has gone further than Vermont is giving gay
couples something approximating marriage. The bill came about after the Vermont
Supreme Court unanimously ruled in December that gay couples were being
unconstitutionally denied the benefits of marriage.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Backs Faster Rural Web Connections
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WHITEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- President Clinton today urged better and faster
Internet connections in homes and businesses in rural America. Residents of this
farming community can access the World Wide Web. But for some people, who depend
on ordinary phone lines, it's more like the "World Wide Wait," the White House
said. Clinton's trip to Whiteville was the fifth in a series of "New Market"
tours the president has made to stress the need for economic development in
depressed areas of the nation like Columbus County, N.C.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S., Russia Launch Security Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov today launched a new
round of security negotiations with the Clinton administration. He pledged
cooperation despite deep differences over anti-missile defenses. Hedging his
bets, Ivanov also met with probable Republican presidential nominee George W.
Bush, outlining Russia's foreign policy goals and its objections to undermining
a 28-year-old landmark arms control treaty. The foreign minister's three-day
visit is designed to prepare for a smooth summit meeting in Moscow June 4-5
between President Clinton and Russian President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Brazil Indians Leery of Church Apology
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PORTO SEGURO, Brazil (AP) -- The Catholic Church apologized Wednesday to
Brazil's Indians and blacks for the "sins and errors" committed by its clergy
and faithful over the past 500 years. Indians were reluctant to forgive. The
apology preceded a special Mass held on the beach where Franciscan Friar
Henrique de Coimbra celebrated Brazil's first Mass on April 26, 1500, four days
after the Portuguese expedition made landfall.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Off 179; Nasdaq Down 81
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks tumbled today after the latest sign of economic
growth brought interest rate worries to the foreground for the first time this
week. Blue chip stocks that have failed to live up to the market's robust profit
expectations led the decline. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 179.32 to
close at 10,945.50. The Nasdaq composite index lost 81.14 to 3,630.09. On the
NYSE, decliners led advancers 1,537-1,409.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yanks Blank Twins 2-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Derek Jeter broke a scoreless tie with a sixth-inning homer
and Tino Martinez added another solo shot two outs later as the New York Yankees
beat the Minnesota Twins 2-0 today for their second win in six games. Jeter
drove a 2-2 pitch from Joe Mays (0-3) into the right-field seats for his third
homer of the season. Martinez's homer, also his third, went into the right-field
bleachers. Jeff Nelson (4-0), the second of four Yankees pitchers, pitched 1 2/3
innings and was credited with the win in relief of Andy Pettitte, who made his
first start since coming off the disabled list with a mild back strain.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON
</SUBHEAD>
