<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Pursues Women Voters  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- They said it with flowers, surrounded by earth
tones, on cushy couches that could have come from the Oprah Winfrey
show.
</P>
<P>
   A backdrop filled with the faces of young girls declared, ''For
our daughters.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., who has long counseled GOP
colleagues on how to draw female votes, made it clear that the
party's presumptive presidential nominee will listen to women's
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''Women across the country will have a voice in a George Bush
administration,'' said Dunn, founder of the Republican Women
Leaders Forum that hosted Wednesday's event.
</P>
<P>
   Women are a battleground voting bloc and, although undecided
women tend to vote for Democrats, polls show Bush in striking
distance of Democrat Al Gore among them.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn and Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, hosted the talk
show-style forum at the Ronald Reagan Building International Trade
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife Laura guest-starred, while three groups of
students and their mentors joined them to discuss his campaign
themes: Educating all children, preventing substance abuse and
encouraging volunteerism.
</P>
<P>
   The session highlighted Bush's ''Texas Reading Initiative,'' a
four-year old program in which children are expected to read at
least at their grade level.
</P>
<P>
   Bush listened to the students' stories of learning to read in
English and Spanish and of volunteering, but the Texas governor's
ambition shined through.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm an incredibly optimistic person about your future -- mine
too,'' Bush told students who fight substance abuse among their
peers as part of the ''Kids Saving Kids,'' program.
</P>
<P>
   Face-to-face with Elena Douglass, a Houston second-grader who is
learning to read in English and Spanish, Bush asked: ''How is it
here in the nation's capital, you having a good time?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes sir,'' Elena answered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Me too,'' Bush replied with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the session, he exclaimed: ''I can't wait to be
the president.''
</P>
<P>
   But before that happens, Republicans acknowledge Bush must go
further than his GOP predecessors in closing the gender gap among
women against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Republican pollster Tony Fabrizio told the
conference the party has a fair shot at women voters, who will be
crucial to GOP victories in the November presidential and
congressional elections races that he said are on track to be the
closest in modern history.
</P>
<P>
   Women, he said, split their loyalties between Gore and Bush
depending on the issue. Polls show that Bush is strong among women
on education, tax cuts and defense, while Gore is strongest on
health care, saving Medicare and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have your work cut out for you,'' Fabrizio said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee later Wednesday said that in
Texas, Bush has a poor record on appointing women, on domestic
violence deaths and employment rates among women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
