<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miami Elian Protesters Head to DC  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL LA CORTE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Shops reopened and people returned to work
Wednesday, a day after a general strike in Little Havana to protest
the seizure of Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   But the protests over the pre-dawn raid by federal agents are
far from over. About 80 people, including college students and
others upset with the government's action, left for Washington,
D.C., in a caravan of cars and buses Wednesday. Messages written on
the windows read: ''Justice for Elian,'' ''Elian's S.W.A.T.'' and
''We'll never forget you Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the trip's organizers, Bettina Rodriguez Aguilera of a
group called New Generation Cuba, said the protesters would rally
outside the White House at noon Thursday. They hoped to give
President Clinton a letter asking for an investigation into what
they called the Immigration and Naturalization Service's abuse of
power.
</P>
<P>
   The group was also trying to get a permit to protest outside the
Cuban diplomatic mission.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was seized by armed federal agents Saturday morning from
the home of his Miami relatives, who cared for the 6-year-old boy
after he was rescued from the waters off Florida in November and
are fighting to block his return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was reunited with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, in
Washington. They are now staying at the secluded Wye River
conference center on Maryland's Eastern Shore while awaiting a
federal appeals court ruling on whether Elian should be granted an
asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday -- called ''Martes Muerte'' or ''Dead Tuesday'' in
Little Havana -- businesses kept iron gates closed, workers stayed
home and students skipped school.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Sixto, 21, did not go to his job at his parents'
factory, which was closed.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Miami-Dade Community College student said he
learned about the trip to Washington just an hour before it was to
leave. He quickly packed a bag, knowing he would miss two days of
classes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to help in any way I can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Cuban American National Foundation:
http://www.canfnet.org
</P>
<P>
   New Generation Cuba: http://www.ngcuba.org
</P>
</TEXT>
