<DOCNO> APW20000426.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> March Durable Goods Orders Rebound  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Orders for big-ticket goods in March posted
their first increase this year after two months of decline,
providing fresh evidence of an economy hot enough to force another
increase in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Orders for durable goods -- items expect to last at least three
years -- rose a bigger-than-expected 2.6 percent last month to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $215.2 billion, led by a heavy
demand for electronic products. That reversed the pattern of the
two previous months in which orders declined, the Commerce
Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the report revived fears among investors that
the Federal Reserve will continue to boost interest rates until the
economy slows to a more sustainable pace. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 179.32 points to 10,945.50; the Nasdaq closed down
81.14 points to 3,630.09.
</P>
<P>
   ''Consumers are demanding more big-ticket items. ... We think
this should subsequently raise the level of manufacturing as a
whole in the coming months,'' said economist Richard Yamarone of
Argus Research Corp. ''This engine is not running out of gas
anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Orders for electronics and electrical equipment, including
semiconductors, circuit boards and home appliances, soared 9.7
percent, the eighth increase in the last 10 months and the biggest
jump since November. Such orders rose 9.3 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   ''This tells the story of the technology wave that is helping to
fuel economic growth,'' said Michael Niemira, an economist with the
Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   Total durable-goods orders fell 1.9 percent in January and 2
percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those declines, durable-goods orders were up 7.4
percent in the first quarter of 2000 from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said March's durable-goods report provides a glimpse
of the strong growth that took place in the larger economy during
the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The surge in orders indicates the economy is still on fire,''
said Joel Naroff of Naroff Economic Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the government will release a report showing the
economy's growth during the first three months of this year. Many
analysts expect the economy grew at a 6 percent rate, well above
the Fed's preferred speed limit but not as brisk as the 7.3 percent
rate posted in the fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates five times since
June 30 to slow the speeding economy and to keep inflation under
control. Given the outlook for strong continuing growth, many
economists believe the Fed will bump up interest rates again on May
16.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Fed is looking for signs of moderation, they won't find
it here,'' First Union's chief economist David Orr said of
Wednesday's durable-goods report.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the booming economy has helped push the nation's
home ownership rate to an all-time high of 67.1 percent in the
first quarter of this year surpassing the previous record of 67
percent set in the third quarter of 1999, the Department of Housing
and Urban Development said in a report.
</P>
<P>
   Orders for transportation equipment grew by a solid 1.8 percent
in March as an increase in orders for cars and automobile parts
more than offset a decrease in shipbuilding and tanks.
Transportation orders fell by a sharp 9.7 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the volatile transportation category, total
durable-goods orders rose 2.8 percent in March, the largest
increase since July. Transportation is often volatile because it
includes such big purchases as airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Primary metals, the category that includes steel, saw orders go
up by 0.5 percent last month following a 1.6 percent decline in
February.
</P>
<P>
   But orders for industrial machinery, including computers and
machine tools fell 2.1 percent in March following a 3.8 percent
decline the month before. Those orders have been down four of the
last five months.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments of big-ticket items, a good sign of current demand,
rose 1.5 percent in March after a 1.4 percent drop the month
before.
</P>
<P>
   ''Strong investment by American companies will continue to
propel the economy forward in the second quarter of 2000,''
National Association of Manufacturers President Jerry Jasinowski
said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The durable-goods report can be found:
http://www.census.gov/indicator/www/m3
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
