<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oneidas hope to ease fears of landowners legally  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ONEIDA, N.Y. (AP) -- With litigation looming to settle its
longstanding land claim, the Oneida Indian Nation on Wednesday
offered to legally protect private property owners if the case ends
up in court.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is essential that we do everything we can to make sure that
everyone knows that we will keep our word,'' Oneida Nation
representative Ray Halbritter said. ''On the eve of going back into
litigation, we want to make it clear to everyone that the
landowners will be protected. Rent or eviction is not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that, the Oneidas filed two documents earlier in the
day with U.S. District Court Judge Neal P. McCurn in Syracuse. One
document, a stipulation agreement, would remove the possibilities
of damages, rent or eviction.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe also asked McCurn to separate the proposed defendants
so the case against the state would proceed first. In effect, the
state would be agreeing to be sued, and the documents would make
sure that it couldn't wiggle out of the case later on.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people would like more of a binding, legal assurance,''
Halbritter said. ''That's why we're doing this. For us, our word is
enough. Our word is our bond. We believe it will relieve some
tension. That's as much as we can possibly do and retain our legal
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   In order to make both documents legally binding, the state and
Madison and Oneida counties have to sign them, in effect agreeing
not to use the Oneidas' position against them in court at a later
time. The Oneidas of Wisconsin and Canada, who also are part of the
land claim, also have to sign the agreements, and Halbritter said
he would appeal to them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Halbritter said if the documents are signed, private landowners
would not be added as defendants initially. And he said if the
tribe is able to get full restitution from the state ''there would
be no need for further lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   State attorneys had not yet heard from the Oneidas, Michael
McKeon, spokesman for Gov. George Pataki, said. McKeon questioned
how serious the overture was if the Oneidas were going through the
media first.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this means that the Oneidas are ready to return to the
negotiating table after walking away the last time, then they are
welcome back,'' he said. ''We haven't left. We've been sitting
there waiting for them to come back. This was a press conference.
We are going to wait to hear what they say at the negotiating table
and see if this is real.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks collapsed earlier this month after officials said the two
counties rejected a $45 million cash offer, and the state would not
back off from its demand for a 25 percent share of all ''new
gaming'' revenue at the tribe's Turning Stone Casino.
</P>
<P>
   The land claim stems from the state's purchase of 250,000 acres
in the two counties from the Oneidas in the late 18th and early
19th centuries. The Oneidas filed a lawsuit in 1974 over the
transactions. The U.S. Supreme Court found in 1985 that those
transactions were illegal and ruled that the Oneidas were entitled
to compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, in an attempt to bring more pressure on the state
to negotiate, the federal government sided with the Oneidas and
filed an amended complaint asking that 20,000 landowners in the two
counties be added as defendants. However, McCurn has not yet
decided whether to add the landowners as defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Halbritter said the Oneidas were still willing to negotiate a
settlement, but he held out little hope for that. Both sides have
to inform McCurn of their intentions by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're obligated to carry on the land claim,'' Halbritter said
as he stood in a meeting room at the tribe's new Children and
Elders Center. ''It's about our future generations. Our elders got
us here. Our children will carry us to the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 1823 </TRAILER>
