<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anheuser-Busch Earnings Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Anheuser-Busch Cos.'s profit rose 9.7 percent
in the first quarter as the brewer inched closer to capturing half
the beer market in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The results beat Wall Street expectations. Its stock fell in
afternoon trading but recovered to finish at $74.56 1/4, up 18 3/4
cents, at 5:15 p.m. EST on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of the best-selling Budweiser and the top light beer,
Bud Light, earned $350 million, or 76 cents per share, in the three
months ended March 31, up from earnings of $319 million, or 66
cents per share, a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial expected
earnings of 74 cents a share in the latest quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose to $3.30 billion from $3.16 billion. The company's
domestic market share rose 0.8 percentage point to 49 percent in
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Budweiser and Bud light from wholesalers to retailers
rose 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic beer shipments increased 0.6 million barrels to 23.7
million barrels. The company said the increased shipments reflected
the continued strength of Budweiser products, particularly Bud
Light, which continued to grow at a double-digit pace.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Anheuser-Busch rolled out Tequiza Extra, an extension
of the tequila-and-lime flavored Tequiza brand introduced a year
earlier. And in May, the company plans to introduce its Doc Otis
lemon-flavored malt beverage, aimed at consumers of imports and
specialty alcoholic drinks.
</P>
</TEXT>
