<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein's Doherty upbeat on prospects for peace in NorthernIreland  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Sinn Fein vice president Pat Doherty told
Irish Americans in and around New Jersey's state capitol Wednesday
he is confident that the peace process in Northern Ireland can
survive recent setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the process ''solid,'' Doherty said, ''It is not the
text (of the accords), it is the good will that has been lacking
... There will be problems, but fundamentally there will be no
turning back.''
</P>
<P>
   British authorities in February suspended the elected Assembly
and its ruling cabinet, claiming the IRA's refusal to disarm had
placed the provincial government in danger of permanent collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty is one of the 108 elected members of the Assembly, and
his Sinn Fein party has been linked to the IRA and often speaks for
it. He said suspending the government was an irrational move
because armed militants will agree to disarm only if elected
government institutions are in place and are shown to be stable.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not resolve it unless there is a political context,
and a political way to move forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty said continuous support from millions of Irish-American
Catholics has kept international attention on the crisis, which in
turn limits the danger that secretive political maneuvers in
Belfast will scuttle the 1998 Good Friday accords.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly the White House has never disengaged from the
process,'' Doherty said. ''I think it is primarily due to Irish
Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Doherty has played a prominent role in disarmament talks and was
more upbeat in his New Jersey tour than Sinn Fein president Gerry
Adams has been on the prospects of salvaging the fledgling
government.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty met with Irish-American political and business leaders
at the Statehouse, and was scheduled later to visit popular Irish
clubs and bars in neighboring Hamilton Township, where collections
are frequently taken to help the families of dead or imprisoned IRA
men.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters if he ever feels his own life is at risk,
Doherty said, ''If I woke up every morning worried about who was
going to shoot me, I would never get out of bed.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Statehouse news conference Doherty said he was pleased to
find so many Irish surnames in the New Jersey political
establishment, including Woodbridge Mayor James McGreevey, a likely
Democratic candidate for governor next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have said constantly peace without justice is not peace,''
said McGreevey, who as a state legislator sponsored trade
resolutions intended to help economic development in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty was also joined by U.S. Rep. Christopher Smith,
R-Robbinsville, chairman of the House Human Rights subcommittee
that has staged visits and hearings in Northern Ireland on civil
rights abuses, most recently the harassment and killing of Catholic
criminal defense attorneys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
