<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
By Diane Scarponi, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson confronted a
group of white supremacists in Wallingford Wednesday, after
applauding lawmakers and the governor for passing a law that would
force the town to close its offices on Martin Luther King Day.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was in Wallingford for a rally in support of the
legislation will require all 169 municipalities in Connecticut to
recognize the holiday. Wallingford is currently the only town in
Connecticut that keeps its offices open on King Day.
</P>
<P>
   A group of about 10 people waving Confederate flags showed up to
protest Jackson's visit. Jackson offered to shake the hand of one
man who was dressed in Ku Klux Klan garb, but was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time for sheets to be worn on a bed and not to hide a
person's face,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation occurred minutes before Jackson was to attend
a church service and lead a march to town hall.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate gave final legislative approval to the King Day
bill minutes before midnight Tuesday, and Gov. John G. Rowland
signed it Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm glad this governor signed this bill today to make a
statement for the country and for the world,'' the civil rights
leader said between privately meeting with Rowland and addressing
the state House of Representatives in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Wallingford Mayor William Dickinson has ''slept
through a revolution'' while leading the only town in the state
which has not closed its municipal offices on King Day, despite a
1986 law making it a state holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may be looking at a Rip Van Winkle situation where some
people sleep too long,'' Jackson said. ''And while they're asleep,
the world passes them by.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was expected to meet with Dickinson Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson has said the controversy is not about race, but a
dispute with the town's labor unions. Dickinson wants town workers
to swap another holiday for King Day, but union leaders want
workers to get the day off as an extra paid holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Jan. 17 holiday this year, three people wearing Ku
Klux Klan hoods and robes walked along Main Street in Wallingford.
On the holiday, one of those people stood near a church where a
celebration honoring King was being held. Neo-Nazi literature also
has been distributed around the town.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to make bigots feel uncomfortable in
Wallingford and everywhere else,'' said Rep. Mary Mushinsky,
D-Wallingford. ''And its' important that my hometown Wallingford
reiterates that we are a town that thrives on diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to a national report released this week that says
minority youths are treated less fairly than their white peers by
the judicial system, Jackson called for a change in the way young
black and Latino offenders are dealt with.
</P>
<P>
   He said improved education in communities and prisons will
reduce criminal recidivism rates among juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now they leave jail sicker and slicker and return to jail
quicker,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also was expected to join a rally with striking workers
at the Avery Heights nursing home in Hartford Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 1826 </TRAILER>
