<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox 14, Rangers 4  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN HAWKINS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra had three hits,
including a home run, to extend his hitting streak to 13 games as
the Boston Red Sox routed the Texas Rangers 14-4 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's RBI double provided Boston's first run, and was
part of a five-run first-inning outburst after Texas starter Mark
Clark (2-2) got the first two outs. Garciaparra was among seven
straight Red Sox hitters to reach with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom seven hitters in the batting order, responsible for
Boston's best first inning of the season, had at least two hits.
The 21 hits were a season high for Boston and the most allowed by
Texas this season.
</P>
<P>
   With his second 3-for-5 game in the series, plus an intentional
walk with Boston leading by six runs, Garciaparra was 8-for-14 in
the three games against Texas. He is 25-for-48 (.521) against the
Rangers since the start of last season.
</P>
<P>
   During his hitting streak this season, Garciaparra is 25-of-54
(.463). He raised his average 17 points to .386 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After Clark got the first two Boston batters out, Brian Daubach
and Garciaparra hit consecutive doubles. Following a walk, Carl
Everett hit a three-run homer and No. 9 hitter Wilton Veras later
added an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach had four hits, including a career-high three doubles.
Everett's third hit was an RBI double as the Red Sox added four
more runs in the ninth off Tim Crabtree, the sixth Texas pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Clark left after giving up a one-out RBI single to Troy O'Leary
in the second. He gave up six runs on seven hits in the shortest
outing by a Rangers starter this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox scored in each of the first four innings to build a
9-0 lead. Jason Varitek hit the first pitch of the third, and
Garciaparra hit his second homer of the season an inning later when
another run also scored on a Texas error.
</P>
<P>
   Boston starter Jeff Fassero (2-1) was the benefactor and didn't
allow a run until David Segui doubled and scored on a fielder's
choice grounder in the fourth for Texas. Ivan Rodriguez hit a
two-run homer, his seventh, in the fifth. Tom Evans had an RBI
single in the ninth for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero was pulled after Segui led off the sixth with a sharp
single to left. Fassero allowed three runs on seven hits, three of
them by Segui, with two strikeouts and two walks.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Before Clark's early departure, Texas pitchers had 17
straight starts in which they went at least five innings. That was
the longest streak for the Rangers since 1984 when the starters
went five-plus innings in 36 straight games. ... Both teams are off
Thursday, Texas before a three-game series at Baltimore and the Red
Sox prior to playing three games at Cleveland. ... Segui had three
hits for his eighth multi-hit game in his last 12 and 12th overall,
second in the majors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
