<HEADLINE> Bush Faces Criticism at Home  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE MABIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush should ask the state
health commissioner to resign over his comments about teen
pregnancy and Hispanics, civil rights groups said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, the Congressional Hispanic Caucus also asked for
Dr. Reyn Archer to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Archer has been under fire since telling The New York Times
earlier this month that Hispanics are culturally resistant to the
idea that ''getting pregnant is a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He has apologized, in writing and in person to state
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas Freedom Network, League of United Latin American
Citizens, Mexican-American Legal Defense &AMP; Educational Fund and
Rainbow Coalition said apologies weren't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're putting Governor Bush on notice: as his appointee to the
post of commissioner of health, Archer's comments only fuel
questions about Governor Bush's tolerance of racism and sexism,''
said Samantha Smoot, director of the Texas Freedom Network.
</P>
<P>
   Archer ''has no plans to resign,'' said his spokesman, Doug
McBride.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Mike Jones said the governor is satisfied with
Archer's apology and wouldn't seek his resignation. ''Governor Bush
does not tolerate racism in any form,'' Jones added.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also was criticized Wednesday by a group of Republican
women from the Houston suburb of Clear Lake, who oppose a new state
emissions permit for a chemical plant in nearby Bayport.
</P>
<P>
   The women said the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission, the state's environmental agency, continues to grant
permits to polluting plants despite deteriorating air quality.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Jones defended the governor's record, saying
Texas has reduced toxic emissions more than all other states
combined.
</P>
</TEXT>
