<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Karl Still Teaching Bucks  </HEADLINE>
By GREG BEACHAM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. FRANCIS, Wis. (AP) -- George Karl has coined a phrase to
describe his Milwaukee Bucks, who sometimes play to their potential
and sometimes look as if they've never been coached before.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're my sometimes team,'' the Bucks coach said.
</P>
<P>
   After 83 games and seven months of daily contact, Karl said he
still doesn't know a lot about the Bucks, who face the Indiana
Pacers on Thursday night in the second game of their first-round
series.
</P>
<P>
   Though his team has taxed his patience and his own faith in his
abilities, Karl calls this season one of his most constructive as a
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not saying this has been my best year, but I got to do a
lot more coaching than I did in the last while,'' Karl said.
''That's something you enjoy when you haven't been doing it for a
while. It's been a return to my roots, so to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was fired by Seattle in 1998, the SuperSonics were a
finely tuned machine. They won 55 games or more in six straight
seasons, but a lack of playoff success and a fight with team
management doomed him.
</P>
<P>
   In his first two years in Milwaukee, he has thrilled fans and
owner Herb Kohl by taking the Bucks to the playoffs twice. The
once-proud franchise endured seven years out of the postseason
during the coaching tenures of Mike Dunleavy and Chris Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Karl still insists the team has exceeded his own expectations
despite a roster with two All-Stars and a wealth of offensive
talent. While he knows expectations for next season will be higher,
he has already declared the current one a success.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all proud of what we've done this year, but we need to
win in the playoffs to make it all worth it,'' Glenn Robinson said.
''Coach has got us to this point, and we hope we can pay him back
by taking it further.''
</P>
<P>
   As a defense-minded coach, Karl is in an unusual situation with
the offensively talented Bucks. The team's stars are all standout
jump-shooters and mediocre defenders, and their talents are
particularly unsuited to play Karl's brand of basketball.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it took the Bucks until the season's final 15 games to
begin to grasp the defensive scheme Karl and assistant Terry Stotts
employed to great effect in Seattle. The system, which depends
heavily on double-teaming and intelligent decisions on switches,
helped make a defensive star of Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   But the younger Bucks spent almost the entire season befuddled
by the system. Even earlier this week, Karl stopped a practice
scrimmage to chastise Ray Allen for missing a switch, saying,
''You've been messing that up all season long, Ray!''
</P>
<P>
   But with 15 games left in the season and the Bucks three games
out of a playoff spot, things suddenly kicked into gear. Milwaukee
went 11-4 to close the season and streaked past Orlando for the
East's final playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee held its opponents to 96.1 points per game -- a number
that would have been much lower without two high-scoring overtime
games -- and gave a greatly increased effort on defense. Some Bucks
say it was because they finally figured out Karl's defense, though
Karl isn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think our system isn't as complicated as it's made out
to be,'' he said. ''Defense is about your heart more than your
talent. I don't know if we've always displayed that heart this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl thinks the Bucks finally started to play defense because
they realized a trip to the playoffs hinged on it. He doesn't know
why he was unable to motivate them to do it earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like I said, they're the sometimes team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Bucks are in the playoffs, the languorous schedule
has Karl struggled to keep his team focused during three straight
off-days. He thinks the extra time off is beneficial to aging,
playoff-tested teams like the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd rather play a best-of-11,'' he said with a grin. ''Just
get out on the court and go. That would be the best thing for my
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1848 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defending Decathlon Champ Trailing  </HEADLINE>
By CHUCK SCHOFFNER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Kip Janvrin had only himself to blame
for where he stood after the first day of the Drake Relays
decathlon.
</P>
<P>
   Kamau Sullivan, who trained under Janvrin for two years in
Warrensburg, Mo., took the lead Wednesday with a career-best 4,006
points. Jeff Sander, who trains under Janvrin now, was second with
3,909.
</P>
<P>
   Janvrin, seeking his sixth consecutive Drake title and 11th
overall, was third with 3,878.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the leaders is to hold on because Janvrin's
second-day events are his best. Last year, he trailed Sullivan by
nine points after the first day and ended up beating him by 556.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm up and coming and he's already there at a high level,''
said Sullivan, who now lives in Indianapolis. ''When we intersect
at that high level, it's going to be a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   And when might that be?
</P>
<P>
   ''That's supposed to happen tomorrow,'' Sullivan said with a
grin.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State's Barbara Szlendakova led the heptathlon with 3,216
points. Wichita State's Mellanee Welty, the winner the last two
years, was second with 3,190.
</P>
<P>
   Decathletes compete in the 100 meters, long jump, shot put, high
jump and 400 the first day. They finish with the 110 hurdles,
discus, pole vault, javelin and 1,500. Janvrin is especially strong
in those last four.
</P>
<P>
   ''I need to do a good job in the hurdles. That's one of my best
events,'' Sullivan said. ''Then I just have to relax and remember
what he taught me and do some of that on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Janvrin, 34, said he was in a good spot despite being 128 points
off the lead. He has faced even greater deficits at Drake and still
won.
</P>
<P>
   ''The guys ahead of me are guys I've worked with. I know what
they can do,'' he said. ''I just need to be within eyesight of them
in the 1,500 and I'll be OK. Nobody can beat me in the 1,500.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan won the high jump Wednesday and finished third in the
100, shot put and long jump. Janvrin finished first in the 100 and
400 but lost 256 points to Sullivan in the high jump and long jump.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Iowa's Travis Geopfert won the shot put and
Washington's Jacob Predmore won the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   Janvrin said a groin injury has hampered his training in the
hurdles. He also said Sullivan and Sander have improved in the
throwing events and will be tough to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not afraid to lose. I'm not afraid to pass the torch to
somebody younger,'' Janvrin said. ''At the same time, I'm not going
to make it easy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Szlendakova seemed shocked to be leading the heptathlon. She
missed the outdoor season last year because of a stress fracture
and had not done a heptathlon since the NCAA championships in June
of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''I happy to be ahead, but it's still the first day and it
doesn't mean anything,'' Szlendakova said. ''I really need to get a
good long jump tomorrow and then see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Szlendakova did not take the lead until winning the 200, the
final event of the day. She was third in the 100 hurdles but was
disappointed with her throw of 33 feet, 4 inches in the shot put,
which placed her seventh among the 11 competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just not very good at throws,'' said Szlendakova, a slim
sophomore from the Czech Republic. ''It's all technique. I'm
throwing well in practice, but I come to the competition and can't
convert it.''
</P>
<P>
   Welty won the high jump, Alcorn State's Millicent Sylvan won the
hurdles and McKendree's Neisha Thompson finished first in the shot.
Sylvan was third overall with 3,153 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
