<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legal actions keep high court busy, shovels still  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) The motions are filed, the sound bites
recorded, the political positions staked.
</P>
<P>
   But the shovels are still.
</P>
<P>
   And many children -- rich and poor, from Cape May to High Point --
attend schools with overcrowded classrooms, outdated wiring and
leaky roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman has promised a school construction program
for all districts -- rich and poor, south and north -- as she tries
to remedy years of neglect that have left behind crumbling and
overcrowded schools.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes the need for school repairs and building. But
the question is: How much should the state pay?
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins is asking the state Supreme Court
to answer that question.
</P>
<P>
   He believes the high court's 1998 decision allows the state to
force even the poorest districts to ante up a share of an estimated
$6 billion in construction costs.
</P>
<P>
   He has asked the Supreme Court to clarify that ruling, which
directed the state to launch an enormous school construction
program in the 30 special needs districts.
</P>
<P>
   But both the Education Law Center, which represents poor
children, and the state -- usually at odds with each other -- agree
that the ruling is clear.
</P>
<P>
   In briefs filed this week, both urged the high court to reject
Collins' request.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for poor children and some Democratic lawmakers say
Collins' maneuver is further delaying the long overdue and sorely
needed program.
</P>
<P>
   ''The children have been waiting for years now for their
crumbling, overcrowded and obsolete school buildings to be
replaced,'' said David Sciarra, director of the Education Law
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ''The speaker has brought us back to court at the very time when
shovels should be in the ground,'' he said. ''For that reason, the
court should immediately reaffirm compliance'' with the order.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the legalities won't further delay the program.
Legislation will be in place by the end of June, he promised last
week.
</P>
<P>
   But he still questions how the court can force lawmakers to
fully fund school construction without ever including them in the
case that ordered it.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we aren't a party to the case, why are we bound by the
case?'' Collins wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Sciarra, though, says the law and the court decisions are clear.
</P>
<P>
   The state can't force property-poor towns to raise taxes to
finance school construction. That means the state has to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Sciarra also wonders why Collins is raising the issue now --
nearly two years after the court ordered the construction program.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes down to money, said Don Sico, executive director of
the state Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   When the court issued its decision in May 1998, the estimated
cost of repairs and new construction in the 30 ''special needs''
districts was about $2.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, Sico said, has to question whether the state should be
forced to pay that much, especially when many other districts are
begging for construction funds.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman and lawmakers have promised to help all districts
finance their school construction costs, which have mounted as
tax-weary voters routinely reject building referendums, even in
growing, suburban towns.
</P>
<P>
   The entire cost in these other nearly 600 districts is loosely
estimated to be about $6 billion, said David Rosen, a budget expert
in the state Office of Legislative Services.
</P>
<P>
   The state would pay about one-third of that, under proposed
legislation, Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the total annual cost to the state could eventually
climb to a daunting $770 million, Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, lawmakers have earmarked only about $220 million from
lottery proceeds, the cigarette tax and the national tobacco
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   That promises to eventually put a lot of pressure on lawmakers
to come up with either a new tax, to cut spending or to skimp on
construction funds for New Jersey's other districts.
</P>
<P>
   If the speaker can successfully challenge the court's ruling,
the state stands to save millions.
</P>
<P>
   But while that challenge takes place, millions of children
master math in trailers and attend schools that lack libraries. For
them, answers to these questions can't come soon enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
