<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Jitney' Proves Playwright's Talent  </HEADLINE>
V0047-----
r e *1404AP-Theater-Jitney     04-26 0578
*1404 AP-Theater-Jitney,0577   
'Jitney' Proves Playwright's Talent   
An AP Entertainment Review, 
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Right from the beginning, August Wilson was
quite a storyteller, a playwright unafraid of big themes, big
emotions and vividly drawn characters.
</P>
<P>
   The proof can be found at off-Broadway's Second Stage, where
''Jitney,'' a revised version of his first full-length play, has
finally made it to New York, some two decades after it was written.
The only question: What took it so long?
</P>
<P>
   In ''Jitney,'' Wilson skillfully recreates a very specific
environment, the world of gypsy cab drivers who gather between
fares in a rundown Pittsburgh storefront that's soon to be
demolished.
</P>
<P>
   It's a world of prickly camaraderie -- with occasional violence,
which snakes through the casual banter and posturing of these
drivers. Wilson populates this informal club with some memorable
people, a group of black men brought to life in this tough-minded
production by a superb collection of actors.
</P>
<P>
   The most showy is Turnbo, the club gossip, played to
scene-stealing perfection by a fireplug named Stephen McKinley
Henderson. ''I'm just talking what I know,'' Turnbo says, defending
his gleeful recitation of news, good and bad, about the residents
of the Hill District, the black area of Pittsburgh where the play
is set.
</P>
<P>
   Turnbo lives to irritate Youngblood, a young Vietnam vet
(Russell Hornsby), who, it appears, is cheating on his girlfriend
Rena (Michole Briana White).
</P>
<P>
   The playwright stuffs his play, which is set in 1977, with
enough plot for three dramas. At its core is a bitter estrangement
between father and son. Becker (Paul Butler) runs the jitney
operation that ferries poor blacks ignored by regular cab
companies. In that respect, ''Jitney'' resembles ''Fences,''
Wilson's biggest Broadway success, which also focuses on a volatile
family relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Becker's son, Booster, has just gotten out of prison after
serving 20 years for killing a white woman. Once the bright light
of his family, Booster can't bridge the distrust and disappointment
that have grown between the two men while he has been in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Butler and Carl Lumbly, who plays Booster, square off in several
fierce confrontations that show Wilson at his explosive best.
Director Marion McClinton knows how to handle these battles, which
punctuate the proceedings as if they were gunshots -- unexpected,
quick and emotionally devastating.
</P>
<P>
   But they are part of a larger landscape, which designer David
Gallo has physically created on a marvelous set showing the dingy
jitney waiting room as well as aging automobiles parked beyond the
building's dirty windows.
</P>
<P>
   Life within this room is the family most of these men don't
have, and the playwright doesn't stint in the ways he has these
guys bond -- not only bond but stay together.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's Wilson's marvelous language that makes this evening
soar. The talk is tough, of the street, but there is a poetry to
it, not to mention a sense of humor that is honest and very, very
funny. His ear is unerring in its ability to capture what these men
say -- and don't say.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jitney'' began Wilson's cycle of ten, decade-by-decade plays
mirroring the black experience in 20th century America. Judging
from this production, it was an auspicious beginning, an amazing
preview of what was to come in the next 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1902 </TRAILER>
