<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regulators approve New Jersey pipeline; Ohio plan still in limbo  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE RIZZO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators approved a plan to expand a
long-distance natural gas pipeline in New Jersey and Pennsylvania,
but gave a company a deadline to find a new gas supply.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Attorney General John J. Farmer said Wednesday the
state would appeal the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission's
decision to let Houston-based Transcontinental Gas Pipeline Corp.
add 91 miles of pipeline in 10 New Jersey counties.
</P>
<P>
   The commission ''overlooked the impact such construction would
have on the residents and the environment,'' Farmer said Wednesday.
He said the appeal would be filed with the U.S. Court of Appeals in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may not be FERC's priority, but the safety of our residents
and the protection of our environment are my priorities,'' said
U.S. Rep. Rodney P. Frelinghuysen, R-N.J. ''The Transco pipeline
must be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Transco spokesman Chris Stockton said the company's MarketLink
extension was expanding along the paths of existing pipelines in
both states.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have operated our existing pipeline safely, not just in New
Jersey but in 13 states,'' Stockton said. ''We've never had a
public injury in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners gave Transco permission Tuesday to begin building
the 150-mile project through northeastern Pennsylvania and central
and northern New Jersey, provided the company has signed contracts
for 100 percent of the gas that would move through the system,
spokeswoman Tamara Young-Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline, intended to move gas from the Chicago to New York,
was first proposed by a partnership of natural gas sellers:
Transco, Coastal Corp.'s ANR Pipeline Co. and National Fuel Gas
Supply Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Before regulators give similar permission for that project,
known as the Independence Pipeline, they said they want to see
contracts for at least 35 percent of capacity by a certain date.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they don't submit those within 60 days their application
will be dismissed,'' Young-Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   FERC had voted in December to deny permission for the
Independence Pipeline to break ground, and said then the proposal
could be revived with enough signed contracts to prove the
construction is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline would go through 31 municipalities in ten New
Jersey counties -- Bergen, Burlington, Essex, Hunterdon, Middlesex,
Morris, Passaic, Somerset, Union and Warren. In Pennsylvania, it
would add to pipelines in Lycoming, Northampton, Clinton and
Columbia counties.
</P>
<P>
   Both portions of the pipeline proposal have generated local
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, homeowners, environmental experts and politicians
have said the project isn't necessary, threatens wetlands and might
pose a safety risk in densely populated areas.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey officials have been wary of gas pipelines since a gas
explosion leveled much of an Edison apartment complex in 1994,
injuring more than 100 people and forcing 1,000 residents to flee.
Gov. Christie Whitman has said the pipeline could cause safety
hazards and hurt her efforts to preserve open space in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Transco maintains that the new pipelines are needed because
their existing network is at 100 percent of capacity and the
company anticipates the increased use of natural gas to fuel power
plants in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Safety also is a concern in Pennsylvania and Ohio. Farmers in
northern Ohio have complained that it would disrupt costly drainage
systems on which agriculture there depends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 1918 </TRAILER>
