<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shooting Suspect Faces Adult Charges  </HEADLINE>
By DERRILL HOLLY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A 16-year-old boy accused of shooting seven
children at the National Zoo will be charged as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Bernard Jones, who police say is the son of a convicted
drug enforcer, is charged with assault with intent to commit murder
while armed in the shooting of an 11-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, who remains in critical condition with a gunshot wound
to the head, was wounded when Jones allegedly opened fire on a
group of young people outside the zoo Monday, police said. Police
have said the shooting stemmed from a quarrel between two groups of
youths.
</P>
<P>
   Six other children between 12 and 16 years old were also hurt
but they were all treated and released from hospitals. Jones, who
was arrested Tuesday, will probably face other charges, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   At his arraignment Wednesday, Jones was ordered held without
bond pending a May 12 preliminary hearing. If convicted, Jones
faces a maximum sentence of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''This 16-year-old acted alone out of anger,'' said Terrance W.
Gainer, the Metropolitan Police Department's executive assistant
police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' attorney, Renee Raymond, refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Jones is the son of 44-year-old James Antonio Jones,
who once was an enforcer for the Rayful Edmond drug ring. Officials
said it used to be the largest drug enterprise in the city's
history, bringing as much as 1,700 pounds of cocaine into
Washington a month.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Jones was sentenced to 29 years in prison after a 1990
drug conspiracy conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Gainer said police know where Jones threw the 9 mm handgun they
believe was used in the shootings but the weapon has not been
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The quick arrest and Wednesday's reopening of the zoo helped
restore calm to the area. ''I think it's been taken care of. And
I'm not afraid,'' said Faye Griffith, who jogs regularly on the
landscaped grounds of the 163-acre facility.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging problems with youth and gun violence, Mayor
Anthony Williams says Washington a safe city with a declining crime
rate.
</P>
<P>
   The city's homicide rate was down nearly 8 percent through the
end of March, and the overall serious crimes including robberies,
assaults, and arsons were down 13.5 percent during the same period,
police records show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1930 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bryant: Lakers Ready for Real Thing  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NADEL, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kobe Bryant says the Los Angeles Lakers are
tired of beating up on each other. They'll finally get a chance to
beat up the Sacramento Kings on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think guys are a little antsy, agitated,'' Bryant said after
practice Wednesday, a workout both Bryant and coach Phil Jackson
said was much better than the previous day's practice. ''PJ
(Jackson) says it's important for us to take care of business. It's
imperative we defend our homecourt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have done an excellent job in that area since Staples
Center opened last fall. Their 117-107 victory over the Kings on
Sunday in Game 1 of the first-round best-of-five playoff series was
their 37th win in 43 home games this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings realize a victory in Game 2 is a must if they're going
to have a realistic chance at upsetting the Lakers, who entered the
playoffs heavily favored to win their first championship since
1988.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll try to get that first win and go from there,'' Kings
coach Rick Adelman said. ''They held homecourt. We're trying to get
a split, then hold homecourt at our place.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, the Kings would become just the third No. 8
seed to beat a No. 1 seed since the 16-team playoff format was
adopted 16 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think if we can win this one, it's going to put a tremendous
amount of pressure on them,'' said Glen Rice, who scored 18 points
to help the Lakers win Game 1. ''We definitely want to try and put
this team away.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson remembers how close the Kings came to upsetting Utah in
the first round last spring, extending the Jazz to overtime in the
fifth and deciding game. And that was after Utah won the opener
117-87.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're a fine, young team, they have the potential,'' Jackson
said. ''I'd like to sweep the series, I'd like to sweep the
championship, I'd like to go 15-0. The less you have to play in the
playoffs, the better; the less chance of injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but also the more chance of rust.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a good practice today, short and right to the point of
what we wanted to do,'' Jackson said. ''I think we're OK. Everybody
seemed to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson called Tuesday's practice one of the season's worst, but
cited the down time between games as a possible factor. Both the
Lakers and Kings enter Game 2 having played just once -- against
each other last Sunday -- since the regular season ended four days
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Teams seldom have four days between games during the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, who had 46 points, 17 rebounds and five
blocked shots in Game 1, said the extra time between games is fine
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's good for me, I can get a lot of rest, chill out at the
crib,'' he said. ''We'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal realizes the Kings will attempt to do a better job on him
defensively, but smiled when asked what could be done to stop him,
replying, ''Nothing. I'm telling you, I've got 350 moves on each
block. I'm a 7-footer who can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Game 1, the Kings said O'Neal got away with camping in
the key and barging into them to get into position for his shot.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm good enough to go around people, I don't have to go
through them,'' he said. ''I'll never have to go through (Kings
center) Vlade Divac, period. If we got all the calls, how come they
shot 35 free throws and we shot 14?''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, but Kings star Chris Webber fouled out with 6:53
remaining, after scoring 28 points in 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully I'll get more time than 27 minutes, and more than
five rebounds,'' he said. ''Rebounding is a key, it was a glaring
statistic why we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers outrebounded the Kings 54-37.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said he believes Game 2 will be officiated differently.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think at first, the game might be called under a microscope,
to an extent,'' Bryant said. ''As the game goes on, the calls will
loosen up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant also said he believes the Kings enter Game 2 with the
same confidence they've always had.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have nothing to lose,'' he said. ''They'll come back and
play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
