<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Al Fayed Not Entitled to Documents  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW BARAKAT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- A federal appeals court ruled Wednesday
that Mohamed Al Fayed isn't entitled to U.S. government records
related to his son and Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Egyptian-born multimillionaire sought all
documents concerning his son Dodi and Diana, who were killed in a
1997 car crash in Paris, as well as documents pertaining to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Al Fayed has said he believes there was a murder conspiracy by
people who disapproved of Diana's relationship with his son. An
investigation by a French magistrate blamed their driver, who tests
reveal was drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Al Fayed initially sought the information from the National
Security Agency under the Freedom of Information Act. NSA refused,
saying release of the information created the possibility of
''exceptionally grave damage'' to national security.
</P>
<P>
   The agency says its documents about Diana contain only
incidental references and she was never a target of surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Al Fayed's request under a different federal law was rejected in
Wednesday's ruling. The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
unanimously upheld the decision of a lower court judge who
determined Al Fayed was trying ''to make an end run around'' the
Freedom of Information Act.
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls Wednesday afternoon to Al Fayed spokeswoman Laurie
Meyer in London were not answered.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department was pleased with the ruling, said
spokesman Charles Miller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
