<HEADLINE> Bosox Hurler Pedro Martinez Is Hot  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN HAWKINS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- By Pedro Martinez's standards, it was a
tough game. He trailed and gave up two earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   The result was still the same for the Boston ace.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming a nine-day layoff and his first deficit since last
September, Martinez beat Texas 6-3 Tuesday night for his 10th
straight regular-season victory, a career best. The streak is 12,
counting his two 1999 postseason wins.
</P>
<P>
   And the two-time Cy Young winner insists he's still not at his
best this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I might not be quite where I want to be,'' Martinez said.
''I'll wait and see but I hope I feel better.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez (4-0) admitted Wednesday that he was a little more sore
than usual after the extended layoff. He hopes to be getting back
on a normal schedule after his latest start was pushed back by four
straight rainouts.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rangers scored two runs without getting a ball out of
the infield to take a 2-1 lead in the second inning, Martinez was
behind for the first time since Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Martinez had trailed was against the Yankees, when
Chili Davis hit a second-inning homer for a 1-0 lead. Martinez went
on to pitch a one-hitter that day and began a streak of 54 1-3
consecutive innings in the regular season with the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Other than falling behind, the only other obvious negatives for
Martinez were that his American League-best ERA increased from 1.27
to 1.59 and he surrendered a solo homer to Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo's homer was only the 11th Martinez has allowed since the
beginning of 1998, all of them with the bases empty. The other four
Rangers hits off of him were singles, including two infield hits in
the second.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's far and away the best pitcher out there,'' said Kenny
Rogers, Texas' No. 1 starter and the winner of Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could maybe put Randy (Johnson) up with him, but Pedro's
got more stuff. He's got more pitches and throws just as hard. He's
not just overpowering with his stuff, but he also uses a mentality
of pitching to the hitter's weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers maintained their 2-1 lead over Martinez until the
sixth. That is when the Red Sox scored four unearned runs after an
error on a potential inning-ending double play grounder.
</P>
<P>
   ''You knew at the time that was all he needed,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he didn't feel right, Martinez threw 68 of his 103
pitches for strikes, walking just one and hitting a batter. He left
after seven innings, even though he said he felt stronger as the
game went on.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could have gone probably one more inning, but we're playing
it safe really early in the season,'' Martinez said. ''You'd much
rather play it safe at this time of the year where you still have
to recover from a loss or whatever, than losing your ace for the
whole season.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez hasn't lost since last Aug. 19 to Oakland and Tim
Hudson. He avenged that defeat when he beat Hudson and the A's in
his previous start, April 15, but hadn't pitched since because of
the rainouts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pedro goes out there, he's got a mindset. When he puts the
ball in his hand, he does his job and gives us an opportunity to
win,'' Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1949 </TRAILER>
