<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Millionaires Threatened  </HEADLINE>
By JARED KOTLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Leftist rebels say they will begin
kidnapping millionaires and corporate executives who refuse to bow
to extortion demands aimed at funding the guerrilla insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel statement, read to the media late Tuesday by the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, was the boldest
statement yet of a long-standing rebel practice of extorting and
kidnapping the wealthy to finance its nearly four decade-old
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement seemed to contradict recent indications that
the FARC, Colombia's largest rebel group, was considering a
cease-fire. It also follows recent guerrilla contacts with leading
businessmen aimed at boosting fledgling peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting angrily to rebel statement Wednesday, President Andres
Pastrana blasted the FARC, saying it was ''incomprehensible'' that
the guerrilla group would announce a kidnapping plan with
cease-fire discussions slated to begin Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana's statement came on the same day as the resignation of
his chief peace envoy, Victor Ricardo.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo -- a key player in shepherding peace talks with the FARC
-- denied his decision to step down was linked to death threats he
said he recently received from right-wing paramilitary groups.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo was a controversial figure in Pastrana's government,
often bearing public criticism for the president's perceived
naivete in dealing with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana has made peace with the FARC his government's top
priority despite mounting criticism of ongoing rebel attacks and
kidnappings since negotiations began last year.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia has the highest kidnapping rate in the world, and the
problem is getting worse. Last year, 2,945 people were abducted,
about half by leftist rebels. Common criminal gangs were the second
biggest culprits.
</P>
<P>
   In the three-point communique read by guerrilla field marshal
Jorge Briceno, the FARC said its extortion policy was needed to
counter government aggression fueled by its taxes on multinational
corporations and ''Yankee imperialism.''
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas oppose a $1.7 billion anti-narcotics aid package
for Colombia under discussion in Washington, seeing it as a veiled
plan to defeat the FARC under the guise of the drug war. Along with
extortion, a key source of FARC revenue are ''taxes'' it levies on
drug traffickers and laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rebel policy, individuals or heads of companies
worth more than $1 million who refuse to pay an unspecified tax
will be kidnapped. ''Their liberation will depend on a ransom to be
determined,'' the FARC added.
</P>
<P>
   The talks have moved slowly amid criticism of strong-arm
guerrilla rule in the zone.
</P>
<P>
   Ernesto Borda, a former peace envoy and political analyst at
Bogota's Javeriana University, said the rebels could be trying to
reassert the widely discredited notion that they are ''Robin
Hoods'' -- stealing from the rich in order to serve the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas' image has deteriorated sharply amid rising rebel
involvement in the drug trade and widespread kidnappings of
Colombians of all means, Borda added.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the Catholic Church said the rebels have
begun extorting parishes around the country and threatening priests
who refuse to pay.
</P>
<P>
   The army estimates the FARC earns about $10 million a month from
extortion and took in about $84 million from ransom kidnappings
last year alone. The guerrillas claim those numbers are wildly
inflated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 1955 </TRAILER>
