<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House passes bill to give World War II vets high school diplomas  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The House of Representatives unanimously
passed a bill Wednesday that would grant diplomas to World War II
veterans who left high school before graduating to join the
military.
</P>
<P>
   The bill already passed the Senate, but must head back to that
chamber for a vote because of a change made by the House. Gov. John
G. Rowland has said he would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be comforting to have the diploma,'' said Hudson C.
Pelton, of Old Saybrook, whose 13-year-old granddaughter lobbied
for the bill. ''There wasn't time for it after I got out of the
service.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelton, 75, left high school and joined the Navy in 1942, when
he was 17. He saw action in both the Atlantic and Pacific during
four years of service before returning home to a job and a family
of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, any veteran honorably discharged after at least
90 days of service would be eligible to receive a diploma. The time
of service is shortened if a veteran was discharged for an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Local school boards would be empowered to hand out the diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is recognizing the civics course that they saw and lived
first hand,'' said Rep. Mary Ann Carson, R-New Fairfield, whose
father was a World War II veteran.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 World War II veterans live in Connecticut. Sen.
Thomas Gaffey, the bill's chief sponsor, did not know how many
would be affected by the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Pelton's granddaughter, Colleen Fenn, wrote letters to dozens of
state officials in seeking passage of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Pelton, who worked 40 years in a Hartford foundry, said his lack
of a diploma didn't keep him from making a living, but was an
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ''When somebody asks you about it, it's kind of awkward,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pelton recalled, he didn't think twice about leaving
school for the service.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States was being threatened and England was in
trouble so there was just reason (to enlist),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gaffey, who received one of Fenn's letters, said the bill is
about ''setting things right.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a matter of dignity,'' the Meriden Democrat said. ''It's
a simple gesture we as a state can accord our veterans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 2004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
