<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mother of Slain Sergeant Files Claim  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- The mother of a black police sergeant
shot to death by two white officers filed a $20 million claim
against the city Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he were white, he'd be alive. It's not a very difficult
question to answer for me,'' said attorney Johnnie Cochran Jr., who
is representing Leisa Young, the mother of slain Sgt. Cornel Young
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   A state grand jury last week decided not to indict the two
officers who killed Young.
</P>
<P>
   Young, 29, was off duty and in street clothes when Officers
Carlos Saraiva, 30, and Michael Solitro, 33, mistook him for an
armed suspect in a violent fight and shot him. The officers'
defenders blamed inexperience for the Jan. 28 shooting, since
Solitro had been on patrol just seven nights. Saraiva was on the
force three years.
</P>
<P>
   Leisa Young is divorced from her son's father, Maj. Cornel Young
Sr., the highest-ranking black on the Providence force. Maj. Young
is not involved in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Vincent Cianci Jr. said he respected Leisa Young's right
to sue but rejected any criticism of the police.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think lawsuits if they're kept in the realm of legalities
and kept in the courtroom, they can be productive,'' Cianci said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
