<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tricon Reports Higher Earnings  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE SCHREINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Fast-food giant Tricon Global Restaurants
reported a 28 percent gain in first-quarter earnings Wednesday as
overseas sales surged and its pizza business surpassed
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The parent of Pizza Hut, Taco Bell and KFC had operating
earnings of $96 million, or 64 cents per share, for the quarter
ending March 18.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're off to a solid start and we want to keep it going,''
said David C. Novak, Tricon's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had projected first-quarter earnings would amount to 55
cents per share, according to a survey by First Call/Thomson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a gangbuster quarter,'' said Tony Howard, restaurant
analyst with Hilliard Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profits were up 33 percent in Tricon's international
business, which accounts for more than one-third of the company's
sales.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, Pizza Hut delivered better-than-expected
results. Sales at Tricon-owned stores open at least a year were 2
percent shy of last year, when sales soared 14 percent on the
successful introduction of The Big New Yorker pizza.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very pleased with Pizza Hut's strong sales and we are
optimistic it is well positioned to have a better-than-expected
2000,'' Novak said.
</P>
<P>
   Same-store sales at Taco Bell were slightly above last year's
first-quarter performance, the company said. At KFC, same-store
sales for the first quarter were down 3 percent from its
strongest-ever quarter in 1999. Sales from KFC's chicken sandwiches
continued to produce about $130,000 in average annualized sales for
each restaurant, above the $100,000 the company had expected when
the sandwich line was introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Tricon said it refranchised 183 restaurants during the quarter.
The company also invested more than $135 million to buy back 3.9
million of its shares as part of a $350 million share repurchase
effort announced last September. Since the share repurchase began,
Tricon has invested more than $270 million in buying back 7.2
million of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville-based Tricon's stock was up $1.18} at $34.43}
Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
