<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------
Canada Denounces Execution in Vietnam
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Canada has fiercely denounced the execution of a
Canadian citizen convicted in Vietnam of smuggling heroin.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy expressed shock
Wednesday at the unexpected execution of Nguyen Thi Hiep, who was
found with 5.4 kilograms of heroin in her luggage at a Hanoi
airport in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen, 43, was executed by firing squad early Monday at a Hanoi
jail.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Vietnam but became a Canadian citizen after
moving to Canada and settling in Montreal in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Toronto police forwarded extensive written and
audio information to Vietnamese authorities suggesting that Nguyen
''may have been duped into transporting drugs out of Vietnam,''
according to Raymond Chan, secretary of state for Asia-Pacific
relations.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Nova Scotia Tory President Quits
</P>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- The knocks against Joe Clark's
leadership of the federal Progressive Conservative party keep
coming.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Nova Scotia's Conservative party resigned
Wednesday to help organize Tom Long's bid for the Canadian Alliance
leadership, which is expected to become official today.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter of resignation, Tom Jarmyn said the federal party
under Clark's leadership has tried to be all things to all people,
adding that the only way to defeat the Chretien Liberals is to
build a broad-based conservative coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Jarmyn's criticism came on the heels of another blow to the
federal Tories: Tuesday's resignation of party whip Andre Harvey,
who has represented Quebec's Saguenay region for three terms.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Ontario Students To Sing National Anthem
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Pledging allegiance to the Queen will soon become
a daily ritual for every student in Ontario, a move not even avowed
monarchists are sure they like.
</P>
<P>
   Come September, students will have to recite the Oath of
Citizenship as part of a proposed code of conduct that includes
daily singing of O Canada, Education Minister Janet Ecker announced
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an important symbol that shows respect for our country,''
said Ecker, who was unable to recite by heart what she repeatedly
referred to as the citizenship pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchist League of Canada, which fought for years to keep
the Queen in the pledge, believes Ecker's intentions are good but
doesn't favor making the oath part of a daily school ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Manners, president of the Ontario Secondary School Teachers
Federation, is also unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Singing O Canada and reciting a pledge of citizenship that
even the minister doesn't know is hardly a solution to safer
schools,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Demonstrations in Halifax Against Education Budget Cuts
</P>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- Students continued to pour out of
Nova Scotia classrooms Wednesday to protest a $20-million cut to
education, defying pleas from teachers and school boards to stay in
school.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined in their defiance of the Conservative
government's cost-cutting budget by parents, teachers, nurses and
transportation workers at a noisy demonstration in front of the
legislature, which peaked at more than 3,000 late in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Tory budget promises to cut 1,600 public-service jobs,
including 400 teachers.
</P>
</TEXT>
