<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slain Teens Buried in N.M.  </HEADLINE>
By PETE HERRERA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA VILLITA, N.M. (AP) -- Two high school sweethearts who were
killed while making a Good Friday pilgrimage were buried
side-by-side Wednesday next to a small grove of cottonwood trees.
</P>
<P>
   Green and yellow balloons floated into the cloud-free sky as the
blue and cream-colored caskets were lowered simultaneously into
adjacent graves in the small cemetery in Ricky Martinez's hometown
of La Villita.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez and Karen Castanon, both 17, were shot to death before
dawn Friday as they walked to the Santuario de Chimayo,
participants in an annual pilgrimage that draws thousands to the
church in the small northern New Mexico village of Chimayo. The
church has a small hole in the floor exposing dirt that the
faithful believe has healing powers.
</P>
<P>
   Amid cries of ''We love you Ricky and Karen,'' relatives,
friends and classmates gave a heart-wrenching, tearful farewell to
the two Los Alamos High School juniors.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's body was found by another pilgrim along a road
leading to the church. Hours later, Castanon's body was found in a
remote hilly area. Both had been shot and left to bleed to death,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't make any sense out of it. I can never imagine how this
could ever happen to them,'' said Justin Hogan, a classmate of the
victims who attended the services Wednesday. ''They were two great
people, school-spirited and everything. They were friends with
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   While Martinez and Castanon were being buried, the man accused
of killing them marked his 20th birthday in jail. Carlos Herrera,
arrested early Sunday in the neighboring village of Alcalde, is
charged with murder and kidnapping. He is being held without bond.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not offered a motive for the killings other than to
say it did not appear to be robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral Mass was held at St. John The Baptist Catholic
Church, where Martinez was to have portrayed Jesus Christ during a
religious service on Good Friday evening. Good Friday commemorates
the sentencing and crucifixion of Christ.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
