<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Couple Eyes Canada Refugee Status  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Aisha and David Taylor are battling to do
something rare for U.S. citizens -- obtain refugee status in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Turned down by the Canadian Immigration Refugee Board, the black
couple now wants to appeal the rejection to a federal court. If the
appeal fails -- as more than 99 percent do -- they would have to
return to the United States, where they say they have been harassed
by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're here for political reasons,'' David Taylor, 41, said
Tuesday. ''We were persecuted for our political beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 200 applications by U.S. citizens for so-called
convention refugee status in Canada from 1995 to 1999, only one was
approved, said Paul Hardy, a spokesman for the Immigration Refugee
Board.
</P>
<P>
   The Taylors say they qualify because of FBI harassment under a
government program against black activism, known as COINTELPRO. The
Taylors claimed that the program was directed against black
activists in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the program was dismantled in 1971 but the
Taylors say it continued operating and targeted them after Aisha
led a successful challenge against the Charlottesville, Va., school
system's treatment of black students in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   They claimed in 4,000 pages of documents filed with their appeal
that the FBI tapped their phones, intercepted calls, stole their
mail and planted surveillance devices in their home.
</P>
<P>
   They say such harassment deprived them of a ''normal life'' in
the United States, making them eligible to seek convention refugee
status in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Johlie, an FBI spokeswoman in Richmond, said Wednesday she
was unaware of any FBI records involving the Taylors.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Immigration Refugee Board rejected the Taylors'
application for refugee status because of a lack of evidence. The
couple can remain in Canada until all appeals have been exhausted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 2043 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
