<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Says He Would Restore Civility  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush, addressing Washington's
Republican elite at a record-breaking fund-raiser, promised
Wednesday to reach across party lines and end a ''cycle of
bitterness, an arms race of anger'' that stymies progress in the
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   On his first trip to Washington since sealing the Republican
presidential nomination, the Texas governor said ''both parties
bear some of the blame'' for excessive partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will set a different tone in Washington, D.C. I will restore
civility and respect to our national politics,'' he said in a
keynote speech.
</P>
<P>
   The audience included the GOP's top politicians, operatives and
donors -- most of whom understood Bush's critique of both parties as
an appeal to independent-minded voters who tell pollsters they are
tired of partisan bickering.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 1,500 fell silent when Bush said both parties are
to blame for partisan mudslinging and gave him his loudest applause
when he promised to ''respond aggressively'' when attacked by
Democratic rival Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he promised a more civil discourse, Bush offered
full-throated criticism of Gore, accusing the vice president of
running a negative political operation. ''For Al Gore's campaign,
every day is scorched-earth day,'' Bush said. ''It's time to clean
up the toxic environment in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   He was the keynote speaker at a GOP gala that organizers
announced had raised $21.5 million for the Republican Party, a
record for political fund-raisers. Bush has raised more than $80
million for his own campaign, a record in itself.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner's guest list included many officials from major
companies doing business with the government. Nearly 40 companies
or individuals raised or donated at least $250,000 for the gala,
and an additional 16 contributed at least $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Though campaigning as a political outsider, the Texan and his
aides took advantage of the trip to strengthen their bonds to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Strategist Karl Rove, top fund-raiser Don Evans, campaign
manager Joe Allbaugh and communications director Karen Hughes met
or planned to meet with party officials in Washington this week.
They were discussing how to blend operations of the campaign and
the Republican National Committee, as well as how to gather advice
from top Washington Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was leaving town Thursday morning but his team planned to
remain in Washington through Saturday for a series of meetings,
including their first major strategy session for the Republican
National Convention in August. Bush is still without a convention
chairman, a key slot he hopes to fill soon.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself met Wednesday with Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov to discuss U.S.-Russian relations. The Texan's grasp of
foreign affairs has been a question mark over the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also met privately with Democratic Sen. Bob Kerrey
of Nebraska to discuss Social Security reform. The meeting was
meant to symbolize Bush's commitment to bipartisanship; Texas
Democrats favoring Bush over Gore accompanied the governor on a
campaign trip this week.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, Nebraska chairman of Gore's campaign, said he believed
both Bush and Gore were capable of working with lawmakers in both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think either one of them understand that you're going to
have a closely divided House and Senate, regardless of what happens
in the general election,'' Kerrey told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Americans crave bipartisanship after ''eight years of
excessive partisanship and finger pointing, eight years of attempts
to exploit fear and foster division, all to score political
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Laying most of the blame on Democrats, he said, ''The
Clinton-Gore administration has been the most relentlessly partisan
administration in our nation's history, but sometimes some in our
party have responded in kind. Americans have seen a cycle of
bitterness, an arms race of anger.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said donors at the dinner, including
the National Rifle Association and tobacco companies, ''have been
the biggest impediments, obstacles and walls to real reform in this
country. For him to preach nonpartisanship is sort of like talking
about tolerance and then going to Bob Jones University.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the South Carolina university have criticized
interracial dating and the Catholic Church. Bush spoke at the
university during the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Bush calling Gore a negative campaigner, the vice
president's team fired off a list of examples of Bush criticizing
Gore in highly personal terms.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the back-and-forth, Bush promised a more civil approach as
president. Bill Clinton in 1992, campaigning for his first term in
office, made the same promise as a southern governor trying to
become president.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will treat the other party with respect and when we make
progress for the American people, I will be willing to share the
credit,'' he told the GOP crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Before the fund-raiser, Doris Haddock, the 90-year-old New
Hampshire woman who walked cross-country to promote campaign
finance reform, was turned away for trying to attend without a
ticket. She wanted to speak with Bush, who opposes most proposed
campaign finance changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
