<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson confronts Klan in Wallingford  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson confronted a
group of white supremacists at a downtown rally Wednesday, as he
applauded a new law that forces the town to observe Martin Luther
King Day along with the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Wallingford is the only town in Connecticut that keeps its
offices open on King Day. A state law signed Wednesday requires all
municipalities to observe the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 people waving Confederate flags protested Jackson's
visit and shouted at Jackson through a bullhorn as he preached at a
downtown church.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson offered to shake hands and tried to peek under the face
mask of one man who was dressed in Ku Klux Klan garb, but he was
rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time for sheets to be worn on a bed and not to hide a
person's face,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The man in the Klan robe with the frayed hem said he was not
preaching hate but wanted to demonstrate pride in his white race.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Jackson of not standing up for white people who have
been killed by blacks in Africa and in American cities.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters refused to give their names, saying they feared
reprisals on the job, in the media and in the community.
</P>
<P>
   About 600 people, including many residents of Wallingford of all
races, came out to support Jackson with a candlelight march and
rally from the church to town hall in the drizzling, cold rain.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is good to see the real Wallingford stand up,'' Jackson
told the crowd inside St. Paul's Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   Many shouted ''Jesse!'' above the bullhorn-amplified shouts of
the white supremacists at the town hall rally. Others, including
Candy Gehring, waved handwritten placards in protest of the Klan
display.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are disgraced by having this in our town. I'm ashamed to
live here,'' said Gehring, 19.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the steps of town hall, Jackson urged the crowd to
''love people who do not understand and are trapped in fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate gave final legislative approval to the King Day
bill minutes before midnight Tuesday, and Gov. John G. Rowland
signed it Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm glad this governor signed this bill today to make a
statement for the country and for the world,'' the civil rights
leader said between privately meeting with Rowland and addressing
the state House of Representatives in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Wallingford Mayor William Dickinson has ''slept
through a revolution'' while leading the only town in the state
which has not closed its municipal offices on King Day, despite a
1986 law making it a state holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may be looking at a Rip Van Winkle situation where some
people sleep too long,'' Jackson said. ''And while they're asleep,
the world passes them by.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson has said the controversy is not about race, but a
dispute with the town's labor unions. Dickinson wants town workers
to swap another holiday for King Day, but union leaders want
workers to get the day off as an extra paid holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson could not be reached for comment Wednesday. Calls to
his office and home were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Jan. 17 holiday this year, three people wearing Ku
Klux Klan hoods and robes walked along Main Street in Wallingford.
On the holiday, one of those people stood near a church where a
celebration honoring King was being held. Neo-Nazi literature also
has been distributed around the town.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to make bigots feel uncomfortable in
Wallingford and everywhere else,'' said Rep. Mary Mushinsky,
D-Wallingford. ''And it's important that my hometown, Wallingford,
reiterates that we are a town that thrives on diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   While at the Capitol, Jackson also took time to call for prison
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to a national report released this week that says
minority youths are treated less fairly than their white peers by
the judicial system, Jackson called for a change in the way young
black and Latino offenders are dealt with.
</P>
<P>
   He said improved education in communities and prisons will
reduce criminal recidivism rates among juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now they leave jail sicker and slicker and return to jail
quicker,'' Jackson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 2051 </TRAILER>
