<HEADLINE> Jackson Confronts Klan in Conn.  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALLINGFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson confronted a
group of white supremacists here Wednesday after applauding
lawmakers and the governor for passing a law that forces the town
to close its offices on Martin Luther King Day.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was in Wallingford for a rally in support of the
legislation that will require all municipalities in Connecticut to
recognize the holiday. Wallingford is the only town in the state
that keeps its offices open on King Day.
</P>
<P>
   A group of about 10 people waving Confederate flags showed up to
protest Jackson's visit. Jackson offered to shake the hand of one
man who was dressed in Ku Klux Klan garb, but was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time for sheets to be worn on a bed and not to hide a
person's face,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation occurred before Jackson attended a church
service and led a march of over 500 people to town hall for a rally
supporting the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is good to see the real Wallingford stand up,'' Jackson
told the crowd inside St. Paul's Episcopal Church.
</P>
<P>
   As the group marched through town, the white supremacists
marched beside them shouting taunts.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate gave final approval to the King Day bill late
Tuesday, and Gov. John Rowland signed it Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to make bigots feel uncomfortable in
Wallingford and everywhere else,'' said Democratic state Rep. Mary
Mushinsky. ''And its' important that my hometown Wallingford
reiterates that we are a town that thrives on diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallingford Mayor William Dickinson has said the controversy is
not about race, but a dispute with the town's labor unions. He
wants town workers to swap another holiday for King Day, but union
leaders want workers to get the day off as an extra paid holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson did not return telephone calls seeking comment
Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
