<HEADLINE> NH Gets Female Supreme Court Justice  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- The state's first female governor on
Wednesday swore in its first female Supreme Court justice, making
New Hampshire the 49th state to name a woman to its high court.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeanne Shaheen swore in Linda Dalianis during a crowded
Statehouse reception.
</P>
<P>
   Dalianis, 51, of Nashua, was named Superior Court chief justice
just one month ago, and her promotion comes at a difficult time for
the Supreme Court. She will replace former Justice Stephen Thayer,
who resigned on March 31 rather than face prosecution for allegedly
trying to influence his own divorce case.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Legislature is investigating whether other
justices committed impeachable ethics violations.
</P>
<P>
   ''She brings an incredible amount of integrity, fairness and
understanding of the process,'' Shaheen said. ''I'm glad I was
governor at a time when I had the opportunity to appoint the first
woman to the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalianis said she must help restore public confidence in the
court.
</P>
<P>
   South Dakota is the only state yet to name a woman to its high
court.
</P>
</TEXT>
