<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujimori Expects Quick Vote Results  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori said Wednesday that
speedy returns in a clean and open runoff election will lay to rest
international concerns about the fairness of Peru's presidential
vote.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton on Tuesday signed a congressional resolution
warning Fujimori that economic and diplomatic relations with
between the two nations could suffer if the Peruvian government
does not respect democratic processes in the upcoming ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori said he was not concerned by Clinton's message because
his government was striving to provide the free and fair elections
sought by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori will face economist Alejandro Toledo in a second round
showdown in late May or early June.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the first round there were accusations that caused damage
to the image of Peru. Of that there is no doubt,'' the president
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori fell just shy of the majority he needed for a first
round victory in an April 9 election so riddled with irregularities
and accusations of fraud that much of the international community
all but insisted on a second round.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials took three days to tally enough votes to
determine that Fujimori had fallen short of an unprecedented third
term. The delay increased suspicions of election rigging, which
Fujimori has denied.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the second round, with results that we expect will come in
much more quickly, we will be able to recuperate Peru's good
image,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has accused Fujimori and his supporters of dragging their
feet on a proposed pact to conduct a clean runoff election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
