<DOCNO> APW20000426.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broadway Producer Merrick Dies  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA, AP Drama Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Broadway producer David Merrick, whose savvy
sense of show business and popular taste helped create such
enduring musical hits as ''Gypsy,'' ''Hello, Dolly!'' and ''42nd
Street,'' has died at age 88.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick, who died Tuesday in London, had been ill for some time,
having suffered a stroke in 1983 that left him severely disabled
and forced him to use a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick dominated New York theater in Broadway's Golden Age
after World War II, producing more than 80 shows including
''Oliver!,'' ''Carnival,'' ''Fanny,'' ''Look Back in Anger,''
''Becket,'' ''Irma La Douce,'' ''Play It Again, Sam,'' ''A Taste of
Honey,'' ''Stop the World -- I Want to Get Off,'' ''Cactus Flower,''
''Philadelphia, Here I Come,'' ''Forty Carats,'' ''I Do! I Do!''
and ''Promises, Promises.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I loved the man, and he certainly knew how to handle
publicity,'' Carol Channing, the original star of ''Hello,
Dolly!'', said Wednesday. ''I always called him 'Mr. Merrick.' I
couldn't call him 'David.' I had too much respect for his
showmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   That showmanship was the stuff of Broadway legend, stunts that
often outraged critics but brought people to the box office for his
plays and musicals.
</P>
<P>
   One of his most famous involved the musical ''Subways Are for
Sleeping,'' which received tepid notices from the critics.
Undeterred, Merrick took a newspaper ad with rave quotes from seven
men who just happened to have the same names as the critics for New
York's seven daily newspapers. The ad ran in one edition of the New
York Herald-Tribune before it was noticed -- and then yanked.
</P>
<P>
   ''He couldn't care less what was said about him, as long as his
shows were mentioned,'' recalled Lee Solters, a veteran press agent
who was with Merrick from his first musical hit, ''Fanny,'' in
1954.
</P>
<P>
   The reviews for ''Fanny,'' which starred Ezio Pinza, Walter
Slezak and newcomer Florence Henderson, were largely negative. Yet
the producer got a two-year run out of the show through heavy
advertising -- in such faraway places as the French Riviera -- and a
series of stunts that kept it in the news. Among his gimmicks: He
placed a life-size nude statue of the musical's belly dancer in
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick was a master at extending the lives of his productions
through big-name casting, too. He was one of the first producers to
use stars to replace stars. With ''Hello, Dolly!'', he had a
succession of famous Dollys follow Channing in the title role,
including Ginger Rogers, Martha Raye, Betty Grable, Pearl Bailey,
Phyllis Diller and Ethel Merman, who closed the show after a run of
2,844 performances.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s and 1960s, the producer reportedly grossed $20
million annually, earning $2 million a year from his hits. His
productions have won countless Tony Awards -- ''Hello, Dolly!''
alone picked up 10 Tonys in 1964 -- as well as other theater prizes
including the New York Drama Critics' Circle Award and London's
Olivier Award.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dolly'' was one of the producer's biggest triumphs. It was
based on Thornton Wilder's ''The Matchmaker,'' which Merrick had
produced successfully on Broadway nearly 10 years earlier with Ruth
Gordon as Dolly Levi.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick was not above bringing culture and serious drama to
Broadway either, particularly the work of British playwrights. He
imported plays by John Osborne, Tom Stoppard, Shelagh Delaney and
Joe Orton, as well as Irish author Brian Friel.
</P>
<P>
   His flops were well-known, too, particularly ''Breakfast at
Tiffany's,'' which never officially opened in New York despite the
potent box-office draw of two television stars, Mary Tyler Moore
and Richard Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, despite his infirmities, Merrick invested heavily
in the 1996 musical ''State Fair,'' based on the 1945 and 1962
films of that name. It also failed to make any money.
</P>
<P>
   Born in St. Louis, Merrick attended Washington University and
later St. Louis University, where he majored in law. In 1946, he
became general manager for director and producer Herman Shumlin.
Three years later, Merrick produced his first play,
''Clutterbuck,'' which closed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick's private life was as stormy as his public one. He had
five wives and six marriages. He was married to wife No. 3, Etan,
twice, and the couple frequently battled in court over their
divorce proceedings. His fourth wife was Karen Prunczik, who played
Anytime Annie in the original company of ''42nd Street.'' In 1989,
Natalie Lloyd, his lawyer's receptionist, became his live-in
companion. They were married last November.
</P>
<P>
   One of Merrick's most dramatic successes, ''42nd Street,''
occurred late in his producing career. Adapted from the 1933 Ruby
Keeler movie, the musical had a run of more than eight years, the
longest of any Merrick show. It was directed by Gower Champion, who
died of a rare blood cancer hours before the New York opening in
August 1980. Merrick announced Champion's death to a stunned
opening-night audience immediately after the curtain came down.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Merrick is survived by two daughters
from previous marriages, Cecilia Anne of Mullica Hill, N.J., and
Marguerite of New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
