<HEADLINE> Bill To Give Vets Diplomas Advanced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- State lawmakers unanimously passed a bill
Wednesday that would grant diplomas to World War II veterans who
left high school to join the military.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is recognizing the civics course that they saw and lived
first hand,'' said Rep. Mary Ann Carson, R-New Fairfield, whose
father was a World War II veteran.
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 World War II veterans live in Connecticut, although
it's unknown how many would be affected by the measure. The bill
would give local school boards the authority to give diplomas to
any veteran honorably discharged after at least 90 days of service,
or less time if the veteran was discharged for an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''There wasn't time for it after I got out of the service,''
said Hudson C. Pelton, who left school to join the Navy in 1942,
when he was 17. ''The United States was being threatened and
England was in trouble so there was just reason (to enlist).''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill passed Wednesday must be reconciled with a Senate
version before being sent to the governor. Gov. John G. Rowland has
said he would sign it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
