<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Viacom Reports Pre-Merger Earnings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Viacom Inc., owner of the MTV cable channel and
the Blockbuster video chain, reported a large jump in net earnings
in the latest fiscal quarter, which will likely be its last
reporting period before merging with CBS Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom earned $76 million, or 11 cents per share, in the three
months ended March 31, compared to $44.9 million, or 5 cents a
share, in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The year-ago results included $23.5 million in expenses relating
to early retirement of debt, without which profits would have been
$68.4 million, or 8 cents a share, making this year's result an
increase of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The per-share earnings of 11 cents far exceeded the 6 cents per
share forecast by analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson
Financial. The company's stock was priced at $54.56\ at 5:15 p.m.
EST on the New York Stock Exchange, up $2.81\ or more than 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues rose 2.5 percent to $3.03 billion from $2.95 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings announcement came a week after Federal
Communications Commission staff recommended that the commission
approve Viacom's merger deal with CBS, provided the companies sell
assets to comply with federal rules.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would own television stations reaching 41
percent of the national audience, but current rules limit that
amount to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Current FCC rules also prohibit one company from owning two
broadcast networks, a complicating factor for the combined company,
which would own both CBS and UPN. But that rule is currently being
reviewed by the FCC and could be relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   On March 31, Viacom acquired the 50 percent of UPN that it
didn't already own from Chris-Craft Industries for $5 million,
ending a troubled partnership with the former boat builder-turned
media company.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Justice Department said Wednesday that it won't
seek to block the proposed merger.
</P>
<P>
   The department determined after a thorough investigation of the
merger that ''the proposed transaction did not violate the
antitrust laws,'' said Justice spokeswoman Gina Talamona.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom's biggest revenue gains in the quarter came from its
cable networks business, which includes MTV, VH1 and Showtime.
Revenues in that segment rose 14 percent to $760 million.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues from entertainment slipped 3 percent as theaters had
lower results because of adding new multiplexes. But earnings from
television stations and syndication of shows such as ''Judge Judy''
were higher.
</P>
<P>
   Publishing revenues slipped 8 percent on lower sales in the
company's Pocket Books division.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
