<HEADLINE> Korea Officials Meet Before Summit  </HEADLINE>
By KYONG-HWA SEOK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) -- North and South Korean officials held a
second round of talks Thursday in preparation for June's first-ever
summit between leaders of the rival nations.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting opened at Unification House, an administrative
building in the northern sector of Panmunjom, a border village
inside the 2{-mile-wide demilitarized zone separating the Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   At the first meeting on the southern side of the village last
Saturday, South Korea presented its proposed agenda and other
details for the June 12-14 summit in the North's capital of
Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   The summit would be the first between leaders of the Koreas,
which were divided into the communist North and the pro-Western
South in 1945. The two signed no peace treaty at the end of the
1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   For the agenda, South Korea proposed four topics -- economic
cooperation, peace measures, the reunion of separated family
members and the establishment of a permanent government channel of
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea was expected to make its proposals at the second
round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   In previous talks, the North has complained about South Korea's
anti-communist national security law and the presence of 37,000
American troops in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials say the summit between their president,
Kim Dae-jung, and North Korean leader Kim Jong Il will be in
jeopardy if North Korea insists that such topics be included in the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The summit comes as the impoverished North Korea has become
increasingly desperate for aid to rebuild its dilapidated economy.
U.N. figures show that the communist country has received more than
dlrs 1.2 billion in emergency outside aid since 1995 to feed its 22
million people.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office more than two years ago, Kim has pushed a
so-called ''sunshine'' policy of engaging North Korea. He believes
the summit is a product of his policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
