<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amateur astronomers capture rare gamma burst  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH JAVA, N.Y. (AP) -- Two nights on a cold, damp hillside paid
off for four amateur astronomers who succeeded in capturing the
faint afterglow of an explosion in space that occurred billions of
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Only two other astronomers in the world, both professionals,
recorded the gamma ray burst early March 4. The four amateurs were
honored this month by NASA.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was pretty neat,'' Frank Chalupka said of the High Energy
Astrophysics Workshop he attended with the others at NASA's
Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala. ''Just about
everybody there had a Ph.D. They were calling us '''the Buffalo
group.'''
</P>
<P>
   Chalupka is a technical representative for Simplex Systems in
Williamsville. Two of the others, Dennis Hohman and Bill Aquino,
are technical writers at TX RX Systems in Angola. Tom Bakowski is a
junior at Orchard Park High School.
</P>
<P>
   The group captured the phenomenon using a 12-inch mirror which
reflected the gamma burst into the lens of a homemade digital
camera they had duct-taped to the barrel of their 40-year-old
telescope.
</P>
<P>
   In Huntsville, they were toasted for being the only amateur
astronomers, among 65 or so around the world, who had aimed
telescopes toward the constellation Hercules to capture the
celestial phenomenon. They were among the first amateurs in the
world to record one of these powerful explosions.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo Astronomical Association team had been alerted by
Internet postings that spacecraft had detected a gamma ray burst
near Hercules. The group assembled at Beaver Meadow Observatory,
about 35 miles southeast of Buffalo, on the evening of March 3 only
to be thwarted by rain. By 2 a.m. the next day, the sky had cleared
and the telescope was trained on the coordinates supplied by
professional astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   Gamma ray bursts are so faint and fade so quickly they are
extremely difficult to find, even with the largest of telescopes.
Gamma ray burst 00301(C), as this one was called, had a brightness
of the 20th magnitude -- a comparable star would be a million times
dimmer than the dimmest stars visible to the naked eye.
</P>
<P>
   The group focused on the location for two hours and enlisted the
help of Arne Henden, a professional astronomer at the U.S. Naval
Observatory near Flagstaff Ariz., to upload five-minute exposures
into a computer.
</P>
<P>
   To the untrained eye, the pictures despict nothing more than
dark spots on a light background.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're part of the early response network,'' Aquino said. ''Our
job is to find and monitor these events until the big guns can get
on them.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what that night was about -- to see if we could pull it
off,'' Hohman said.
</P>
<P>
   Gamma ray bursts result from explosions of incredible violence,
such as the collision of neutron stars. The first was detected less
than 30 years ago and the first afterglow was recorded by the
Hubble space telescope three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here was an event that occurred in the neighborhood of 12
billion to 15 billion years ago,'' Aquino said. ''When the light
left (the point of impact), the Earth and sun didn't even exist.
They're only 5 billion years old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 2132 </TRAILER>
