<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protest cost police, agencies $500,000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MORRISTOWN, N.J. (AP) -- A three-day protest at a World Bank
conference cost state, county and local police and other agencies
over $500,000, law enforcement officials announced Wednesday. Much
of that is for overtime costs.
</P>
<P>
   The protest, which attracted about 200 demonstrators the weekend
of April 1-2, led to nine arrests for charges including trespassing
and failing to disperse, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Something of this financial size is new,'' said Capt.
Christopher Linne of the Morris County prosecutor's office.
</P>
<P>
   The county police chief's group has asked Rep. Rodney
Frelinghuysen, a Republican whose district includes much of Morris
County, to help find compensation, Linne said.
</P>
<P>
   The largest costs were borne by the sheriff's department,
$173,511; Florham Park police, $43,872; and the Morris County
prosecutor's office, $31,325, according to an accounting
distributed by the group.
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers had originally told police that at least 500
protestors could be expected at the Hamilton Park Conference Center
in Florham Park.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was sponsored by the World Bank, International
Monetary Fund and the Brookings Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The rally was organized by a coalition of grassroots groups
called the New Jersey/New York Mobilization for Global Justice. The
groups maintained that the World Bank and the IMF, charged with
improving life in developing countries, instead throw the countries
into debt while enriching corporations and degrading the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Police determined that some of the groups planning to attend
participated in the rioting at the World Trade Organization
conference in Seattle in December.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, authorities activated the highest level of the
Morris County Regional Deployment System, drawing personnel from
every police department in the county to provide a 24-hour
presence.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was clear from all the advance information that the protest
could be on a scale that could quickly overwhelm the resources of
the Florham Park Police Department as well as the contiguous
municipalities that would usually provide mutual aid in an
emergency situation,'' according to a statement from Morris County
Prosecutor John B. Dangler and the chiefs association.
</P>
<P>
   Every town in Morris County, except for Victory Gardens, which
has no police department, contributed personnel to the effort, as
did several agencies from the state and neighboring counties,
including NJ Transit, $9,207; and the Passaic County Sheriff's
Department, $5,217.
</P>
<P>
   The regional deployment system was created last year to deal
with natural disasters and civil disturbances, Linne said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-26-00 2148 </TRAILER>
