<HEADLINE> Violence at Bolivia-Colombia Match  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A linesman was hit in the head by a bottle thrown
from the
stands Wednesday during Bolivia's 1-1 tie with Colombia in a World
Cup qualifier.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The game was suspended for almost 10 minutes in the second half
after linesman Yuri Pineda was hit. Pineda recovered and finished
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Erwin Sanchez scored off a free kick in the 16th minute for
Bolivia (0-1-1). Jairo Castillo answered for Colombia (0-0-2) in
the 32nd minute.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez was expelled in the 76th minute for arguing with referee
Jose Arana of Peru, and was joined two minutes later by Colombia's
Mario Yepez, who was ejected for a foul.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, four-time World Cup champion Brazil met
Ecuador, Paraguay edged Uruguay 1-0, Venezuela played Argentina,
and Chile took on Peru.
</P>
<P>
   In an exhibition games, Russia extended its unbeaten streak
against the United States to four with a 2-0 victory
</P>
<P>
   Igor Titov scored in early in the first half and Valery Karpin
added a goal two minutes into injury time in the first game played
between the teams in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay's victory came on Celso Ayala's first-half goal. Ayala
drove in a header in the 35th minute as Paraguay improved to 1-1,
the same record as Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Defending World Cup champion France scored three times in the
second half, including David Trezeguet's goal in the 94th minute,
to rally for a 3-2 win over Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   Italy behind goals from Filippo Inzaghi and Francesco Totti,
blanked Portugal 2-0 in another exhibition, while South Korea and
Japan, the co-hosts for the 2002 World Cup, played a 1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   In other exhibitions, it was: Czech Republic 4, Israel 1;
Macedonia 1, Albania 0; Romania 2, Cyprus 0; Ukraine 1, Bulgaria 0;
Sweden 1, Denmark 0; Greece 1, Ireland 0; Germany 1, Switzerland 1;
Belgium 2, Norway 0; Hungary 1, Northern Ireland 0.
</P>
<P>
   Armenia and Georgia, Poland and Finland, and the Netherlands and
Scotland all played scoreless ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
