<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, April 26, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Awaits Visit From Teacher, Friends
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez's former kindergarten teacher and a
10-year-old cousin from Cuba flew into Washington's Reagan National Airport
tonight and were driven to an undisclosed location. In addition, four of the
6-year-old boy's classmates, along with three of their mothers and one father,
are expected to receive visas from the U.S. diplomatic mission in Havana and fly
to the United States tomorrow. ''A young 6-year-old ... needs to have someone to
play with,'' State Department spokesman James Rubin said. Elian remained
secluded in rural Maryland with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, stepmother and
half brother.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Says He Would Restore Civility
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush, addressing Washington's Republican elite
at a record-breaking $21 million fund-raiser, promised tonight to reach across
party lines and end a ''cycle of bitterness, an arms race of anger'' that
stymies progress in the nation's capital. ''I will set a different tone in
Washington, D.C. I will restore civility and respect to our national politics,''
he said in a keynote speech. The crowd of 1,500 fell silent when Bush said both
parties are to blame for partisan mudslinging and gave him his loudest applause
when he promised to ''respond aggressively'' when attacked by Democratic rival
Al Gore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gun Group Alleges Trade Conspiracy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seven gun makers and an industry group sued the Department
of Housing and Urban Development and 16 cities today over a plan to give
preferential treatment to Smith &AMP; Wesson when buying guns for law enforcement
agencies. The lawsuit filed in an Atlanta federal court alleges an illegal
conspiracy in restraint of trade. Under the agreement, Smith &AMP; Wesson was to be
dropped from lawsuits against gun makers that were being contemplated by federal
officials and some cities. In addition to Smith &AMP; Wesson, any other gun maker
that agreed to the plan would also be given preferential treatment.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pets.com Socks It to 'Late Night'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Online pet supply store Pets.com says the friendly
reputation of its kitschy ''spokespuppet'' has been defamed by a foul-mouthed
dog puppet featured on NBC's ''Late Night With Conan O'Brien.'' In a federal
lawsuit filed last week, Pets.com accuses ''Late Night'' writer Robert Smigel,
creator of the show's ''Triumph the Insult Comic Dog,'' of defaming the
ubiquitous sock puppet. Marc Liepis, a spokesman for ''Late Night,'' said
neither the show nor Smigel would comment on the lawsuit. But, he noted that the
cigar-smoking Triumph made his debut long before the arrival of the sock puppet.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Deliberates Pinochet Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Amid clashes between foes and followers of Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, a court today began deliberating on whether the former
dictator should stand trial on human rights abuse charges. Judges will decide if
Pinochet can keep the immunity from prosecution he currently enjoys as a
senator-for-life, a post he created for himself during his 1973-90 regime. a
trial of the former ruler. According to an official report, 3,191 people were
killed or disappeared during Pinochet's 17 years in power.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Korean Officials Meet Before Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) -- North and South Korean officials held a second round
of talks Thursday in preparation for June's first-ever summit between leaders of
the rival nations. The Koreas were divided into the communist North and the
pro-Western South in 1945 and signed no peace treaty at the end of the 1950-53
Korean War. For the agenda, South Korea proposed four topics -- economic
cooperation, peace measures, the reunion of separated family members and the
establishment of a permanent government channel of dialogue. North Korea was
expected to make its proposals at the second round of talks.
</P>
