<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Ravaged Mozambique Still Needy  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW SELSKY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Images of Mozambicans clinging
to trees above swirling floodwaters are already a fading memory,
but their country now faces a critical phase in its recovery, a top
U.N. official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The flood victims who were plucked to safety by helicopters have
been returning to their homes -- or what's left of them -- and need
roads, bridges, schools and hospitals rebuilt, said Mark Malloch
Brown, head of the United Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, a system of dams that will hold back floodwaters
that poured into Mozambique last February and March from upstream
neighboring countries Zimbabwe and South Africa also needs to be
constructed to prevent a recurrence of the disaster, Malloch Brown
said in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''The second act is starting,'' said Malloch Brown, who will be
hosting an international donor conference for Mozambique in Rome on
May 3-4.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to raise dlrs 450 million in the Rome conference, which
will be attended by representatives of dozens of nations, aid
agencies and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of countries and aid groups provided emergency aid to
Mozambique during the height of the crisis. But other crises -- a
looming famine in Ethiopia, violent political turmoil in Zimbabwe --
have grabbed headlines since the floodwaters receded, and threaten
to distract donors from following through on Mozambique's recovery,
Malloch Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The southeast African country had once been a poster child for
the misery that can strike the continent. A 15-year civil war
killed 600,000 people before it ended in 1992. Marxists who took
over from the departing Portuguese colonial government in 1975
struggled to build the country, which nevertheless stagnated as one
of the world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   But after the government liberalized its economy in the
mid-1980s, foreign investors flocked in. The country's economy
recently averaged 10 percent annual growth. Most Mozambicans
remained poor, but the economic boom held the promise of a better
future.
</P>
<P>
   Then the floods came.
</P>
<P>
   Torrential rains from two cyclones swept away the homes or
livelihoods of 10 percent of Mozambique's 19 million people. They
damaged more than 600 primary schools, wrecked more than 620 miles
of roads and downed 250 miles of power lines.
</P>
<P>
   Crops in fertile river valleys in central and southern
Mozambique were destroyed. Large tracts of agricultural land have
become quagmires.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Luisa Biogo recently cut economic growth
projections to 6 percent for this year, and said inflation would
almost double to 10 percent. The World Bank's preliminary estimates
of the cost of the flooding is about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Malloch Brown, speaking from Dakar, Senegal, where he was
attending an education conference, said donors should help
Mozambique recover totally from the disaster, in order to keep one
of the continent's rare success stories going.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 2203 </TRAILER>
