<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinals Break Home Run Record  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Pitcher Rick Ankiel, Jim Edmonds and Fernando
Tatis homered Wednesday night as the St. Louis Cardinals set a
major league record with 50 home runs in April.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals broke the mark of 49 set by the 1997 Cleveland
Indians. They have four games left to chase the record for homers
in any month, 58 by the 1987 Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, St. Louis broke the previous National League record
of 41 by the 1998 Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   All three homers came off Steve Woodard of the Milwaukee
Brewers. Ankiel hit a three-run shot in the fourth, Edmonds had a
leadoff homer in the fifth, and Tatis broke the record with a
two-run shot later in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have homered in 17 straight games, tying the team
record set in 1998, with 40 homers in that span. They've connected
in all but one of their 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis hit 194 home runs last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
