<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressJonathan Allen:
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Jonathan Allen, an MIT professor who
developed a talking computer at a time when such a machine sounded
like science fiction, died Monday. He was 65.
</P>
<P>
   Allen received worldwide notice in the 1970s for creating a
computer named Morris that could talk and read. A computer system
developed by Allen has been used to aid physicist Stephen Hawking,
who is paralyzed as a result of Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   A member of MIT's faculty since 1968, Allen had directed the
school's research laboratory of electronics since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's research centered on speech processing, computational
linguistics, computer architecture and integrated electronics.
Jack Best:
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Jack Best, who helped build a glider for an
audacious plan to escape from Germany's Colditz prison during World
War II, died Saturday. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners at Colditz were freed by Allied forces before the
glider could be tried, but a reconstruction made for a television
program last year proved that the craft could have flown.
</P>
<P>
   Best, a Royal Air Force pilot, was captured in 1941 after he was
forced to ditch his plane off the coast of Greece. He was held at
Stalag Luft III prison -- known from the film ''The Great Escape'' --
but tunneled out with fellow prisoner Bill Goldfinch. They made it
125 miles to Szczecin, Poland before being recaptured.
</P>
<P>
   Best was then sent to Colditz, a huge Saxon castle near Leipzig
where the Germans put their most escape-prone Allied prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Best worked with Goldfinch and two other prisoners to build a
glider with a 32-foot wingspan in an attic above the chapel.
Andre Jarrot:
</P>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Andre Jarrot, a French Resistance hero who went on
to a successful political career, died Thursday. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac described him as ''a legendary figure
of Free France'' during World War II who ''dedicated his life to
his country and his fellow citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrot was parachuted many times into Nazi-occupied territory in
France and led sabotage operations against key French industrial
sites fueling the German war effort.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he was mayor of Montceau-les-Mines in Burgundy
from 1965 to 1986 and a member of the European Parliament from
1962-1984. Jarrot also was Quality of Life Minister from 1974-76
and a member of the French Senate from 1986 to 1995. He was a
founding member of the Union for the New Republic, the predecessor
of Chirac's center-right Rally for the Republic party.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrot was captured by the Germans following the French
capitulation in the summer of 1940, but quickly escaped. He made
his way by bicycle back to Burgundy, where he soon devised escape
routes for other prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Some 4,000 Allied airmen, shot down in Europe during the war,
are thought to have escaped from German hands thanks to Jarrot's
careful planning. He was arrested again by the Gestapo in 1942, but
was released for lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the United States, Britain and Belgium decorated
him for his heroism. Gen. Charles de Gaulle awarded him the Cross
of the Liberation, one of France's highest military honors.
David Merrick:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Broadway producer David Merrick, whose savvy
sense of show business and popular taste helped create such
enduring musical hits as ''Gypsy,'' ''Hello, Dolly!'' and ''42nd
Street,'' died Tuesday. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick dominated New York theater in Broadway's Golden Age
after World War II, producing more than 80 shows including
''Oliver!,'' ''Carnival,'' ''Fanny,'' ''Look Back in Anger,''
''Becket,'' ''Irma La Douce,'' ''Play It Again, Sam,'' ''A Taste of
Honey,'' ''Stop the World -- I Want to Get Off,'' ''Cactus Flower,''
''Philadelphia, Here I Come,'' ''Forty Carats,'' ''I Do! I Do!''
and ''Promises, Promises.''
</P>
<P>
   The reviews for ''Fanny,'' which starred Ezio Pinza, Walter
Slezak and newcomer Florence Henderson, were largely negative. Yet
the producer got a two-year run out of the show through heavy
advertising and a series of stunts that kept it in the news.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick was a master at extending the lives of his productions
through big-name casting, too. He was one of the first producers to
use stars to replace stars. With ''Hello, Dolly!'', he had a
succession of famous Dollys follow Channing in the title role,
including Ginger Rogers, Martha Raye, Betty Grable, Pearl Bailey,
Phyllis Diller and Ethel Merman, who closed the show after a run of
2,844 performances.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s and 1960s, the producer reportedly grossed $20
million annually, earning $2 million a year from his hits. His
productions have won countless Tony Awards -- ''Hello, Dolly!''
alone picked up 10 Tonys in 1964 -- as well as other theater prizes
including the New York Drama Critics' Circle Award and London's
Olivier Award.
</P>
<P>
   His flops were well-known, too, particularly ''Breakfast at
Tiffany's,'' which never officially opened in New York despite the
potent box-office draw of Mary Tyler Moore and Richard Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick's private life was as stormy as his public one. He had
five wives and six marriages. He was married to wife No. 3, Etan,
twice.
Frank Rothman:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former MGM chairman Frank Rothman, considered
one of the nation's top sports and entertainment attorneys, died
Tuesday of complications following surgery. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman had handled lawsuits involving the National Football
League, the National Basketball Association and the Professional
Golfers Association. His entertainment industry clients included
Warner Bros., Walt Disney Co., Paramount Pictures, Home Box Office
and 20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman litigated a number of landmark cases, including one
involving basketball player Spencer Haywood that led to the
''hardship rule,'' which allows undergraduates to leave college
before four years and play in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   He also represented a number of teams, including the Boston
Celtics, the Seattle Supersonics, the Portland Trailblazers and the
Los Angeles Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Kerkorian, MGM's principal stockholder, asked Rothman in
1982 to take the company's top job. After four years as MGM
chairman and chief executive, Rothman decided to return to law.
Robert L. Zion:
</P>
<P>
   IMLAYSTOWN, N.J. (AP) -- Robert L. Zion, a landscape architect
who redesigned the grounds of the Statue of Liberty during its 1986
centennial, died Tuesday following an accident. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Zion was internationally known for his work that also included
Liberty State Park in Jersey City, Cincinnati's Riverfront Park and
the Sculpture Garden at the Museum of Modern Art in New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
