<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Fugitive Dies After Standoff  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- A fugitive in a bulletproof vest took his own life
during a standoff with police Wednesday after he shouted to his
mother that he knew he faced decades in prison, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Taylor had been sought by police since Sept. 2, when he and
his friend, murder suspect Jason Pierce, allegedly exchanged
gunfire with police near a mall in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, 21, had been sought for an Aug. 26 shooting in an
Atlanta suburb that injured his girlfriend and killed her two
roommates. The three women had recently moved from Boston to
Georgia to attend college.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce was injured in the Brookline gunfight and captured.
Police said Taylor fled on foot and escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Police received a tip that Taylor was at a home in the city's
Roxbury neighborhood about 3:15 p.m. They soon observed him through
a window in a third-floor apartment, said police spokesman Cliff
Connolly.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not fire any shots during the standoff, though Taylor
fired several times after officers and relatives pleaded with him
to surrender, police said. He fired again through the apartment
door as police tried to break it down, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Before officers got inside, he fired for a last time, shooting
himself in the head, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said he knows where he'll be for the next 25, 30 years,''
Connolly said. ''All of us basically came to the conclusion that he
was not going to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was taken to Boston Medical Center, where he died, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Three people who had been in the apartment left before the
shooting started, police said. The three could face charges of
harboring a fugitive, Connolly said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
