<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Christian Commune Leader Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON (AP) -- The leader of a Christian commune convicted of
charges linked to a series of sabotage attacks on oil and gas
installations in northwestern Alberta was sentenced Wednesday to 28
months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Wiebo Ludwig, a former evangelical preacher who moved his
extended family from Ontario to Alberta 13 years ago, was the chief
suspect of a police investigation into more than 160 incidents of
sabotage and vandalism since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig has railed against the fast-growing energy industry in
Alberta, blaming oil and gas projects that now encircle his farm
for killing livestock and causing three miscarriages among the
women in his commune.
</P>
<P>
   He was convicted on five of 14 counts, including a possession of
explosives charge from a 1998 explosion at an oil well.
</P>
<P>
   A second defendant, Richard Boonstra, 53, received a 21-day
sentence for his conviction on one mischief charge.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks, which ranged from minor vandalism to powerful
bombings of oil-well sites, caused no injuries but angered area
residents and prompted energy companies to implement anti-terrorism
programs. l
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
