<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Icebreaker Begins Arctic Voyage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- A U.S. ship built for traveling through ice-packed
polar waters has started a rare trip through Canada's disputed
Northwest Passage.
</P>
<P>
   The voyage by the U.S. Coast Guard ship Healy is the fourth by
an American-flagged vessel through the passage since Canada and the
United States signed an Arctic cooperation agreement in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, both countries pledged to work together to
help with the navigation of icebreakers and share research,
according to Foreign Affairs spokesman Reynald Doiron.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of who controls the icy link between the Arctic
and Atlantic Oceans has remained unresolved. The United States has
never recognized Canada's 1973 claim of the Northwest Passage as an
internal Canadian waterway.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian scientists on board the Healy plan to collect data on
polar ice and test scientific equipment and the new ship's
performance in Arctic conditions, Doiron said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the cooperation agreement, two U.S. ships sent without
permission -- the oil tanker Manhattan in 1969 and the icebreaker
Polar Sea in 1985 -- caused disputes between the neighboring
countries.left Halifax, Nova Scotia, on April 3 and was expected to
complete its journey in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 2249 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000426.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statements in Murder Case Admissible  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENTONVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- Statements that a man made to police
before he was arrested for the rape and murder of a 13-year-old boy
may be admitted as evidence in his trial, a judge ruled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Don Carpenter, 38, and his roommate, Joshua M. Brown, 22,
are accused of rape and capital murder in the Sept. 26 death of
13-year-old Jesse Dirkhising at their apartment in Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter is to be tried July 17. Brown will be tried
separately.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys argued Carpenter's constitutional rights were
violated when the Miranda warning that he could remain silent was
not read to him in the hours leading up to his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Judge David Clinger disagreed. He also ruled that Carpenter
voluntarily gave consent for police to search the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say the teen-ager was tied up and gagged and
repeatedly raped in the men's apartment.
</P>
</TEXT>
