<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton pledges no prez run in 2004; hopes Elian and father stay inU.S.  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton
pledged Wednesday that if elected she would not run for president
in four years and said she hoped their time in the United States
would eventually convince Juan Manuel Gonzalez to keep his son
Elian in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that this taste of freedom and the opportunity to be
with his son and to have this time perhaps would lead to that,''
the first lady said when asked about Cuban boy's case during a town
meeting broadcast nationwide by CNN from the University of Buffalo
before an audience of more than 350 people. ''But at the end of the
day this has to be the father's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also again defended the government's armed removal of
Elian from his Miami relatives, saying it was ''regrettable, but I
understand the necessity for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by CNN host Wolf Blitzer about her earlier pledge not to
run for president in four years, even if Republicans win the White
House this year, Clinton said: ''I am going to serve my six-year
term as senator. I owe it to the people of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also said that while she was a supporter of
abortion rights, she could support legislation backed by President
Clinton that would outlaw what critics call partial-birth abortion
except in cases where the woman's health or life was at stake. She
noted that congressional Republicans have refused to let that
legislation come up for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments came at the end of a long day on the campaign
trail in which she went from cow country to the college campus,
calling for tax changes to help keep family farms in the family and
accepting two offers to debate rival Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also said she had concerns about pursuing the
third party ballot line of the New York wing of the Reform Party
because of the possibility that she could be on a ticket headed by
conservative Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a very big difference with him on nearly every issue
you can imagine,'' Clinton told reporters after a speech to
Democrats in the Cattaraugus County community of Salamanca.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and the New York City mayor have both been
invited to a forum for Senate candidates Saturday in Buffalo by New
York's Independence Party. Giuliani has accepted while Clinton said
Wednesday that she is still ''working it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Independence Party is currently in the midst of a court
battle over its leadership with one faction supporting Buchanan and
the other adamantly opposed to his candidacy. Giuliani has also
spoken out repeatedly against Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
count votes received on third party ballot lines. That can make the
difference in close races.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady stopped in Salamanca on her way to Buffalo for
the televised town hall meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has attended 76 town hall meetings in New York
City as mayor, is scheduled for his own nationally televised
college forum next week at the Rochester Institute of Technology
when he appears on MSNBC's ''Hardball'' with Chris Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   In Salamanca, Clinton said she had accepted invitations for two
televised debates in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Juleanna Glover Weiss, a spokeswoman for Giuliani's campaign,
said the mayor had earlier accepted one of those debates and was in
discussions concerning the other. She said the mayor has made it
clear he wants debates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton wants to have it both ways and no way. She'd like
to debate, but apparently doesn't want the mayor there,'' Glover
Weiss said. ''We've offered to sit down to discuss mutually
feasible dates, but the Clinton campaign won't work with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, who had never lived in New York until she moved
to the state in January, said that her visit to Cattaraugus County
meant she has visited 56 of the state's 62 counties.
</P>
<P>
   ''By the end of tomorrow, I will have gone to 58 counties and
I'm trying to get to all 62'' before the Democratic state
convention on May 16, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's important that New York be represented in the
Senate by someone who will represent the entire state,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been making much of the fact that while she has been
crisscrossing the state for months, Giuliani has made only sporadic
forays outside the city, something that has drawn criticism for the
mayor even from his fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Starting her day in Letchworth state park beside the thundering
middle falls, Clinton seemed to press that point.
</P>
<P>
   ''You travel with me, you see New York,'' she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a stop at a dairy farm in Wyoming County, the first
lady called for increasing the estate tax exemption for family
farms and other family-owned businesses to $1.75 million, up from
the current $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''You ought to be able to leave your land and the bulk of your
fortunes to your children and not to the government,'' she told
more than 100 rural New Yorkers on hand for the event.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton got a warm reception at the farm and at the Democratic
luncheon in Salamanca.
</P>
<P>
   But not all Democrats on hand in Salamanca were impressed by
what they heard.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't like the Clinton administration,'' said Pete Whalen,
who said he had driven from Bradford, Pa., to see the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the 48-year-old dentist offered something of a
compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's hot,'' Whalen said. ''She must have been a real babe 15
years ago ... Make that 10 years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
