<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, April 26, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Columbine Shooting Video Released
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- Colorado authorities today made public video from last
year's Columbine High School massacre in which 14 students and one teacher were
slain. Some of the footage was set to a pop music soundtrack for the training of
police and fire personnel and showed the damaged cafeteria, bullet-riddled
classrooms and the library, where 10 students were killed. Jefferson County
District Attorney Frank Hutfless released the tapes to the victims' families
yesterday under a court order after a judge ruled that the relatives have an
''undeniable and compelling public interest'' in seeing the footage. Copies of
the video were made available for $25.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Father Seeks To Represent Son
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Juan Miguel Gonzalez's attorney today asked in an
emergency petition for the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to speak on behalf
of his 6-year-old son Elian ''...who has no other suitable representative.'' The
father asked the court to reject a bid by the boy's great-uncle and former
temporary guardian, Lazaro Gonzalez, to have his lawyers and doctors see the
Cuban refugee and speak for him before the court. The Justice Department also
opposed Lazaro's motion for a court-appointed guardian to examine and speak for
Elian.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Pledges New 'Tone' for D.C.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush, addressing Washington's Republican elite
at a record-breaking $21 million fund-raiser, promised tonight to reach across
party lines and end a ''cycle of bitterness, an arms race of anger'' that
stymies progress in the nation's capital. ''I will set a different tone in
Washington, D.C. I will restore civility and respect to our national politics,''
he said in a keynote speech. The crowd of 1,500 fell silent when Bush said both
parties are to blame for partisan mudslinging and gave him his loudest applause
when he promised to ''respond aggressively'' when attacked by Democratic rival
Al Gore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pets.com Socks It to 'Late Night'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Online pet supply store Pets.com says the friendly
reputation of its kitschy ''spokespuppet'' has been defamed by a foul-mouthed
dog puppet featured on NBC's ''Late Night With Conan O'Brien.'' In a federal
lawsuit filed last week, Pets.com accuses ''Late Night'' writer Robert Smigel,
creator of the show's ''Triumph the Insult Comic Dog,'' of defaming the
ubiquitous sock puppet. Marc Liepis, a spokesman for ''Late Night,'' said
neither the show nor Smigel would comment on the lawsuit. But, he noted that the
cigar-smoking Triumph made his debut long before the arrival of the sock puppet.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Flood-Ravaged Mozambique Still Needy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Images of Mozambicans clinging to trees
above swirling floodwaters are already a fading memory, but their country now
faces a critical phase in its recovery, a top U.N. official said Wednesday. The
flood victims who were plucked to safety by helicopters have been returning to
their homes -- or what's left of them -- and need roads, bridges, schools and
hospitals rebuilt, said Mark Malloch Brown, head of the United Nations
Development Program. Torrential rains from two cyclones swept away the homes or
livelihoods of 10 percent of Mozambique's 19 million people last February.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ukraine Marks Chernobyl Anniversary
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- Ukrainians on Wednesday marked the Chernobyl nuclear
disaster with a degree of openness that contrasted sharply with the secrecy that
once surrounded it. The reactor explosion and fire at the Chernobyl nuclear
power plant April 26, 1986 was the world's worst nuclear accident. Soviet
authorities tried to keep the disaster a secret but the aftereffects are grimly
visible: an estimated 4,000 deaths among those who took part in the hasty and
poorly organized cleanup and 70,000 people disabled by radiation, according to
government figures.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Lower
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped early Thursday following a retreat on Wall
Street. The benchmark Nikkei Stock Average shed 46.86 points to 18,087.45 in the
early trading. On the stock market, Tokyo players remained cautious about
prospects for the U.S. stock market. In New York, the Dow Jones industrial
average fell 179.32 points to 10,945.50 at Wednesday's close. The Nasdaq
composite index closed at 3,630.09 points, down 81.14.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reds Demolish Mets 12-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Cincinnati Reds' Denny Neagle allowed two hits in seven
scoreless innings to snap the New York Mets' nine-game winning streak with a
12-1 victory tonight. Dmitri Young went 4-for-5 with a homer and five RBIs, and
Ed Taubensee added three hits, a home run and three RBIs for Cincinnati, which
ended its longest losing streak since September 1998 and the Mets' longest
winning stretch since May 1998. But the story for the Reds was the performance
by Neagle (2-0), who had no trouble pitching on a rainy, 43-degree night.
</P>
