<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Humanitarian Plight Alarms UN  </HEADLINE>
By CASIMIRO SIONA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUANDA, Angola (AP) -- Families driven from their homes by
Angola's civil war are eating worms and grass to survive, the
United Nations said Wednesday in a report that called the
humanitarian situation in the country alarming.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued by the U.N. humanitarian office in Luanda,
said aid shipments must quickly be increased and thousands of
displaced people must be moved out of badly run temporary shelters
where sanitary conditions are terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is important for the international community and the
government of Angola to react promptly if we are to avert the
current crisis from becoming a major humanitarian tragedy,''
Carolyn McAskie, deputy U.N. emergency relief coordinator, said in
statement released in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The report said some displaced people are being harassed by
government soldiers. Recent news reports have claimed soldiers are
stealing food aid from displaced people.
</P>
<P>
   The government estimates the fighting has uprooted some 3.8
million people -- about one-third of the southwest African country's
population. Many of them are living in makeshift camps and almost
all rely on aid to survive.
</P>
<P>
   At increased risk are children, widows, and the handicapped.
''These groups are on the edge of an abyss,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Angola is fertile, but skirmishes between the army and
the UNITA rebels have forced civilians to flee to the major
government-held cities. Meanwhile, roads made dangerous by land
mines and ambushes have forced aid groups to distribute aid by air,
bringing a steep hike in the cost of operations.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations this year is asking donors for an estimated
$258 million for Angola, more than double last year's $110 million.
</P>
<P>
   Angola's civil war reignited in December 1998 after four years
of jittery peace under a U.N.-brokered peace accord. UNITA has said
it is prepared to negotiate a new peace deal. However, the
government has ruled out fresh talks, saying the rebels cannot be
trusted.
</P>
<P>
   Two previous peace deals also collapsed, the first one in 1992
when UNITA rejected its defeat in the country's first democratic
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The government and UNITA, a Portuguese acronym for the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, began fighting after
the Southwest African country gained independence from Portugal in
1975.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-26-00 2301 </TRAILER>
