<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-26 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks slipped Thursday morning following a
retreat on Wall Street. The dollar was higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 8.18 points,
or 0.05 percent, to 18,126.13 at the end of the morning session. On
Wednesday, the average closed down 138.02 points, or 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 106.27 yen, up 0.39 yen from late Wednesday in
Tokyo and unchanged from its late New York level.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, Tokyo players remained cautious about
prospects for the U.S. stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors can't move before seeing U.S. data later Thursday,''
said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager at Tokyo Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government was to release data on that nation's
employment costs and gross domestic product for the first quarter
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 179.32 points
to 10,945.50 at Wednesday's close. The Nasdaq composite index
closed at 3,630.09 points, down 81.14.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 11.02 points, or 0.66 percent, to 1,656.87.
The TOPIX closed up 2.61 points, or 0.16 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, traders said some foreign investors bid up
the greenback against the yen in an attempt to cover losses in U.S.
stocks by selling Japanese shares.
</P>
<P>
   But trading was moderate ahead of the release of major economic
data in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 97.96 yen, up from
97.60 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.7400 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.7350 percent. Its
price fell 0.04 point to 100.51.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Tokyo Stock Exchange: http://www.tse.or.jp./
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
